<HEADLINE>Division in ranks of the full-time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES TRAYNOR reports on a scramble among first gang of ten.
THE pre-occupation with the plight of Aberdeen, who continue to dangle
precariously over the premier-division trapdoor, has caused the real
danger to be overlooked.
Hardly a thought has been spared for the clubs scrambling to end their
exiles in a first division which will exact a heavy toll on ambition
before sanity prevails, if indeed it ever does.
Last year, the Scottish League was committed to four divisions, each
of 10 teams, and clubs pledged to preserve that structure for at least
five seasons. But if their word truly is their bond -- and that would be
a departure in a business in which deceit often abounds -- the Scottish
game could fall into disrepair.
Indeed, a growing number of managers believe the plight of some clubs
could become desperate, and some directors are beginning to ask if
gearing up for the top league is worth the risks and the costs.
In most cases, the strain of remaining full-time in the hope of
winning a place in the premier division either by finishing first or
through succeeding in a play-off with the second-bottom club in the top
league will mean reverting to part-time.
The financial implications of failure to promote themselves in every
sense will be severe. It's simple arithmetic and straightforward logic.
Some chairmen tried to alert others to the inherent dangers in opting
for four divisions of 10, but too few listened. Too many had been
spooked by the threat of a breakaway league -- remember the push by the
bigger clubs to form a Super League? -- and not enough directors were
thinking straight when called to decide the way ahead.
Now, they must live with real fear, and their anxiety should be
widespread because the standard of football, which is already dreadfully
low, will fall in conjunction with any reduction in the number of
full-time clubs. ''There have already been cut-backs and we are still in
the first season of five with four divisions of 10 clubs in each,'' said
Airdire's chairman, George Peat.
''This is a matter which should be of genuine and serious concern for
everyone. I just can't see all of the full-time clubs in the first
division remaining so without premier-division football at some point in
the near future.
''My own club could survive perhaps for two more years, but after
that, it is doubtful if we could remain full-time without the premier
division.''
Peat warned before the current structure was voted into being that it
would have an adverse effect on club finances, and he was particularly
disappointed he didn't win support of other outfits of similar standing.
Currently, there are 16 full-time clubs, although the likes of
Hamilton and St Mirren have a mixture of full and part-time players.
''If I hadn't argued for the need to have a play-off so that two first
division clubs would have the chance of promotion, then we wouldn't even
have been given that facility.
''I was also disappointed that the Scottish Professional Footballers'
Association did not become involved,'' Peat said. ''Surely having as
many full-time clubs as possible was in their interests also.''
Airdrie, of course, hope to be moving into a new 10,000 all-seater
stadium in a year, but they could find themselves in the same position
as St Johnstone, who have a modern ground which would enhance the
premier division, but unfortunately for them, they can't get membership.
The McDiarmid Park club have fallen 10 points behind leaders
Dunfermline, Dundee, and Raith Rovers, and appear unlikely to catch up
in the time left. The Perth club need to be in the premier division
where the real money is to be found.
Dunfermline almost escaped at the end of last season, but Falkirk
edged them out by one point on the last day of the season. Manager Bert
Paton was left stunned and couldn't believe another season in purgatory
beckoned, although his side's win against Stranraer the other night
enhanced the Fifers' chances of getting out.
The East End Park side are in an almost impossible situation because
they need to upgrade their facilities, which, frankly, are abysmal, and
they must always be trying to improve the quality of their team.
Debts can mount very quickly in the first division, as even the most
frugal of clubs have found in the past. Ambition does not come cheap as
Raith Rovers' chairman Alex Penman has discovered.
''I have put quite a lot of money into my club to fund a full time
set-up for two years,'' he said, ''and we are in the first year of that
programme.
''Of course, our success in the Coca Cola Cup has helped to the extent
that we might be able to stretch our commitment to three years, but we
really must get into the top division.
''I'd rather see my team fighting to get into a premier division of 16
clubs because that would give us a better chance of staying up, but as
things stand at the moment, I see little real merit in struggling for
promotion only to be faced with the prospect of falling back down again
almost immediately.''
The Stark's Park chairman knows also that promotion might help him
hold on a little longer to his manager, Jimmy Nicholl, who has been
making a name for himself, and will be enticed away sooner or later.
''There is little point in continuing like this,'' Penman added.
Dundee, who have been leading the way for most of the season so far,
face similar fears, and their manager, Jim Duffy, also said that selling
the best talent always has to be an option.
''Clubs might have to do that just to remain full-time in the first
division,'' added Duffy, who is hardly new to the pressures of promotion
and relegation.
''I've been there,'' he said. ''I missed out on the last day when I
was with Falkirk, and I won promotion on the last day when I was with
Partick Thistle, but the supporters and directors feel it more than
players. As for the manager, he knows he has a short span if there is no
success.
''A manager rarely gets three years unless he can show there has been
considerable improvement.
''There is a risk even for the bigger teams as you can see if you look
at Aberdeen. I believe that if the premier division had more teams, then
Willie Miller would have been able to make his changes and he would
still have been in a job today. But the premier division allows hardly
any room for error.
''A larger top division would help keep more clubs full-time, and that
would be preferable to what we have just now. It is up to the people in
charge of the big clubs to make the changes needed.''
All involved in the struggle to reach the premier division door agree
a larger top division would reduce the fear of failure and provide
greater opportunity for younger players to be introduced, and in reply
to those who say there would too many meaningless matches in a 16-team
top flight, they say that the premier division is already a split
competition.
''Look how far in front Rangers are at the moment,'' Duffy said.
</TEXT>
