<HEADLINE>Officials as dangerous as the thugs themselves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR, CHIEF SPORTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE authorities continued yesterday to talk of deranged minorities,
and as the hours passed lending greater distance to the violence visited
upon a wonderfully accommodating Irish city, football's administrators
were recovering their composure and trotting out promises based on
nothing other than their own remarkable arrogance. Those people who at
this stage say the European Championship finals can be conducted safely
are as dangerous as the Englishmen who tore up parts of a Lansdowne Road
stand.
They could be encouraging foreign visitors, including Scots, to put
themselves at risk because the only certainty as football stands head
bowed in shame before the outside world is that the primeval people who
prevented a friendly international match between the Republic of Ireland
and England from being played in Dublin will strike again.
In most cases these thugs are driven by a hatred of someone else's
beliefs, the colour of their skin, or the sound of their language. Their
violence is not born on the terracings of football's grounds, rather
they have attached themselves to a sport which is universal.
''Anarchists are at work,'' Jim Farry of the SFA said. He is correct.
It is irresponsible of the FA's chief executive Graham Kelly to say
England should not be denied the championship finals, which are
scheduled for the summer of next year, and it is more utterly
preposterous than usual for FIFA's Joao Havelange to splutter his
platitudes about local difficulties. They may be that to someone who has
never had to cower from bricks and pieces of wood or protect a
frightened child, but to those closer to reality Dublin raises genuine
concerns.
The game's bureaucrats should not be allowed to tell supporters it
will be safe to attend matches during the finals and they must be
prevented from offering UEFA, a self-perpetuating body willing to
off-load responsibilities, assurances that all will be well.
For God's sake, how can the FA, who have an ancient president, Bert
Millichip, who spoke in defence of Eric Cantona, tell anyone that what
happened in Lansdowne Road couldn't happen in Leeds, Manchester,
Newcastle, Nottingham, Liverpool, Birmingham or London next summer?
It will be possible to segregate supporters in the English grounds
which will host matches, but it won't be so easy to keep them apart
outside or in the city centres. ''Ah, not our problem,'' football would
insist while pointing in the direction of the police authorities, and
for once football would be doing the right thing.
The only people who can provide a lead or say whether or not it is
safe to stage the European finals in England are the constabulary.
Unless the police decide they can cope and offer protection to genuine
fans and the citizens of the half dozen venues, the finals should not go
ahead. The FA and UEFA are concerned only with their image and loss of
revenue.
If there are any doubts at all, the finals should be moved.
No doubt the FA took comfort from the words of Detective Chief
Inspector Bryan Drew, who heads up the Football Intelligence Unit, when
he said yesterday that England is better placed than most other
countries to stage the tournament. He should try telling that to the
people who suffered at Stamford Bridge last week.
The resourcefulnes of the thugs should not be underestimated. They are
organised and plan months in advance. It would be an extremely foolish
policeman or a member of the FA who would believe these hooligans are
not planning some kind of demonstration during the finals.
Also, there will be fans of a similar bent in England on the backs of
their own national sides. The Dutch have their hooligans and so, too, do
the Germans, Italians, and Spaniards.
Then, of course, the Scots could be there also and although our people
have been remarkably well behaved over the last decade, complacency
would could be costly.
There is always the feeling that if the Scottish fans blow, it will be
spectacular.
Kelly may insist a minority of thugs shall not win the argument, but
football has to ask if it is all worth the risk?
</TEXT>
