<HEADLINE>English security has Walker on a full alert.  The two faces that sum up English football</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER SFA secretary Ernie Walker will inspect England's European
venues next week in the aftermath of the Dublin riots, and the
highly-respected legislator will have a major say in the security which
will surround the European Championship in l996.
And on top of that, the FA have been surprised by the amount of
sympathy they have received from the Continent.
Walker is chairman of UEFA's Stadia Committee, and in that role he
also carries responsibility for crowd troubles. It is an important
position, made more so after the Dublin troubles, and the influential
Scot has the ear of UEFA President Lennart Johansson.
The all-powerful Dane believes that fences may have to be built at the
English venues.
Last night he said: ''We will be meeting next week to discuss the
whole affair. Reports will come from the Irish FA, the FA and other
observers. Then we will come to a decision. Security has to be correct.
That is paramount, and if fences have to be built at the grounds, then
that will happen. It is one of the options we will consider.''
Yesterday, Walker maintained: ''It would be absurd if these people who
caused the trouble in Dublin are allowed to dictate our lives.
''It would be wrong to allow the organised hooligans to change the
venue of the European Championship. I do believe that the trouble in
Dublin was organised, and I also believe that the people involved are
not football supporters. I will be visiting the various grounds in
England next week to check that all of them are up to UEFA standards,
and part of my brief is to look at security.
''I do not see UEFA changing the venue of the championships. These
people looked on Dublin as a soft target, and that will not, and cannot
be the case in England in l996.''
England has been given worldwide approval to defy the thugs and stage
the championships. Prime Minister John Major, and Joao Havalange,
president of football's world governing body, FIFA, united yesterday to
back the FA's message of not surrendering to the hooligans.
FIFA chief Havalange said: ''England does not deserve, because of a
local problem, to have a sporting right withdrawn.''
UEFA, however, will not rubber-stamp England's continuance as 1996
hosts until it has received and scrutinised reports on the riot from the
FA and Football Association of Ireland's joint inquiry.
But president Lennart Johannsen and general secretary Gerhard Aigner
have both indicated their sympathy. Chief executive Graham Kelly said:
''We are very heartened by the support we have received right across the
board.''
Meanwhile, Ernie Walker's views will be accepted when UEFA meet next
week. The former SFA supremo said: ''There will be no hysterical
reaction. We won't give in to these people.''
And at Park Gardens, SFA Chief Executive Jim Farry added: ''We want
England to play at the new Hampden in l997. The invitation has gone out,
it has been accepted, and it remains in place.
''We will welcome the footballers of England just as we would hope our
own players would be welcomed in the south.''
The English last night called on genuine supporters to turn in the
thugs and help them to save the 1996 European Championships.
The FA, still reeling from the Dublin riot and abandonment of
England's friendly against the Republic, have set up a free hotline --
0800 515495 -- to help to identify the troublemakers.
FA officials have remained in Dublin to pursue the joint inquiry which
is hoped to reach initial conclusions next week. ''It's urgent that we
know what happened and why it happened,'' said David Davies, the FA,'s
director of public affairs.
Glen Kirton, director of Euro 96, pledged that no-one identified or
convicted as a troublemaker will be able to purchase tickets for the
finals.
He added: ''What happened will add to the store of knowledge we and
the police already have of the way this tiny minority operate. What it
is not going to do is change the overall structure of what we do.''
But first comes the inquiry into how a small core of suspected
politically-motivated thugs infiltrated the England Travel Club Section.
Davies revealed that the FA had sent back around 800 of the 2500
tickets it received from the Irish.
The FA also faces some heartsearching over next October's friendly
against Norway in Oslo, their next senior away game, and -- ironically
-- an under-21 UEFA Championship qualifier against the Republic in Cork
next month.
And the FA are naturally worried about the resumption of European club
competitions, with Arsenal due in France and Chelsea in Belgium.
Graham Kelly added: ''We will be talking to the clubs, but we have had
a very successful record since we went back into Europe and we want to
retain that.''
</TEXT>
