<HEADLINE>Drew's driving ambition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DREW Docherty will tonight take his newly-found confidence into the
ring at The Tryst in Cumbernauld, and the likeable young man from the
village of Condorrat is convinced he can take the World Boxing
Organisation bantamweight championship from Alfred ''The Cobra'' Kotey.
Docherty freely admits that, despite having an abundance of talent, he
was never the most confident of boxers, but all that has changed since
he won outright ownership of a Lonsdale Belt after successfully
defending his British title against Ady Benton last November.
The Scot is still the most modest of men, but he no longer
underestimates his own capabilities. ''Kotey has lost only once and that
says a lot,'' said Docherty. ''However, you could say the same about me.
''The only time I have lost as a pro was when challenging Vincenzo
Belcastro for the European title. I didn't get the decison that night,
but I know what went wrong -- I used the wrong tactics.
''That was the lowest point in my career and I certainly don't want my
family to have to go through anything similar tomorrow night.''
So how come the new confidence from a man who would rather keep in the
background but realises his responsibility to cooperate fully with the
media? ''When I signed up with Tommy Gilmour, he promised me title
fights and said the rest would be up to me,'' said Docherty.
''He was as good as his word, and when I won the British title by
beating Joe Kelly and was presented with the Lonsdale Belt, I wanted
nothing more than to win it outright. It became a burning ambition.
''I then successfully defended against Donnie Hood, and after that
came the big one against Ady Benton. Now, no matter what happens, I have
that belt as tangible proof that I achieved something worthwhile.
''Mind you, my burning ambition now is to become world champion, and
that means beating Kotey.''
Ghanaian Kotey, who took up the sport at the age of seven -- when a
boxing coach watched him get involved in a punch-up during a football
match -- won the title in London last July by beating Puerto Rico's
Rafael del Valle and has made one successful defence against Armando
Castro.Both were points victories.
It should be a fight for the purists. Both are excellent boxers who
are in top condition -- Docherty was bang on the championship limit of
8st 6lb at last night's weigh-in while Kotey scaled 8st 5lb 4oz -- and I
think the judges will be called on at the end of 12 rounds.
One of the judges is Jean Williams, from Atlantic City in New Jersey,
who will make a little bit of history by becoming the first woman to
officiate at a boxing match in Scotland.
On the undercard, Tranent super-middleweight Willie Quinn should
extend his winning run when he meets Martin Jolly, of Alfreton, while
Cumbernauld's Alan Peacock should give the locals a win when he meets
Hartlepool light-welter Kevin McKenzie.
There will be a lot of interest in Nigerian heavyweight Richard Bango.
The 6ft 5in boxer, who won a silver medal at the Barcelona Olympics,
goes in against Denis Bailey, of Liverpool. Other bouts:
Bantam -- Spencer Oliver (London) v Des Gargano (Manchester). Feather
-- Dean Pithy (Coventry) v Kid McAuley (Doncaster). Super-feather --
Hugh Collins (Stirling) v Paul Wynn (Newcastle).
</TEXT>
