<HEADLINE>Higgins is on a high</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Higgins took just 75 minutes to beat Ken Doherty
5-0 in the third round of the Sweater Shop Open at Bournemouth
yesterday.
And then Mark Johnston-Allen beat new Benson &amp; Hedges Masters champion
Ronnie O'Sullivan 5-2 just 48 hours after his shock 5-4 victory over
world champion Stephen Hendry.
The former public schoolboy from Bristol now goes for a hat trick
today against Jimmy White in the quarter-finals of the #325,000 event.
Scot Higgins produced a fine display of potting, starting with two
century breaks, as he inflicted on world No.7 Doherty the heaviest
defeat of his professional career.
Higgins, beaten by O'Sullivan in the final of the Benson and Hedges
Masters at Wembley, said: ''That's the best I've played against a top
player. I'm on a high and feel as if all the luck is going my way.''
The 19-year-old from Wishaw started with a break of 106 in 10 minutes
and followed-up with a 101 in the second frame.
Doherty, 25, said: 0''It's the first time I've been whitewashed in a
ranking tournament, but there was nothing I could do about it.''
Higgins now faces fellow-Scot Euan Henderson, the world No.119 from
Glenrothes, who continued his giant-killing run when he beat 1979 world
champion Terry Griffiths 5-2 to qualify for the quarter-finals of a
major tournament for the first time.
Henderson knocked out another former world champion, Dennis Taylor,
after having beaten world No.3 James Wattana in the first round. He is
now guaranteed at least #9050.
Steve Davis beat Peter Ebdon for the second time in 19 days -- then
tipped him as a future world champion. Davis, six times world and UK
title winner, won 5-2.
Ebdon was shattered by his seventh defeat against Davis in their nine
matches, but he will have been lifted by Davis's words. ''He has the
qualities and heart to win the world title,'' said the 37-year-old.
Davis now meets Nuneaton's Mick Price for the first time in the last
eight. After having notched his third successive
5-1 victory against Welsh left-hander Darren Morgan, Price, 27, said:
''It's a dream draw.''
John Parrott, holder of the title, eased into the quarter-finals by
beating Canadian Alain Robidoux 5-2, and now meets Glasgow's Alan
McManus for a place in the last four.
McManus, the world No.6, also enjoyed an easy passage, beating
Grimsby's Mike Hallett 5-1.
</TEXT>
