<HEADLINE>Indoor season closed for Gunnell</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S record-breaking sprinter, Melanie Neef, seems fated in her
attempt to find opposition which will fully test her burgeoning 400
metres talents.
Denied a race against Olympic, World, European, and Commonwealth 400m
hurdles champion Sally Gunnell last weekend, when Britain met France in
Glasgow, Neef is now to miss Gunnell's challenge for the second time.
Gunnell has pulled out of the KP invitation meeting in Birmingham a
week tomorrow, because a heel injury is taking longer to clear than she
anticipated, and she will not contest any event during the indoor
season.
Neef says a calf muscle strain is making progress and she is confident
of being fit to face a world-class field which will include Jamaican
Sandie Richards, Commonwealth bronze medallist ahead of her in Victoria.
Brian Whittle won a 400m international race in Moscow on Tuesday with
47.29. His victims included Dmitriy Golovastov, the Russian who blocked,
then beat him, in Glasgow.
* JOHN Regis's time of 20.46sec indoors in Stuttgart a week past
Sunday will not after all be recognised as a UK 200m record, because the
race had just one other person in it.
Under international and UK rules, a minimum of three competitors are
required before a record can be ratified. The race was a heat, from
which a third runner withdrew -- a similar situation to that which cost
Mel Neef a Scottish record at the Kelvin Hall last month. Neef was
fortunate enough to break the record again in the final.
* SELECTION for the World outdoor championships, in Gothenburg in
August, will be guaranteed to all winners of AAA championship titles,
provided they have achieved the required standard. The selectors will
choose up to two more per event.
*THREE Scottish age-group record breakers -- sprinters Allan McBride
and Kris Stewart, and high jumper Scott Kenny -- are included in the
Scottish Schools TSB-backed team for the under-16 international in
Birmingham a week on Sunday. Team (women in italics):
60m hurdles: G Stewart (Tynecastle HS), C Low (Carnoustie HS). 60m: K
Scott (Douglas Ewart HS), A McBride (Notre Dame, Greenock). 200m: P
Thomson (St George's), McBride. 300/400m: L Philp (Webster's HS), K
Stewart (Berwickshire HS). 800m: K Montador (Alloa Acad.), J Hand (St
Thomas of Aquins). 1500m: J Ross (Boclair Acad.), C Menelaws (Uddingston
GS). High jump: G Black (Castlehead HS), S Kenny (King's Park Sec.).
Long jump: L Whigham (Lenzie Acad.), N Ritchie (Morgan Acad). Shot: I
Swan (Selkirk HS), G Allan (Milne's HS). Triple jump: R McDonald (Perth
HS). Pole vault: C Rule (Edinburgh Acad.) 4 x 200m from: L Callan (St
Patrick's HS), Scott, Thomson, Whigham, Black, Stewart. Chris Carson (St
Columba's HS), Dunfermline, McBride, Stewart, McDonald, Ritchie.
</TEXT>
