<HEADLINE>Bouncing back to the big time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT needs a big story to deprive Ron Atkinson of the back page lead in
English newspapers, but even he had to give way to the disgraceful
nonsense in Dublin. Otherwise, this remarkable example of survival in
the toughest business of all, football management, would have held
princely court as per habit.
His appointment by Coventry City is the ninth time the man with an
all-year tan, heavyweight jewellery, and the immense self-confidence has
been appointed manager of a club.
That in itself is a testament to his ability to convince the world
that he succeeds even when he apparently fails. This is a special
talent, a gift that is at the core of all survivors in most businesses.
The bearing is much to do with it. Atkinson never actually looks like a
man who has got it wrong, even when he has. This is known as the
chameleon factor.
Just when you think he has gone and done it this time, he pops up
wearing a different shirt, fresh smile, and that self-assured attitude
which instantly erases the lurking thought that, if this is his ninth
attempt, is it not time he got it right?
Yet it would be unfair to apply that kind of rationale to the
impossible challenge of football management. Sometimes, they manage to
get it right and wrong at the same club. Billy McNeill was a conquering
hero when he returned to Celtic and won the double in 1988. When he was
dismissed four years later many of his former admirers believed he had
lost his touch.
Howard Kendall could not seem to do anything right at Everton for
years and then his painstaking planning finally came good, and the club
was off winning the league and the cup.
Alex Ferguson, Atkinson's successor at Old Trafford, was pilloried
mercilessly in the early years with Manchester United, before he sent
the critics scurrying into the trees.
The truth probably is that most of the survivors in the management
game are good at what they do, but are faced by so many unforeseeable
factors in football that it can often be beyond any man's capabilities
to influence its course.
Which is why, by his very presence, Atkinson proves he is good at it.
One of the multitude of diverse talents the job requires is the ability
to stay the trip. Endurance under all kinds of external and internal
pressure is imperative, and many of those who have fallen by the wayside
and re-entered civilisation were not equipped with the kind of
resilience which can withstand abuse of the most vitriolic kind.
''Atko'' has done it again. He deserves congratulations and maybe he
will fulfil the promise that he has managed at other clubs, win a trophy
for Coventry.
The former manager of Manchester United, Aston Villa, and others has
proved once again that, in fooball as in life, last week's losers are
next week's winners.
* NOT that it happens very often but I have made ita policy not to
accept invitaions to play in pro-am golf tournaments. This is not
because of a terror of embarrassing my partners to the point of making
their excuses and leaving - which could happen - but because of an
in-built fear that I might cause serious injury somewhere ariund the
course. Let me point out that when it comes to straight driving I am
better than the next man but when you stand on a tee confronted by a few
celebrity spotters baffled b y a) your presence and b) your swing it can
be extremely intimidating. The normally slow, precise and beautiful
movements can be transformed into something akin to a break dancer on
crack and the ball, if hit at all, can go anywhere.
Which is why I have some sympathy with the ex-president of the US,
whose wayward fairway wood cannoned off a tree and hit a spectator on
the head at Palm Springs this week.(''I look up and see smiling faces
and I wonder how I am going to miss them.'') BUsh is reputedly not bad
at the game, unlike one of his partners this week, another former
president, Gerald Ford, who in his hey day, it was said, could hit
anything bar the fairway from twenty yards.
</TEXT>
