<HEADLINE>McStay in contract talks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC manager Tommy Burns revealed yesterday that he has started
contract negotiations with five of his first-team squad -- club captain
Paul McStay, Tony Mowbray, Brian O'Neil, Charlie Nicholas and Jim
Slavin.
All are out of contract in the summer, and Burns said: ''I have
started talks with all of the players and we are relaxed about the
situation, although we don't want any long, drawn out negotiations.''
Burns may be relaxed about the re-signing situation, but he admits to
certain worries over tomorrow's Scottish Cup clash with Meadowbank
Thistle.
''We have had them watched and they will make us work hard,'' said
Burns. ''They will be well organised and it is a game we have to take
very seriously.''
The Celtic manager would not say whether McStay will return after
having been axed from the side which drew with Hibs last weekend. All he
would say was: ''We will be looking at the team selection, but nothing
has been decided. We do have a couple of knocks and also two players who
are suspended.'' The players who are out because of suspension are Tom
Boyd and young centre half Jim Slavin.
Celtic, of course, are looking at the Scottish Cup as the most likely
entry to European football next season, and Dutch striker Pierre van
Hooydonk agrees with that.
''I want to win something here in Scotland and the cup, because of the
number of games involved, is possibly the easiest trophy to win in
Scotland,'' insisted van Hooydonk. ''It is certainly my target.
''It will not be as easy as many people think to win on Saturday, but
we have to do it, and hopefully we will be scoring more goals than
normal. The supporters will want that -- and we have to give them what
they want.''
* ARBROATH have moved quickly to sign former Aberdeen player Ian
Porteous, who scored twice for them as a trialist in Wednesday night's
3-1 win over Queen's Park.
Manager John Brogan revealed that it was one of his former players at
Stirling Albion, Willie Watters, who had alerted him that Elgin City had
freed Porteous. ''Willie is a friend of Ian's and he tipped us off.''
</TEXT>
