<HEADLINE>Bush wins Hoch's vote</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''WHO played the best of the three presidents?'' Scott Hoch was asked
after the holder had partnered Bill Clinton (11-handicap), and George
Bush and Gerald Ford (both 18), in the opening round of the five-day Bob
Hope Chrysler classic at Indian Wells.
''I think it would have to be Mr Bush, although Mr Clinton hit some
good drives and Mr Ford holed a 30-footer for par on the ninth green,''
said the little North Carolinian who failed to hole a two-and-a-half
footer to win the 1989 US Masters and then lost the play-off to Nick
Faldo.
The presidents improved Hoch's 70 by eight strokes for their
better-ball -- 10 behind the top team -- with Bush's card at 92,
Clinton's 94, and Ford's 102. One hundred US Marines were on duty plus
about 40 secret servicemen.
Four spectators were hit by their balls, the worst injured being
71-year-old Nancy Earley who was hit on the forehead when Bush's ball
ricocheted off a tree at the first.
She needed 10 stitches in the wound, but said: ''I told theformer
president I was sorry I had got in the way of his shot.''
Kenny Perry, 34, of Kentucky, led with 63 on his first round at Indian
Ridge.
</TEXT>
