<HEADLINE>Euro rules rescue Els</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISTER NICOL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ERNIE Els twice claimed line-of-sight relief en route to his US Open
success at Oakmont last June, when he defeated Colin Montgomerie and
Loren Roberts in a play-off.
The talented Springbok used his knowledge of the rule book to claim
relief from a huge TV tower and was able to escape with impunity and go
on to record a memorable success.
Back home in Johannesburg yesterday he again kept his cool in the 90
degree heat when, playing his last hole of the first round of the
Lexington South African PGA Championship, he hooked his approach shot
behind a sponsor's scoreboard. And that's when real trouble could have
overtaken him.
This week's event is the first to be co-sponsored by the PGA European
Tour and the South African PGA, and it is standard procedure on the Euro
Tour when a ball finishes behind a similar obstruction to claim a free
drop. But below the equator they do things differently.
South African professionals first have to play the ball as it lies --
and only then, if they hit the obstruction, are they entitled to claim
relief, without penalty.
But Ernie had done his homework and played the game according to the
European rules, not those of his native country. Had he not done so, he
might well have found himself disqualified, according to tournament
director Andy McFee.
''This problem highlights the debates which have been on-going between
the European Tour and other governing bodies round the world,'' said
McFee. ''Our belief is that a player should know exactly what to do
whether he is in Arizona, Yorkshire, South Africa, or the Northern
Territories of Australia. They should all be playing under the same
rules.''
McFee added he had sent warning letters to all 70-plus of the European
contingent playing this week as well as posting the rule change on every
player's locker door.
Els eventually escaped with a birdie 3 and his 65 put him three behind
Wayne Westner, who shot six birdies and an eagle. His 62 was one short
of Fulton Allem's three-year-old course record, but 10 strokes better
than Dean Robertson's opener yesterday.
Leading British player is young Englishman Van Phillips with 66, eight
better than Scottish champion Andrew Coltart.
Old-timer Bill Longmuir had planned to hang a Gone Fishin' sign on the
door of his Nairobi holiday home this week, but responded to a late call
to Johannesburg with a 72.
