<HEADLINE>Eagle lands for Armour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOMMY Armour III, the broad-shouldered 35-year-old grandson of the
celebrated Silver Scot who won the US Open at Oakmont in 1927, scored a
67 in sweltering sunshine at Bermuda Dunes to take the early lead on an
11-under-par 133 in the second round of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic
yesterday at Indian Wells.
Out on the course, a little-known Tennessee pro Harry Taylor, 40, was
out in 31 at Indian Ridge and was back in 33 for a 64 to lead by three.
But for a moment it was glory for Armour, who has had a chequered
career since winning his only tournament, the Phoenix Open in 1990.
Armour finished a lowly 147th on the money list last season, but
gained entry into this tournament by finishing seventh on the Nike Tour.
He left it to his second nine to make his charge into the lead and
gained it with a wonderful eagle 3 at the 540-yard seventeenth with a
big drive, a No.3 wood and a 20-foot putt. He had a long wait to see if
the little known Taylor could beat him by a stroke or two. Leading
scores:
