<HEADLINE>CBI still positive on economy.  Davies urges truce on single currency</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE CONFEDERATION of British Industry continues to take a positive
view of the outlook for the UK economy and said a further interest rate
rise does not look justified in anti-inflation terms. It said a Cabinet
ceasefire on the single currency would be a better response to market
uncertainty.
Speaking at the Guildhall in London yesterday, director-general Howard
Davies said that despite rising headline inflation, and softening of
retail demand, the recovery remains soundly based.
''The financial markets have clearly been unsettled by this week's
economic news, and perhaps by political uncertainty too, but there is no
cause for alarm,'' said Mr Davies.
He added: ''We had expected that growth in 1995 would not match the
pace of 1994. The second phase of tax increases is bound to have an
effect, as is the rise in interest rates we have seen so far. The
expectations are built into the CBI forecast of around 3% growth this
year.''
On inflation, Mr Davies said that ''while there are undoubtedly
continued pressures in industry, driven largely by rises in raw material
prices, we do not expect inflation to move out of the 1% to 4% band. The
most recent figures show that the rate of increase in raw material
prices is reducing in most areas.''
''Output expectations remain strong, particularly for companies well
established in export markets. And our invisibles performance is
particularly strong with a sizeable surplus emerging at the end of last
year.''
Mr Davies did, though, single out investment as the ''fly in the
ointment.'' Investment intentions remain weak, he said, adding, ''that
is why we hope the authorities will not react to market uncertainty with
another interest rate rise which does not look justified in
anti-inflation terms.''
He said: ''It is hard to avoid the conclusion that political
uncertainty is a contributory factor in the market's nervousness. A
Cabinet ceasefire on the single currency, therefore, would be a better
response than a rise in interest rates.''
</TEXT>
