<HEADLINE>European hopes are given a jolt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH clubs with hopes of doing well in Europe next season will not
be helped by the Scottish League when they prepare for their preliminary
ties in the major competitions.
As was the case last summer, the teams will go into their opening,
often crucial matches without the benefit of a domestic game as a
warm-up.
Next season will open with Coca-Cola Cup, first-round games -- not
involving any of the top sides -- on August 5.
The following week the European tournaments kick-off.
On August 12 the premier-division programme has been abandoned because
Scotland meet Greece in a European Championship qualifier at Hampden a
few days later.
League secretary Peter Donald said yesterday: ''I have no doubt that
the major clubs will prepare for the European games by organising
friendly games or taking part in tournaments.''
* THE fee for Hearts' midfielder Brian Hamilton, who left Easter Road
to cross the city and join up at Tynecastle, will be settled by a
transfer tribunal which will sit on March 2.
</TEXT>
