<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We can be the Parc's princes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KENNY Milne is the boss card in the Scottish pack. The 33-times capped
hooker will be the most senior Scotland forward on duty at Parc des
Princes tomorrow as the Scots seek to exorcise the spectre of 26 years
in the French capital without a win.
The Scottish side arrived in Paris last night confident that they can
confound the critics who say that they stand no chance of beating the
Parc des Princes hoodoo, and laying to rest the grim statistic of not
having won on French soil since 1969.
Captain Gavin Hastings, who wins his fifty-fourth cap, declared that
his side can build on the two victories against Canada and Ireland,
although they were not under-estimating the magnitude of the task which
faces them. Hastings added: ''If we play the kind of rugby which I truly
believe this side is capable of, then a victory is not beyond us.''
Milne, as a senior player, will be expected to give a lead to the
youngsters in the side for whom that first exposure to the often
volcanic atmosphere at the Parc could be an unnerving experience.
He makes his fourth visit to Paris, and plays against the French for
the seventh time. He is no stranger to what euphemistically is described
as the French ''streetwise'' ways.
''They will be up to all of their usual tricks. They'll pull a jersey
when you're chasing the ball, and that kind of thing,'' he says.
''For the guys who have never been there before, it will come as a bit
of a shock. But we have to make sure that those who are new to Paris
know just what to expect.
''But we have no reason to fear them. We have to go out there and play
our own game. We have to take play to the French. We must not let them
get into any kind of rhythm, and we certainly must not allow them to
intimidate us.''
There is a precarious path to be trodden here by the Scots. The
sidelined Gary Armstrong recalls how, in his first encounter with the
French in Paris, the side had allowed themselves to be intimidated and
lost 19-3.
Two years later, in 1991, the side had been well and truly psyched-up
by the time they burst from the Parc's dressing room. The result was an
over-eager Scottish side who gave away too many penalties and, for
Armstrong, it led to an uncharacteristic bout of all-in-wrestling with
French captain, Serge Blanco.
Tomorrow, Milne expects the Frenchmen to play with the usual passion
and commitment that they always display on their own turf.
''You find France a different breed on their own patch. The amazing
support they receive is a major factor. It was the same for us against
England during the Grand Slam match at Murrayfield in 1990. The crowd
that day was tremendous and it made us all go the extra yard,'' he said.
Milne knows little about his opposite number, Jean-Michel Gonzales.
''I don't think I've played against him before, but he looks strong. The
French are usually competent in the scrummage. They play a high grade of
club rugby.''
He reckons, though, that the key men for the French will be their
back-row. Benezzi, Cabbanes, and Benetton. The French like nothing more
than conjuring tries seemingly from thin air, and the back-row men are
the conduits for transforming no-hope broken-play situations into
breathtaking tries.
Milne observed: ''They like to set up those mini-rucks, and if they
are allowed to get into their stride, then they can be quite formidable.
We have to put the first-time tackles in and really make them count.''
The Scotland hooker knows that he is under threat from the Scotland A
captain, Kevin McKenzie, who sits on the bench in Paris. Manager Duncan
Paterson let it be known as the team for Paris was announced that he
reckoned McKenzie's time in the full side would come.
Milne, though, will not give up his place without a fight and as the
senior forward, he will try to give a lead in Paris.
He said: ''Kevin is desperate to get into the side. He has his
strengths and weaknesses as I do, but I still reckon I'm a better
player. I was a bit down ater the South Africa game at the end of last
year, but I think I had a good district championship campaign, and I was
quite satisfied with the way that I played against Canada and Ireland. I
did the basic chores, I was quite satisfied with my performance.''
The Scots, with just one Five Nations' game behind them, are in second
place in the championship behind England, who play their third game
against Wales in Cardiff tomorrow.
Final preparations for the game against France take place today when
the Scots will hold a public training session at the US Maison-Laffittee
ground on the outskirts of Paris.
* SCOTLAND'S Under-21 side take on their French counterparts in a
floodlit game at Evry Stadium, near Paris, tonight.
The Scots have not won a game since the 22-6 encounter with Italy in
1986. Last year, at Inverleith, they went down 21-12 to France, but two
years ago in Dijon, they were swamped 67-9, and manager David Leslie
knows how difficult his young side's task will be tonight.
