<HEADLINE>Skipper wants the fans up in Arms</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WALES skipper Ieuan Evans yesterday uttered the dreaded ''C-word'' --
that's Cardiff to you -- in the latest shot in the psychological battle
before the clash with England.
Evans reckoned England's miserable record at Cardiff Arms Park again
could be a factor, as it was when Wales pulled off an unexpected triumph
two years ago.
Then England were expected to steamroller the Welsh, but slipped to a
10-9 defeat after the Llanelli wing pounced on an error by his opposite
number, Rory Underwood, to score the winning try.
''I certainly hope their record in Cardiff will be a factor,''
admitted Evans, who will lead out Wales and complete his top-flight
comeback after a five-month battle for fitness following a broken ankle.
''The atmosphere in the stadium two years ago was something
special.The crowd feed off us as much as we feed off them.''
Saturday will be the fiftieth time England have played on Welsh soil,
with the first game in 1882. In that time, they have won only 14 and
drawn four.
At the Arms Park, England's record is even worse, with just eight wins
from 33 attempts and only one success since 1963. And England have
managed just one try on their last four visits.
But the Wales management will warn their players to forget the
statistics as they attempt to stop England taking a third step towards
another Grand Slam following the victories over Ireland and France.
</TEXT>
