<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Westminster Health Care up 21% to #6.3m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE DEMAND for private nursing home places continues to grow rapidly
with independent estimates of a requirement to build around 100,000 new
and replacement care home beds by the year 2000.
Although the nursing home industry remains highly fragmented,
corporate operators of large numbers of homes are increasing their
market share as they construct purpose-built premises and win Care in
the Community contracts with local authorities.
Westminster Health Care is one such company benefiting from the
commercialisation of private nursing care for the elderly. It operates
at the upper end of the market, offering single en-suite rooms to both
privately and publicly financed residents.
In the six months to 30 November 1994, pre-tax profits rose by 21% to
#6.3m on turnover up by 37% to #32.7m. Earnings per share grew by 18.6%
to 10.2p and the interim dividend per share was raised by 20% to 2.1p.
Overall occupancy levels in its homes remained steady at 92% although
in some areas where local authorities have experienced financing
problems, referrals have slowed down and occupancy levels have fallen to
the mid-1980s level. However, this has been offset by faster occupancy
rates in other areas.
Trading in the second half of the year is said to have started well
and the company has identified good opportunities for further growth.
Chief executive Pat Carter noted that at more than 1400 beds the company
had comfortably exceeded its target of beds in operations since
flotation.
The total number of homes in operation is 65 -- including 12 in
Scotland -- and another 11 homes are under construction in the UK
including a site at Dunfermline. Further sites have been earmarked for
development through to 1997.
The company denied rumours yesterday that it did not announce a rights
issue because of financial problems. Westminster said the timing was not
right even though it had received strong support from institutions.
The company emphasised that it had sufficient existing bank facilities
to finance current expansion plans although it is actively considering
other external forms of financing such as sale and leaseback deals. Its
development programme to date has been financed from existing banking
facilities and net debt at the half year-end was #44m, representing
gearing of 46%.
However, the possibility of a rights issue and a marginal reduction in
the 42% stake held by US shareholder National Medicine Enterprise
overshadowed the strong trading performance and the shares dropped 38p
to 293p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000018</DOCID>
