<HEADLINE>Trade mission to Japan yields #10m of exports</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than #10m worth of exports were generated during the Scottish
Council Development and Industry's latest annual trade mission to Japan
-- twice the level secured the previous year.
Figures released this week reveal that 30 Scottish companies did more
than #1.1m of business during the week-long visit in November, with
another #2.95m of completely new business and #6.05m of continuing
business with existing contacts expected in the short to medium-term.
The total for the previous year was nearly #5m.
SCDI mission manager Les Young, who was on the trip, said: ''It is an
excellent achievement in a very difficult market 6000 miles away.''
Compared with the rest of the UK, the level of Scottish exports to
Japan is disproportionately high. Japan is Scotland's sixth largest
market, with exports totalling #453m in 1993/94.
The delegation, including Glasgow engineering firm Begg Cousland and
patent agent Murgitroyd, consisted mainly of small and medium-sized
companies.
Orkney-based Judith Glue, who designs and produces knitwear, was
delighted with her firm's success on its first visit to Japan.
Mr Young, who was pleasantly surprised by the success of the mission,
said: ''Japan is not a market where you tend to go out for the first
time and sell very easily.''
The strength of the yen continues to make it relatively cheap for the
Japanese to buy goods from abroad. The country's recession has also
produced something of a sea change in attitude, with the Japanese now
focusing on value for money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MIM set off on the gold trail</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IAN Jennings, who has helped Scottish side MIM and England's St Albans
qualify for this weekend's finals of hockey's European Indoor Cup, will
not play against MIM in the event, writes Joseph Dillon.
Jennings, player/coach with Gilford, must return south for a league
match and so will miss out on a possible meeting with MIM in the
knock-out stages. St Albans German player Henning Tewes also will make a
swift departure from Edinburgh because of an engagement with Oxford
University.
Jennings claims that St Albans' strategy is ''to win our group in the
course of tonight and tomorrow and so avoid MIM in the semi-final, and
then, hopefully, get an easier tie on Sunday. This means that the boys
will be able to go on and qualify for the final, which will be enough to
let Old Loughtonians win promotion to the A Division of the championship
next year.''
This leaves too much to chance, for if St Albans avoid MIM, the
Slovakian side, Raca, and Olten, from Switzerland, may carry as much a
threat.
MIM begin their campaign tonight against Avoca Mazda, from Ireland,
and with Jonathan Smyth fit after injury, this match should be a mere
stepping stone to top ranking in their group, and eventually the gold
medals come Sunday. Today's games are:
Raca v Olten 4pm, Royal White Star v Jedinstvo 5pm, MIM v Avoca Mazda
6pm, St Albans v Stockholm 7pm.
* THE European Hockey Federation has based the groupings for the
finals of the European nations mens' outdoor cup in Dublin on April 16
to 27 on current ratings, and so Scotland has a fine opportunity of
qualifying for the semi-final stage.
They have been drawn in Group B with Holland, Spain, Belgium, Wales,
and France. Group A is made up of Germany (holders), England, Ireland,
Belarus, Switzerland, and Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ladies don't have too long to wait</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH Ladies, in Germany this weekend for the finals of the A
Division in the European club championship, are out to improve on the
bronze medal they won in the event last year, writes Joseph Dillon.
And their prospects look good. Russelsheim are the only German side in
the event this time, which means that the silver-medal position is
available. However, the Edinburgh team have been drawn in the stronger
of the two groups.
Their early target will be to win their group and in that way avoid
Russelsheim in the semi-finals.
''This gives us a better chance of reaching the final,'' said top goal
scorer Sharon Bissett, ''for I feel we can beat any of the three other
sides in the German's group.''
The emergence of Bissett as leading scorer has come against the law of
averages. She has been relegated from the starting six this year,
something which she is ''hacked off about,'' but it has made her even
more determined when she gets on court.
Edinburgh's group opponents are Valdeluz (Spain), Victoria (Holland),
and the English side, Slough. These are three good teams and any one
could provide an upset, with the Spaniards giving Bissett cause for
concern.
''Some of the girls,'' she said, ''are worried about Slough but I fear
Valdeluz, for their national team deprived Scotland of a place in the
1990 finals of the European Nations' Cup.''
Edinburgh get an early opportunity to find out the strengths of the
Spaniards. The teams clash in the opening series of games this evening.
On form, Edinburgh should do well and go on to win their group to put
them into a semi-final meeting with possibly Stade from Frances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Improved image needed for lambs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY GREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sheep industry has been challenged to improve the image of lamb if
it is to gain a greater share of the meat market.
James Warnock, chairman of the British Texel Sheep Society, which is
celebrating its 21st anniversary, says that everyone involved in the
production chain -- breeders, finishers, wholesalers and retailers --
must face up to the need for major improvements.
''It is up to all of us to promote lamb. It has a great reputation as
a natural tasty meat produced from grass, its image unclouded by
concerns over welfare or intensive systems.
''It warrants a concerted campaign to promote lamb's healthy
nutritional attributes to today's cholesterol conscious consumer.
''Perhaps the word lamb, considered by some to be emotive, should be
dropped in favour of brand or breed names.''
Mr Warnock said that vital statistics did not make good reading. Lamb
accounting for only 10% of the total meat and poultry consumed in the UK
and in France, a vital export market, it was only five per cent.
He said farmers must stop producing over-fat lambs with barely visible
eye muscles and should concentrate on the lean, muscular lambs wanted by
supermarkets, exporters and the convenience food sector.
''The saleable yield of meat from a beef carcase is between 70-73%,
from a pork carcase around 70% while the average lamb is just over 50%.
Clearly sheep producers have a lot to do if they are to move their
product up the league table and they need look no further than the
cattle industry for their first lesson.''
He points out that a growing number of beef animals are now
three-quarter bred or more, the result of an infusion of terminal sire
blood in the female, resulting in improved confirmation, muscling and
lean meat yield giving improved margins for both buyer and seller.
''The sheep industry must follow suit to increase the lamb's depth of
flesh, to breed lambs with broad backs, clean middles, wide, deep
hindquarters and a minimum of fat cover.''
Breeders must also eliminate the use of inferior crossing rams.
The Texel Sheep Society anniversary programme includes a weekend
conference and sale at Peebles on November 10-12
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pauline on guard</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAULINE McManus will win her first senior cap for Scotland at the home
international championships at Mansfield in April.
The 16-year-old, a member of Great Britain's world youth team, is the
youngest member of the team and is one of three new caps. Also making
their international debuts will be students Richard Smith and Martin
Doak.
The Scottish team, aiming for its fifth successive UK title, contains
15 players who competed at last year's Commonwealth championships where
Scotland won two individual and two team medals. Team:
Men. Foil -- R Smith (Stirling), R Cox (Eclipse), M McKay (Leicester
YMCA), M Doak (Culloden). Epee -- G Liston (RAF), J Chalmers (Bristol),
D McKernan (Meadowbank), A Baker (Reading).  Sabre -- P Hoenigmann, R
Cowan (both Team YF), M Hoenigmann (Eclipse), B Hanley (unattached).
Women. Foil -- K Sadler, P McManus (both Blantyre), S Kellet (Salle
Boston), J Walton (Eclipse). Epee -- R McFadden, L Roy (both Eclipse), G
Usher (Brentwood), V Cramb (Leeds).
</TEXT>
