<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Draw shot gives Knox an overtime success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEBBIE Knox was taken to the wire in the Royal Bank of Scotland
Scottish women's championships at Kilmarnock's Galleon Centre yesterday
evening, but after having beaten Kirsty Hay by one shot, Knox was not
complaining.
A fine draw shot gave Knox the one shot she needed for victory in
their second-round game.
But it all could have been different.
It looked as though success had eluded Knox in the tenth end when her
final shot was overswept, but her win by 7-6 followed an earlier defeat
of Carolyn Hutchison by the same score, putting Knox's team at the top
of the rankings.
On the same position is Rhona Martin, who beat Marion Miller by 6-3 in
her opening game, and she followed that win up with a 9-2 victory
against Claire Milne in yesterday evening's play.
Carolyn Hutchison went on to beat Sheila Harvey by 7-6 in the second
round to open her account in the championships, as did Marion Miller,
who beat Margaret Morton by 5-3. Results:
First round -- S Harvey 4, K Hay 11; C Hutchison 6, D Knox 7; R Martin
6, M Miller 3; C Milne 6, M Morton 5.
Second round -- M Miller 5, M Morton 3; R Martin 9, C Milne 2; K Hay
6, D Knox 7; S Harvey 6, C Hutchison 7.
Standings (after two rounds) -- B Knox won 2, lost 0; R Martin, 2-0; K
Hay, 1-1; C Hutchison, 1-1; M Miller, 1-1; C Milne, 1-1; S Harvey, 0-2;
M Morton, 0-2.
Club result
Summit Centre: Jean Gow final -- High Road -- M Henderson 7, A Airey
5. Low Road -- L Heaton 11, M Fulton 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Corsie a record breaker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a case of ecstasy and agony yesterday for two Scots in the
singles matches at the world indoor championship in Preston, with
Richard Corsie cruising to a world record, straight-sets win over
England's Russell Morgan, while Irvine's Paul Foster was well beaten by
John Price.
Corsie swept Morgan aside 7-0, 7-0, 7-2 in a match that lasted just 49
minutes and 10 ends. That chopped 13 minutes off the previous best time
and trimmed the ends total by two. And for good measure Corsie added a
third world record when he restricted Morgan to just two shots.
The previous best was held by Corsie at three shots after a win over
Welshman Lyn Tanner in 1991.
''I'm not normally too quick a starter,'' said Corsie, ''but I can't
have any complaints today. The problem now is maintaining that sort of
form throughout the championship.''
That win puts Corsie through to a second-round clash on Tuesday with
Australia's Cameron Curtis, also a straight-sets winner over another of
the home contingent, Paul Bennett.
Foster, however, tumbled to a four-set defeat at the hands of 1990
champion Price, who won 7-3, 7-1, 4-7, 7-1. Foster, who claimed his
place in the world championship by coming through the Scottish qualifer,
opted not to avail himself of the practise facilities in the Preston
Guild Hall.
''When I got up this morning I thought about it but I just decided not
to practise,'' said the man from Magnum. Foster got his just rewards
when he was outclassed by the former world champion.
In yesterday' other match, former UK champion Stephen Rees won through
with a 7-2, 7-0, 4-7, 7-5 win over New Zealand's Andrew Curtain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dairy farms are star performers in Scotland as buyers chase units. Land values surge by 29%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FARMLAND values have risen by 29% in the past 18 months to levels not
seen since ''the heady days of the late 1980's property boom'' and the
tail end of the farm production boom of the 70's and 80's, say Savills
Agricultural Research in their latest briefing.
The figures for Scotland are slightly behind, with a 27.4% increase
over that period. The biggest increase -- 49.8% -- was shown in the East
Midlands of England, followed by the West Midlands at 32%.
Growth has been strongest for good arable land, ranging from 33% to
40% on a Great Britain basis. Dairy land has grown in value by 26% and
poorer grazing by up to 23%.
Farmers buying with the intention of expanding their business have
continued to dominate the market while institutions and companies have
been net sellers.
Jim Ward, head of agricultural research with Savills forecasts that
capital values are likely to be fairly stable this year, perhaps
drifting lower. Towards the end of the decade, he suggests, a fall in
value of between 5% and 17% is in prospect as CAP reforms take effect.
While admitting that predicting long-term changes in the CAP is
''tenuous at best'' he suggests that it seems probable that current
support levels will remain intact for 1996 and 1997. ''By 1998 it is
likely that the pressures for reform will have started to overcome the
inertia of the EU decision-making process. The possibilities are many,
and include capping of area payments and renationalisation of support
payments. In the UK case, this would almost certainly mean lower
payments or higher environmental management requirements and lower net
margins.''
UA Properties, in their review of the Scottish market, say dairy farms
were the star performer in 1994 with large numbers of prospective buyers
chasing a relatively small number of units. Prices in excess of #1600 an
acre -- without quota or milking equipment -- were paid for farms which
could be converted to a dairy unit.
Well equipped grass farms also attracted good levels of interest. One
farm in Fife, without a house, achieved #1400 an acre.
The market for 1995 is said to be showing signs of following last
year's trend with high demand for good quality units. The impending sale
of British Coal holdings to tenants will be seen as an early test.
Non-farming purchasers have already lifted prices in areas which are
''commutable'' -- often beyond the economically viable limit for for
farmers, says UA Properties -- a member of the United Auctions Group.
However, the capital input into the countryside generated by these
purchasers is seen as helping to keep the countryside alive -- by
providing start-up chances for young farmers prepared to rent the land
and job opportunities for grooms and gamekeepers.
''With such a level of genuine interest in the farmland market, the
advice to anyone thinking of selling is to do so now,'' states the
review. ''As the influence of GATT increases and the European CAP is
altered, the future for farming may not be as rosy in the medium term.
However, the longer term outlook is better. As the population and their
appetites grow and the area of land farmed decreases, food production
will become an increasingly prosperous occupation for those competitive
enough to survive free world trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Galloway sale</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE spring round of pedigree beef cattle sales drew to its conclusion
in Castle Douglas yesterday with the annual Galloway sale. As at so many
other events recently buyers were highly selective but they had good
cause since by general consent the offering was distinctly lacking
quality in depth.
A handful of German enthusiasts were at the ringside and from then
came some prospect of an early resumption of the export trade which a
decade ago put Galloway breeders in clover.
Bertus Johlen, who runs Galloways near Hanover, said: ''It's now
possible that we will be able to get cattle into Germany later this year
especially since the ban on imports of UK beef has been relaxed.'' And
Frau Hanna Mastell, who has bought large numbers in the past at Castle
Douglas bought several heifers yesterday but in the meantime they will
be kept on a farm near Dumfries.
The bull trade was headed at 5500gns for the second prize Adam of
Luchurr by Grange Viceroy from Peter Kennedy Moffat, Lochmailling,
Auldgirth, Dumfries, which sold to Kenneth Lawrie, Snowden Close,
Gillsland, Carlisle, to join his 70 cow herd.
Next best at 4200gns was the reserve overall and senior champion,
Basil of Glenturk by the 9000gns Grange Yeoman from Brian Allan,
Glenturk, Newton Stewart which sold to Gordon Gilligan, High Creoch,
Gatehouse of Fleet, Margaret Gordon, Barfil, Crocketford, Dumfries, and
J G and R Bleazzard, Glenjam, Moniaive.
James Biggar, Grange, Castle Douglas, as ever enjoyed a useful selling
first at 2000gns to George Wilson, Reddings, Moffat, and Neil Manning,
Tweedshaws, Moffat, and then at 2500gns to Robert Brown, Bridgemark,
Dalry, Castle Douglas. M and J Ross, Romesveoch, Dumfries, sold their
reserve junior champion at 2000gns to Tracey Patterson, Kirktonhill,
Lauder, while the supreme champion from Castlemilk Estates, Lockerbie,
was withdrawn at 1200gns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Meat appointment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Premier Meat has appointed Herve Couperie as Sales Director
for France. Brian Pack, chief executive of ANM Group, parent company of
Scotch Premier, said: ''This is the next step in our European
development plan which is important to Scottish livestock farmers. We
aim to double our export sales from 10% to 20% of annual turnover.''
</TEXT>
