<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kale trials</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARIS Kestrel and Bittern have come top of the list of kale varieties
in a trial by the Scottish Crops Research Institute.
They had high fresh and dry matter yields, combined with good
emergence, uniformity and vigour. This was despite a dry summer which
depressed yields well below normal levels. Maris Kestrel produced 31.68
tonnes/hectare compared with Bittern at 27.83 t/ha and Hereford at 22.33
t/ha. This resulted in 4.57 t/ha in dry matter yield for Maris Kestrel,
4.68 t/ha for Bittern and 3.88 t/ha for Hereford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
