<DOCNO>GH950217-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>School closed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAPE TOWN: Black pupils were yesterday barred from a school in a
right-wing white area because they had vandalised it so badly that it
was now a health risk, according to education officials. White residents
with chains, clubs, whips, and dogs had threatened and insulted the
pupils since they were bussed to the abandoned school in a Cape Town
suburb three days ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Full steam ahead as auctioneers bid to gauge set's worth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LITTLE Jonathan White is trading in his steam train set for the modern
diesel variety after his father discovered that the 60-year-old
locomotive layout is an antique valued at more than #1500.
The four-year-old will wave goodbye for the last time to the Hornby
1930s locomotives, rolling stock, and track when it goes up for sale at
a Perth auctioneer's next week.
The boy's father, Mr Willie White, 39, explained: ''The track used to
belong to me, and my late father Angus before that. But my mother is
moving house and there's no room for it.''
The 60ft of track and its engines, wagons, coaches, and trackside
buildings has been valued at more than #1500.
''It has a lot of sentimental value and I had a lot of fun with the
set when I was a boy. But unfortunately you can't keep things forever.''
Mr White, a restaurateur of Glasgow Road, Perth, said that Jonathan, a
model railway enthusiast, would be getting a modern set to replace the
old line.
He added: ''Jonathan will be sad to part with it, but it was a bit
dated for him. He's very keen on trains and anything mechanical.''
Mr White will attend next week's auction to see how much the train set
realises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kleinwort Benson reports#5.5m fall in profits to #97m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN sharp contrast to the turmoil at arch rival S G Warburg, Kleinwort
Benson yesterday presented a picture of comparative tranquility with the
securities house reporting a mere #5.5m decline in pre-tax profits to
#97m.
However, the figures were flattered by a #7m clawback on provisions
made the previous year against the fall in values of vacated property
and also a #9.3m writeback of bad debts.
The biggest change was in dealing income which plummeted #60m to #43m
although #36m of the setback took place in the first half.
Chairman Lord Rockley said the favourable market conditions at the
beginning of 1994 were quickly followed by a more testing and uncertain
period across most major markets as the interest rate cycle turned
upwards in the US and the UK.
He added that confidence deteriorated despite improving economic
statistics resulting in unsettled markets worldwide and difficult
trading conditions.
Kleinwort remains prey to recurrent takeover rumours but any predator
would have to pay dearly because the return on capital of 20% is good
going even if it is down on the 24% reported in 1993.
Even if the volatile dealing profits were down, KLeinwort has
benefited from its concentration on specialist areas such as
international privatisations and cross-border mergers and acquisitions.
Funds under management rose 10% to #14.3bn.
Staff increased slightly to 2892 while the average remuneration rose
from #70,950 to #73,500 and probably passing that of Warburg which is
moving in the other direction.
Current year profits should be maintained at around 1994 levels as the
#16.3m of provision writebacks will not recur this time.
Shareholders will be encouraged by the 16% increase in the dividend
total to 21.5p for a 4.25% yield. The shares were 8p easier on the day
at 631p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wickes plans to quicken its Scottish expansion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRONG performances from its two newly opened stores in Perth and
Edinburgh has encouraged DIY retailer Wickes to accelerate its expansion
plans in Scotland. Stores are currently under development at Clydebank,
Dundee, and Aberdeen and planning permission is being sought for a
couple of stores in Glasgow.
Chairman Henry Sweetbaum said he believed that ''the Scots are very
receptive to the kind of value we offer''. Wickes has carved a
profitable niche for itself selling good value DIY products at the
structural and necessary end of the market rather than the cosmetic and
decorative end occupied by such companies as Sainsbury's Homebase.
Its focus on offering the lowest prices in the industry is attractive
to cost-conscious consumers and has boosted sales. This is reflected in
the 25% jump in its market share to 6%. Last year, Wickes recorded its
thirteenth consecutive year of record sales and profits.
Its sales jumped by 21% to #733.6m and its pre-tax profits surged by
69% to #30.1m. Earnings per share grew by 33% to 5.6p and the dividend
per share was raised by a generous 80% to 1.8p.
Within the retail business, underlying sales grew by 12%. Sales will
be boosted in the current year by the opening of 25 new stores. Wickes
is now the UK's fourth largest DIY retailer with 95 stores in the UK and
37 on the Continent.
There was good news from the Hunter Timber operation which returned to
profitability with an operating profit of #2.3m compared with a previous
loss of #1.6m. Although Malden Timber remained in loss progress was made
in repositioning the merchanting businesses, which were relaunched last
month under the Builders Mate name.
Wickes and Homebase stand out from the rest of DIY crowd in having a
clear focus on their respective markets and in having remained
profitable throughout the price wars and recession that has affected the
sector. Mr Sweetbaum believes that the proposed Homebase takeover of its
larger rival Texas is ''beneficial to us and beneficial to the market''.
He says that given the different focus of Wickes and Homebase, ''we
trade quite happily next to one another and both of us do well''.
Mr Sweetbaum said the group intended to continue to grow the business
by ''forcing down prices and forcing up value''. Sales in the new
financial year have started well with double digit sales growth
throughout the business in January.
The bumper trading news saw Wickes shares add a penny to 96p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sweet dreams</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Hong Kong government has so much money it could abolish salary
taxes for the next four years or give each baby born in 1995 a #120,000
start in life, international accounts Price Waterhouse said.
Hong Kong Financial Secretary Hamish Macleod, in his annual budget
speech on March 1, could give each couple getting married in 1995 a
#160,000 wedding present or abolish corporate taxes for two years.
Unfortunately, ''Price Waterhouse confidently predicts that Sir Hamish
Macleod will not announce any of the measures.''
</TEXT>
