<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The best of the bunch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ROAD TESTS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay tries out the new Ford Escort and finds it to be a vastly
improved and refined car.
BY far the most important thing to bear in mind about the Ford Escort
is that it is the UK's consistent best seller. It has always had its
press critics, who complain that it does not lead the family-car field
in any single aspect of design. This lofty attitude flies in the face of
all the evidence that the Escort package -- including such items as
servicing costs and likely trade-in value -- rings the bell with actual
buyers.
All the same, until now the Escort has seemed to be a lowest common
denominator kind of car. That has changed abruptly with the arrival of
the 1995 model year production. At first glance the latest cars may seem
to be just a revamp, but you can almost see Ford people's eyes bulging
if you use that word. Even a short drive makes it obvious why.
While the body styling remains very much the same, and there are
improvements of various kinds to the interior, Ford has at last let the
real experts loose on the Escort. The same team which, under Richard
Parry-Jones, gave the Mondeo such class-leading standards of handling
and response, has done at least as good a job on the Escort, in terms of
comparison with the models which came before.
I drove a Ghia saloon and estate over a wide variety of terrain in
France, from motorways and city streets to some wiggly and jiggly roads
in the hills. But I had gone only a couple of miles when I realised that
here was a car which, in its general handling, ride quality and noise
suppression, absolutely knocked all previous Escorts into a cocked hat.
Listening to Parry-Jones explaining how his team attacked NVH --
noise, vibration and harshness -- is a mind-boggling experience. It was
by no means just a matter of glueing some extra sound-deadening material
here and sorting out a sealing problem there. This was a really radical
programme, which tracked unnecessary noise and resonance through
suspension units, individual accessory mountings and even the shape of
the sump. The result is a car which is not just the quietest Escort
ever, but is also going to force rival manufacturers to make sure their
own products catch up in this department with the Ford.
The other great improvement is in handling, ride and driveability.
With both cars I tried, I had the impression that there was a lot less
''stiction'' in the steering and suspension. They were lighter to
handle, more responsive and generally just a lot more fun. All the same,
the latest Escort is modified from, but not a ground-up redesign of, a
car which hardly led the class in terms of handling and ride. It is
still not the sportiest-feeling car in its group of natural rivals.
The engines available -- 1.6 and 1.8 petrol, and 1.8 turbo diesel --
are not top of the class either in power, torque or high-rev smoothness.
But the other changes have managed to make the Escort feel far more
refined than it ever did before.
Another major improvement is to the interior. You can see the Mondeo
influence here, and the whole business of fascia design, seats, door
trim and so on has been totally upgraded. Prices run from #9495 for the
basic 1.6 to #17,370 for the RS2000 4x 4. Best interiors, naturally,
come in the Ghia versions from #12,865 in saloon or hatchback form and
#13,620 as an estate.  A straw poll of colleagues who drove the launch
cars showed that the one gripe about the interior appearance concerned
the wood-lookalike material on the Ghia fascia. The majority opinion was
that this was the Escort's only slip back into the realms of naff.
Not all the planned models in the new range will be available right
away, and several variants will come along later in the year. Without
going into great detail, pending a longer drive on local roads, I can
only repeat that the latest Escort is by a long way the best of the
bunch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
