<DOCNO>GH950217-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Second Saatchi departs agency</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHARLES Saatchi, co-founder with his brother Maurice of the Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi advertising agency, yesterday quit the presidency of the company
-- it was always a question of when rather than whether -- charging
''constructive dismissal'' and asserting his position had been made
''intolerable''. He intends to sue for damages.
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi said last night it had accepted the resignation of
Charles Saatchi and totally rejected any suggestion of unfair or
constructive dismissal.
With Maurice Saatchi, fired as chairman in December, already embroiled
in litigation with the group over his founding of a new agency, the
Saatchi saga looks set to run and run, perhaps for years.
First blood was drawn by Maurice Saatchi earlier this week when
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi was refused an injunction in the High Court in London
preventing him from competing with his former agency by soliciting
clients and recruiting former Saatchi staff.
On Wednesday, both the Mirror Group and Gallaher Silk Cut cigarettes
moved their accounts to The New Saatchi Agency, the former with
immediate effect and the latter when its current contract with Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi expires mid year.
Most people connected with the Gallaher advertising had moved to the
new company so Gallaher felt it ought to follow suit. The loss of these
two accounts is not particularly large in terms of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi's
income but it does not do its already battered image much good.
Maurice and Charles Saatchi and three executives who left Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi after Maurice was fired -- and who are also suing for
constructive dismissal -- plan to be equal partners in the new venture.
But at present Maurice Saatchi is the only one who is able to work for
the company although the High Court upheld the right of the four others
to join when they are free to do so.
Yesterday, Charles Saatchi maintained that Saatchi &amp; Saatchi made his
position as president intolerable by naming him in legal actions. The
company, though, claims it invited him to meetings to discuss the
situation and he has not turned up. He in turn says he has written to
the company seeking clarification and has had no reply.
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi has taken legal action against Charles on three
counts -- one claiming a share of the profit he and Maurice made on an
investment in sportswear company Adidas in 1993, over his involvement in
The New Saatchi Agency, and a third over any attempt by the new company
to pass itself off as the old company.
Clearly, on the present course, the solicitors and lawyers are going
to have a field day. The company expects to issue a circular to
shareholders by early next week with its favoured proposal for a new
name for the holding company. Shareholders vote in this on March 16.
Until then it is a case of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi versus Saatchi and
Saatchi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
