<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>January PSDR nears #3000m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER #6000m of corporation tax receipts boosted public revenues last
month, enabling the Government to repay nearly #3000m of debt.
January is the main month of the year when companies settle their tax
liabilities with the Inland Revenue. With company profits on the mend
receipts were over #1100m higher than in January of last year.
Last month's Public Sector Debt Repayment was #1000m higher than a
year ago. Privatisation proceeds conmtributed #88m from the sale of
Welsh assets of British Coal.
With just two months of the fiscal year left the Public Sector
Borrowing Requirement totalled #20.1bn, #9500m less than at the same
period of last year.
In the March Budget the Treasury forecast a PSBR of #34.3bn for
1994/95 against #45.4bn last year. There are still hopes in the City
that the Government will undershoot its target by about #2000m, but the
mad March spend by government departments makes this difficult to
predict. Last year the PSBR totalled #15.8bn in the last two months of
the year.
So far this year both Government revenues and spending have been
undershooting Treasury forecasts, mainly because inflation has been less
than expected.
Cash receipts for the first 10 months were 9% higher at #191.4bn than
in the same period in 1993/4. Inland Revenue receipts were 13.5% higher;
Customs and Excise 9.5% higher; and Social Security 11% higher.
By contrast net departmental outlays, excluding on-lending to local
authorities and public corporations, were 2% higher at #203.1bn.
Privatisation proceeds totalled #4600m against #3500m in the first 10
months of last year. Local authorities have repaid #1500m in the first
10 months, much less than the #4100m at the same stage of last year.
Public corporations have made a net repayment of #2500m so far compared
with #1100m by January of last year.
The strong contribution from corporation tax last month revived City
chat about tax cuts in the November Budget. The Treasury has forecast a
PSBR of #21.5bn next year, falling to #13bn in 1996/7, the year when tax
cuts would be likely to take effect.
By then the PSBR would be just 1.75% of gross domestic product, well
below the EU's central target of 3%. Hence the scope for tax cuts.
But the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, has to be sure
that he does not fuel an untimely boom with tax cuts as Lord Lawson did
in the late eighties.
Fiscal relaxation might have to be accompanied by higher interest
rates than would otherwise be necessary.
Minutes of the meeting between the Treasury and the Bank of England on
December 28, the one before it was decided to increase interest rates
for the third time since September, were largely ignored in the City.
The Governor of the Bank, Eddie George, was pleased with the reception
financial markets accorded the December 7 rate hike. The Chancellor
agreed, but pointed out that it had not been so well received by
sections of the business community, suggesting that it was likely to
have a restraining effect on activity.
Mr George was concerned about persistent cost and price pressures at
the early stages of the production and distribution chain. He also
pointed to evidence of pay settlements edging upwards.
Mr Clarke said that there few indications of inflation pressures at
the retail level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clarke puts final touch to electricity shares</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812511</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke yesterday put the final
touch to the electricity share sale as he fixed the discount to the
institutional price for private investors at 10p per share, the same as
in the BT3 issue of 1993.
So investors who have registered interest with a ''share shop'' will
be paying first instalments of 170p per National Power share and 185p
per PowerGen, 10p less than the institutions.
Mini-prospectuses will start to be mailed to registrants from early
next week, condensed from the 140-page densely printed full prospectus.
But even the mini version remains a tough read and most people will turn
directly to the public application form at the back which follows the
usual pattern.
But investors who do plough through it will find a number of warnings
related to the principle uncertainties facing the companies, which
consist of increasing competition, a possible reference to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission for failing to meet conditions imposed
by the industry regulator, Offer, and tighter pollution controls.
National Power and PowerGen have been exposed to a significant
increase in competition since 1990 from new combined cycle gas turbine
power stations and rising output from Nuclear Electric. The new power
stations run on natural gas and are cheaper to run. They are also much
less polluting than coal plants which provide most of the generators'
output.
The companies have already surrendered market share, particularly
National Power, which is down from 45% in 1991 to 35%. The decline is
likely to continue for a while yet and further competition will come
from the upgraded interconnector from Scotland once this is up and
running.
As for a monopolies reference, the companies can give no assurance
that this would not impact upon them to a significant extent. The
companies are supposed to ensure that prices in the pool or wholesale
market are on average below a figure agreed with the regulator Professor
Stephen Littlechild and to sell off a number of power stations to help
the development of competition. Whether these conditions will be met is
doubtful.
Certainly there has been no sign of any takers for second-hand power
stations. Failure will not automatically result in a reference, though
Mr Littlechild will not want to be seen giving way to pressure from the
generators. A reference could result in the companies being broken up or
more stringent conditions being imposed on them.
Finally there is a warning that future pollution regulation will be
tightened which may result in ''substantial'' further costs or
liabilities, though the industry has already spent around #3000m on
improvements. Not appearing in the prospectus is the possibility of a
tougher environment for the companies should Labour form the next
government, though this should also be borne in mind.
These factors mean that investors should not buy the shares in
anticipation of another threefold rise in the share prices, as has
happened since the first tranche of shares was sold. But they equally do
not mean the latest sale will not be a roaring success.
A total of 3,100,000 people have registered with share shops and most
of these will follow this up by applying for shares. Institutional
interest is reportedly strong and the international marketing of the
issue is not yet complete -- a roadshow is visiting Scotland on Monday.
Keen demand is almost inevitable and the over-allotment procedure will
ensure a steady after-market in the shares. This involves the
Government's advisers, Kleinwort Benson and BZW, over-issuing shares
with the intention of buying them back later in order to support the
price.
The certain prospect of large dividend increases in coming years will
alone be enough to ensure the shares give a reasonable performance,
though this is partly discounted in their current rating. Further in the
future they are likely to settle down into typical utility stocks
offering a higher than average yield, but no excitement.
Most buyers of privatisation stocks give little thought of selling
them but they ought regularly to dust down their share certificates and
see if the shares are still worth holding on to and this will certainly
be the case for the power generators.
Selling as well as buying shares marks out a real investor and though
Mr Clarke proudly declared that privatisation had raised the number of
shareholders to 10 million, few can be said to have become serious
investors, though they must now expect regular mailshots from their
share shops to persuade them to invest more. It is the first sale to use
share shops exclusively for private investors. There was no direct share
information office this time, and Mr Clarke said this would be the
pattern for the future.
So as the Government has finally got privatisation down to a fine art
-- though the regulatory frameworks leave much to be desired -- it has
run out of easy things to sell, particularly as the Post Office, the
Forestry Commission and Scottish water are to remain in the public
sector. Railtrack looms uncertainly on the horizon but it promises to be
the most difficult of the lot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Allied Domecq sells Lyons cakes to Tomkins for #35m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812512</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLIED DOMECQ has sold its Lyons cakes business to Tomkins for #35m
cash subject to approval from the Office of Fair trading. That is
involved because the Tomkins subsidiary RHM is the biggest manufacturer
of ambient cakes in Britain with brands such as Mr Kipling and Cadbury's
Cakes.
The Lyons business include Hales Cakes and Gateaux, based in Dublin.
It is estimated that for the year to March 3 1995, Lyons will achieve
pre-interest profits of #3.4m on sales of #95.1m from net assets of
#29.1m. There appears to be substantial efficiencies to be gained from
putting the two businesses together in an industry with over-capacity.
The acquisition is entirely consistent with the declared strategy of
Tomkins chairmnan Greg Hutchings of making infill acquisitions while it
continues to digest RHM which it bought in 1992.
Unfairly ,the City jury is still out on that deal when it does seem
pretty clear that it was a sound move bringing in a substantial low risk
cash generator.
Allied now has to sell its Tetley tea business to remove one of the
last vestiges of its involvenment in food manufacturing -- it is
currently in talks about the sale of its European baking activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quayle Munro down by 21%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MERCHANT bank Quayle Munro suffered a 21% decline in pre-exceptional
revenue before taxation in the six months to December.
The Edinburgh-based group, which reported yesterday, blamed the fall
on lower-than-expected corporate finance fee income. Revenue before
taxation fell from #323,000 in the first-half of its last financial year
to #290,000 but the December 1993 interim figure was distorted by a
#45,000 exceptional charge.
Boosted by a lower tax charge, interim earnings per share actually
increased from 5.5p to 5.8p and Quayle will pay an unchanged interim
dividend of 3p. The merchant bank predicted the tax cost would also be
less in the second-half.
With its listed investments, particularly London-based advertising
agency WMGO Group, on the slide, net asset value fell 5% from 234p to
222p during the six months. Waste management group Shanks &amp; McEwan was
another loser for Quayle.
Company chairman David Ross Stewart said the second-half had started
more satisfactorily, with a higher corporate finance workload.
However, he added that it was difficult to predict whether the
increased activity would result in an improvement in profits in the
second six months and Quayle shares yesterday tumbled 7p to 175p.
The volume of work on the corporate finance side was less than
expected. Chief executive Ian Jones said that, because of the nature of
the business, fee income was ''largely unpredictable'', with the
possibility of transactions falling through.
On the positive side, Quayle's unlisted investments, primarily Selkirk
circuit board manufacturer Exacta Holdings, Montrose-based Eskfood and
Chorley housebuilder Morris Homes, all traded well and further gains
were predicted.
Quayle, which was listed in June 1993, has a string of corporate
clients. However, it is probably best known now for its high-profile
work for the Scottish Office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
