<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Casualties at Dresden</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN LINKLATER'S article on the bombing of Dresden in the Second World
War perpetuates the myth that up to 250,000 lives were lost during the
raids.
In 1955 the Federal Republic of Germany's official statistical
publication, Deutschland heute, gave the total German loss of civilians
during the war as two million, and of these some 20% to 40% (400,000 to
800,000) can be attributable to strategic bombing.
In other words, if 250,000 lost their lives in Dresden then this
accounts for one-half to one-third of all deaths by strategic bombing in
Germany. I think not; we still have cities such as Berlin, Hamburg,
Cologne, Essen, et al to account for.
Also the destruction of Dresden and other strategic bombing raids
could not have been a war crime. For a crime to be committed there has
to be a law to be broken -- there was no international law regarding
aerial warfare in place.
The last attempt at codifying such a law was the 1923 Hague Air Rules
but these were never ratified or adopted by any nation.
Do not confuse morality with legality; what one can perceive as
immoral is not necessarily illegal.
Alex J Thomson,
63 Braidwood Road,
Carluke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dealer's Choice, National Theatre, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE WODDIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812516</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PATRICK Marber's Dealer's Choice could well prove to be the theatrical
debut of the year, placing him overnight at the front rank. Appearing
with mind-boggling assurance as both author and director, Marber has
already proved his spurs as a stand-up and TV comedy writer, part of the
creative team behind The Day Today and Alan Partridge. He also seems the
English equivalent of David Mamet or Sam Shepard.
Like Shepard's Tooth of Crime and True West or Mamet's Glengarry
Glenross, this play is a metaphorical rutting area where the sound of
locking horns is distinctively male and generational. But not around
sexual conquest (nary a female in sight) -- rather the mysterious and
intoxicating allure of poker. Both seducer and destroyer, the weekly
poker game is the ritual by which Stephen, a London restaurant owner
(sharply evoked in Bunny Christie's split-deck metal and chrome set),
exerts control over his various wavering workers and wayward son Carl,
like father a gambling addict.
Bluff and macho counter-bluff, dreams and despair, winning and losing,
Marber introduces these with an extraordinary mastery of humour and rich
observation. Apart from Nicholas Day's crisp Stephen (his floppy
cardigan belies the calculation with which he manipulates all those
around him), Nigel Lindsay's hapless Mugsy (wildly hooked on the idea of
opening his own restaurant from former public conveniences in the Mile
End Road), Ray Wynstone's wonderfully lachrymose chef, Sweeney, and a
typical wide boy wine waiter from Phil Daniels are beguiling creations.
All too inevitably, there's a final showdown over a game -- and
disappointingly, a slightly weak ending. But by then, audience and
players are locked into complicity. The air has crackled with tension
and Marber is home and dry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Remorse</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY this remorse of conscience over Dresden (February 13)?
As a boy I witnessed Coventry's night of baptism by fire.
As for the raid on Clydebank, I have in my possession a Luftwaffe map
of it, dated September 10, 1939.
If we had lost to Germany, would The Herald be questioning Germany's
conscience? Would The Herald exist under a Nazi regime?
Harry Dowson,
9 Burnfoot Crescent,
Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
