<HEADLINE>More sounds bound for city</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>BOSS GROOVES</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A festival of new music is to be staged in Glasgow in October. David
Belcher describes the shape of music to come.
HAVING last year enhanced the lives of countless Glaswegian
music-lovers with its many live gigs, workshops, and seminars, Sound
City has now moved on to Bristol. But Glasgow's civic leaders last week
officially backed a new event which is intended to continue what Sound
City 94 began. Buried amid the city's recently announced
multimillion-pound annual budget was a grant of #100,000 for a 10-day
festival of new music to be staged in October.
There is much hard work to be done before then, not least in ensuring
that non-civic bodies stump up a sum which matches that figure. And
there's the troublesome task of finding a name for the forthcoming
event, intended to feature bands from all rungs of the career ladder,
and of all musical hues. Local Glasgow bands; Scottish bands; bands of
global stature; ragga-trance bands; Indo-jazz-fusioneering aggregations;
straightahead rock combos.
If it were to be called Sonic City, would Sega sponsor it? Is Music
City too bland? East 17 have successfully made a trademark out of their
post code, so how about Gee One Gigsville? No Mean Beat City? Does
George Unsquare . . . Rock This Town have a bit too much of the blowhard
Glaswegian about it?
At least the event has received positive backing from every informed
local quarter at a series of meetings staged over the past eight months.
Presided over by the event's prime movers, Bob Palmer, of Glasgow's
Department of Performing Arts, and Musicians' Union Scottish organiser
Ian Smith, these meetings have been attended by representatives from
every leading Scottish promoter and city centre live-music venue; by
native media-wallahs; Glasgow-based music-industry lawyers and
accountants; educationists running specialised rockbiz courses at city
colleges; musicians.
Most crucially, given the importance of Radio 1 last year as an
advertising medium for Sound City in Glasgow, all the major Scottish
radio stations -- Radio Scotland, Clyde, Scot FM -- have given the event
the thumbs up, as well as having indicated their willingness to
co-operate in equitably apportioning broadcasts and thus avoiding
conflicts of interest.
''It was easy last year to dangle the carrot of Radio 1 in front of
big bands,'' says Sound City's co-organiser, Willie Knox. ''This year,
Glasgow's year-round promoters -- King Tut's, the Cathouse, the Garage,
Nice'n'Sleazy -- are going to have to work much harder, with support
from the council taking the form of an overall marketing campaign,
producing programmes, flyers, posters.
''With that form of advertising support, it's easier for promoters to
take risks -- and it's a more proper use of council money, too. The
council shouldn't be directly paying big fees for big names and possibly
bearing a big risk.
''In addition, council money should ideally be used to develop new
audiences by subsidising punters rather than subsidising bands, for the
staging of free gigs or the funding of concessionary tickets.
Ultimately, it's more important for a band to have an extra 100 people
at a show instead of an extra #50 on their fee.''
What's in it for Glasgow's civic fathers?
''Throughout last year Sound City staged 200 gigs, featuring 300
unsigned bands. It gave people an appetite for going out, and during the
main April week a lot of people went out to attend more than one show a
night -- yet we still have a curfew which is intended to restrict
movement and prevent people doing that.
''During New York's New Music Seminar, you can see bands from 8pm till
4am. Not in Glasgow. But if the nature and purpose of the curfew could
be reviewed for our October event, it would surely act as a valuable
experiment in determining the true value of the city's night-time
economy.''
And what has been learnt from Sound City's mistakes -- and mistakes
there were, as Whiteout might attest in the wake of their
less-than-well-received East End community tour. Rowdy teenies
vandalised Whiteout's van as the band played; warring gangs battled to
the plangent strains of Starrclub; Whiteout's vocalist was almost
decapitated by an ungrateful yobbo frisbee'ing his free copy of the
group's single out of the crowd, back towards the stage.
''That was an example of something that was very good, that had
honorable intentions -- and it backfired very badly. We felt we were
giving the communities something . . . and the communities felt they
were having something imposed on them. Occasionally, the community
events we staged were at too advanced a level. What worked best in some
places were basic, practical workshops in which people in bands spoke
about being in bands, answering questions like 'Do you make a living
being a band?'
''Some communities had impractical demands, though. I recall the
Possil Loud'N'Proud Revival Tour, various cover bands playing in pubs.
I'm not being disparaging about anybody, but it might have been better
had Sound City funded basic guitar lessons for local 12-year-olds. After
all, they're the future of the local music economy rather than
semi-established bands doing Simple Minds songs.
''Thankfully, all the community officers now see that and are working
more co-operatively with each other and with Sound City's replacement.''
Whatever it's called, let's hope it follows Sound City's example and
funds some of the more ambitious, elaborate, and artistically
challenging events, like NVA's Soundworks at the Arches and Paul Quinn's
Cheap Flights at the GFT. Not all pop is automatically profit-driven. As
civic funding is regularly extended to theatre, art galleries, and
opera, so it should benefit the more adventurous forms of modern music,
too.
* What's in a name? If you'd like to have a go at naming October's
events, you'll get a Sound City T-shirt. If your chosen name is adopted,
you'll be rewarded with a two-person VIP pass to every event . . . and
if you can stump up five-figure wads of sponsorship cash, you can dance
on the roof of the City Chambers with Bob Palmer, Ian Smith, and me in
City of Glasgow tartan kilts and reversed baseball caps. Entries pronto
to: David Belcher's Name-That-Festival, The Herald, 195 Albion Street,
Glasgow, G1 1QP.
</TEXT>
