<HEADLINE>Reiteach, Tramway, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TORCUIL CRICHTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER the success of Craobh Nan Ubhal -- The Apple Tree -- Drama NA
h-Alba, the embryonic Gaelic Theatre Company, might have been expected
to produce another culture-skipping piece.
The Apple Tree -- all scaffolding, lights, noise, and mime -- was
raw-edged expression. It set Gaelic in the modern off-world of North Sea
Oil, language limitations of a wider audience overcome by action and
emotion. Reiteach -- beginning its Scottish tour -- is the complete
opposite. Here the set is bare, the acting subsumed by the words, the
imagery of the language supreme.
To begin the story is a simple boy (bachelor) meets girl (Canadian,
second generation Scot). Just beneath this love tale John Murray has
written an introspection on cultural identity, the Gaelic psyche, that
familiar albatross of bilingual Scots. It is a recurring theme -- sinn
fhein, ourselves -- this time the mirror being held by a woman searching
for a Celtic past. Conflict arises from characters embracing and
rejecting cultural values in increasingly tight spirals.
Away from the complicated text Tony Kearney finds his acting feet in
Reiteach, relishing the maverick character who drives the action to
music. Donna MacLeod and Domhnall Ruadh are confident as the loving
couple backed by singer, actress, and New Yorker Talitha MacKenzie.
This is a demanding play for audience and performers requiring
attention to the subtlety of language as much as the acting. The
script's importance is emphasised by the fact that copies are for sale
in the foyer.
The strong tradition of Gaelic drama is developed with Dan Murray and
Murdo MacLeod joining the professional troup. Nan MacLeod shadowed Irish
director Garvan Macgrath through rehearsals. With Reiteach Gaelic
theatre, like the Gaelic world, is in transition.
</TEXT>
