<HEADLINE>Yggdrasil Quartet of Aberdeen, Mitchell Hall, Aberdeen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I THINK that the Yggdrasil String Quartet, originally of Stockholm,
now adopted by the City of Aberdeen, have the potential to become one of
the great quartets of the day. Launching their inaugural series of
concerts last night -- their official concert debut following their
appointment to Aberdeen in a unique triple partnership between the city,
the university, and the arts council -- they disclosed a catalogue of
credentials.
If those credentials were tarnished at all, then it was probably the
pressure of the occasion -- all the big wheels of the Scottish musical
scene were present.
In two of their pieces -- the Fifth Quartet by Stenhammar and the
first of Beethoven's Rasumovsky quartets -- they took time to settle.
No problems with ensemble: they are phenomenally together. Just an
edginess (and Beethoven's a killer if you're on edge).
By and large, however, this was an outstanding debut. These young lads
are a born string quartet. Their virtuoso playing (and virtuoso dynamic
control) in the Stenhammar was breathtaking.
They found character and wit in the piece. And when the going got
tough they played with massive attack and ferocious bite.
And intelligence, too, as they demonstrated in a performance of Judith
Weir's String Quartet that was marked by clarity and intensity. It was
also, remarked the composer, who was present, the most authoritative
performance that has been given.
More from the Swedish gods soon.
</TEXT>
