<DOCNO>GH950217-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Courtney Pine, City Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COURTNEY PINE has never been exactly what you might call shy on stage.
Now he's in danger of turning a jazz gig into a good night out. The
showman in him was on display early. He loves eye contact with his
audience and as he skated through a far from slushy Misty the bug eyes
were on us. A ''how does he do that?'' bout of circular breathing had
him on his knees.
This was nothing. Not even the audience countdown to a teasingly brief
version of Eddie Harris's funky Listen Here that finished the first half
(a full version opened the second) gave a hint of how far he was going
to take the fun, so for those of you who weren't there I'll fast forward
and tell you how far.
Sidewinder had him careering around the audience, soloing (and making
perfect sense), quoting Stevie Wonder's Isn't She Lovely at a blonde in
row E. If this isn't your idea of fun, you're probably one of the only
two people who failed to stand up and clap your hands as instructed
before the encore could begin.
Not that it was all showbiz. Pine's past concerts have often featured
a whole lot of empty virtuosity. This one had plenty solid jazz and
rather than simply playing to the gallery, Pine's ''sheets of sound''
outing on Misty impressively interwove about six different themes. It
was occasionally slick, sometimes challenging, and the DJs' scratching
and hip hop loops, once they could be heard, fitted well alongside a
hard-working band.
So if you're going to Pine's gigs in Edinburgh (tonight) or Aberdeen
(tomorrow), leave your jazz baggage behind and don't forget your dancing
shoes.
</TEXT>
