<DOCNO>GH950217-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hidden J, CCA, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAYBE it was last week, maybe it was last year, or as far back as
1988, or it might be tomorrow. You suddenly look up and -- like Forced
Entertainment -- you see the bleakness, the messiness, the stupid silly
wastage of our times. Hidden J -- repeated at the CCA tonight and
tomorrow -- is the company's evocation of that landscape which is at
once familiar and yet increasingly inhospitable.
Subtitled Bad News Bad People Bad Debts, the piece jigsaws together
glimpses of little lives that are relentlessly askew. Party animals
losing themselves in a noisy welter of boos and pranks -- fun for all,
but not so funny for the guy who ends up the outsider, naked and
disoriented. Then there's the worst ever Best Man, fumbling and rambling
through the usual cliched phrases -- his incompetence is hilarious, but
as he battles on through one unfinished banality after another the
balance tilts quite brilliantly. The laughter drains away from his
situation, he becomes a sad, drab emblem of something futile and
hopeless.
Everything about the piece has been carefully crafted to suggest
fragmentation, dislocation, harshness, and yet there is a brilliantly
comic edge to so much of the clever incongruity. All the strengths of
this company -- the ability to combine layers of meaning in one image --
means that one can chortle at some poor soul's litany of failure and
inadequacy even as one begins to hear in it sorry echoes of a
Thatcherite regime which has preached a hollow set of values that have
left too many feeling inadequate. Forced Entertainment is at present
facing its own bad times -- arts council funding is being withheld
because, apparently, it turns in poor work. Would that I could see such
poor work more often. For a resume of how much it has achieved, turn up
tomorrow at 2pm for a special talk/lecture that celebrates a decade of
radical experiment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
