<DOCNO>GH950217-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Try feeling good inthe real world, Ken</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke told the Telegraph yesterday: ''I found the
latest figures perfectly balanced and consistent with the healthy
recovery that I think we are delivering.'' His words are subtly
revealing.
Mr Clarke and his colleagues are publicly committed to the primrose
path of economic virtue -- an export-led recovery sustained by stable
prices at home. No tinsel, he promises. No artificial booms. If we can
do that for two more years, the Chancellor argues, all this stuff about
the missing feel-good factor will be seen to have been ''a bit of a
cliche''. By then, presumably, we will all feel good because we will all
be feeling profoundly virtuous.
The Chancellor was speaking as headline inflation edged higher for the
fourth successive month; as dreary retail sales figures for January
punctured some of the post-Christmas sales hype indulged in by leading
retailers; and as the downward trend in the official count of the
unemployed showed signs of tailing off.
Mr Clarke was also talking in the wake of three successive rises in
interest rates, in which he had a hand; a rocky pound; and mounting
evidence that last year's 4% growth is already being squeezed quite
hard.
Whether that amounts to perfect balance is, at best, debatable. But
the most revealing thing about Mr Clarke's comment to the Telegraph is
the tacit admission that neither he, nor anyone else for that matter,
really knows whether the figures add up to a healthy recovery or not.
Look at those words again. The Chancellor thinks he is delivering a
healthy recovery. And he thinks the latest indicators are still
consistent with the fact of that recovery. The trouble is that in the
Treasury, the Bank of England, the City, and everywhere else where
players claim to make sense of what is happening, complex economic
reality, as it is lived and experienced by each and everyone of us, is
reduced to a small set of key monthly indicators.
Changes in these official numbers, and the interpretation placed on
these changes by markets, are the main triggers for action. Each time Mr
Clarke and the Governor of the Bank of England have raised interest
rates in the past five months, that's what they've been responding to. A
signal of inflationary pressures here. A sign of unsustainable growth
there.
The unspeakable question is: how accurate a reflection of economic
reality are these figures? And, if the answer is the equivalent of
putting the height of Ben Nevis somewhere between 2000 and 6000 feet,
does reacting to such slippery evidence with decisive action make things
worse as often as it makes things better?
Of course governments and central bankers try to temper the diet of
official statistics with more empirical evidence of what's going on. The
Bank of England, for example, maintains a network of agents around the
country -- one of them in Scotland -- who carry out a steady programme
of company visits and report back on the mood as they find it.
Achieving that blend of apparently objective evidence and feel for
what is actually happening on the ground is a critical challenge for
modern policy makers, whatever their political hue. You might have
noticed that every time the BBC's Economics Editor Peter Jay wants to
take a poke a current government policy, he takes himself off to the
real world to ram home his point. On Wednesday evening he was reflecting
on the latest inflation and retail sales figures from a shopping centre
in Winchester.
The trouble is that, trapped in the Whitehall birdcage of official
advice, ministerial cars, and the Commons tearoom the hard numbers tend
to win every time over subjective experience. Ministers, central
bankers, and those dawn-to-dusk City analysts simply don't get much time
to go out and soak in what the rest of the world is saying or thinking.
You detect that more and more in the increasingly desperate ''Why are
they not more grateful?'' pleas of ministers, convinced they have
delivered the sweetest confluence of economic circumstances in a
generation. I wonder at their puzzlement.
Take the export-led recovery. Unless you are an exporter, supply an
exporter, own shares in an exporter, or work for an exporter, why would
the export boom that followed sterling's exit from the exchange rate
mechanism make you feel good?
And even if you work for an exporter, booming business may not be
sufficient reason for you to send Ken Clarke a case of his favourite
ale. Ask 600 families at Rolls-Royce in East Kilbride what the group's
latest Indian order means to them.
At the moment, Scotland's computer industry may be shipping boxes as
fast as it can assemble them. But if I worked at IBM in Greenock, say,
my sense of security would be affected as much by the defection, in
quick succession, of the head of IBM Europe, the head of worldwide PC
manufacturing, and the head of IBM UK, as by a bulging, albeit tight
margin, order book. Do they know something I don't?, I would be asking
myself.
It's a similar story in Scotland's other great exporting industry,
whisky, where failure to crack inequitable duties, even at a UK or
European Union level, continues to cast a cloud over the sector's
prospects.
For those untouched by exports or exporting, there are still, it seems
to me, as many reasons for feeling bad as there are for feeling good.
Mortgage rates are edging up again. Council rents and council taxes will
rise substantially in April. Work is becoming increasingly casualised.
The education system is being asked to soak up more and more of the
surplus. Rewards, for most people, are at a virtual standstill in real
terms. We are becoming a more fractious, divided, and cynical society.
Surveying his numbers, resolute in his determination to choke off
inflation, Ken Clarke apparently thinks another two years of the same
will prove all this to have been a cliche. We shall see.
</TEXT>
