<HEADLINE>Thatcher's rule</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BY the use of selective statistics and a careful employment of
language, Michael Fry tries to persuade us that the Thatcherite
experiment was a success (February 11).
In 1979 the UK had a national income per head on a par with that of
France and ahead of Italy. We now struggle to keep ahead of Spain.
The crumbs from a rich man's table theory of income distribution works
(if at all) only if there is substantial, real growth. Contrary to
Michael Fry's assertion, the average annual real growth rate in Mrs
Thatcher's time, at 1.9%, was markedly and disastrously less than during
the oft-maligned premierships of Messrs Wilson and Heath (2.8%).
The reality of Mrs Thatcher's squalid rule included record
unemployment, record bankruptcies, and a catastrophic shrinking of the
country's industrial base.
Gordon McNeill,
68 South Scotstoun,
South Queensferry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000058</DOCNO>
