<HEADLINE>Banda and Currie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
R A P CALDWELL states that Dr Hastings Kamuzu Banda was in general
practice in Renfrew at the same time as my late husband (January 14).
Dr Banda did work with Dr John Todd for a time. In 1941 Dr Banda was
in Liverpool before being directed to Tyneside. He had, as a pacifist,
refused to join the Army.
Gordon Currie graduated in 1944. He was assistant to Dr John Todd for
nine months from the summer of 1945, after which he went to Nyasaland
(Malawi).
The first time he met Dr Banda was at an afternoon tea party at the
start of the Malawi Congress Party's election campaign. This event took
place at Fort Manning. The local MCP candidate introduced us to Dr
Banda. Dr Currie then said, ''I was assistant to Dr Todd in Renfrew'',
whereupon Dr Banda exclaimed with a Scottish accent, ''It's a small
world!'' and warmly shook his hand again.
After the election, Mr M W Kanyama Chiume became Minister of Education
and planned to visit every school in the country. He informed Dr Currie
that he also would address the patients when he came to the leprosarium
school.
On arrival Mr Chiume headed straight for the Protestant church, which
housed the school, omitting the normal formality of seeing the doctor
first. So the doctor had to run after the Minister. This incident may be
the basis of R A P Caldwell's claim that Dr Banda ignored Dr Currie.
Later correspondence between Dr Currie and Dr Banda was entirely
amicable.
Morag M Currie,
6 Durward Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
