<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fortress Britain keeps the drawbridge raised</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JEUX sans Frontieres, jeux avec frontieres. The laager-louts of
British politics -- and they come from both right and left -- are
playing mirthless power games with the nation's status as island
fortress; which has been something of an illusion anyway since the
invention of the smart bomb and the electronic money market.
When the Channel Tunnel opened they worried about rabid rats sneaking
into the country. Now, as M. Santer presses the case for opening the
borders of the European Union, they worry about rabid foreigners.
Borders, frontiers -- they are powerful totems on the landscape of the
human story. They have earned a menacing place in literature and drama:
the long Le Carre walk through the checkpoints of the Berlin Wall, the
furtive figures beneath the watchtowers, the bureaucrats on the Stamboul
Train, the desperate swimmers in the Rio Grande.
In fiction and in fact the border is the emblem of an exquisitely
tormenting ambiguity. It is danger and safety, homecoming and exile,
capture and escape, acceptance and rejection.
Even in the stale ennui of our airport queues we can't quite evade
these resonances. Which of us hasn't felt shifty as we look the
gatekeeper in the eye? At the extreme edge of border nervousness is the
nightmare of the refugee. And it's a mad irony of British resistance to
the freeing of EU frontiers that the nation who most protests is the
nation with the least experience of the trauma of the fugitive. It's
nearly 300 years since the last Englishman fled to safety across the
Scottish Border, and vice versa.
North of the Border, South of the Border. We have lived more or less
comfortably with Britain's internal frontier for three centuries. Its
line is something of an abstraction. Certain laws and institutions
readjust themselves when we cross it. The domestic architecture, the old
designs of towns and villages and the configuration of the countryside
slowly change, but these shifts are scarcely fundamental.
Instead, we turn the ghostly boundary into something which either
satisfies or disappoints our romantic expectations of the frontier
crossing.
At its western end it's a river; no mighty Zambezi or trans-European
waterway like the Danube, but the meagre River Sark, where the interface
between Scotland and England subsides into sullen flatlands, as if
exhausted by old wars. The M74 treats the Sark with contempt. At the
eastern end it is almost-a-river, but the A1 fords the Tweed some few
miles south of the invisible line. For frontier drama we must choose the
high pass of Carter Bar, where the A68 vaults over the Cheviots on a
crest which marks the Border.
The natural obstacles of rivers and ranges have defined many a
nation's edges. ''Climb every mountain,'' sang the mother superior in
The Sound of Music. So the Family Von Trapp packed their rucksacks and
walked over the Tirolean alps into Switzerland, the model bolthole.
Europe has devised double standards for Switzerland, its oldest
multicultural, plurilingual democracy. The country which invented the
cuckoo clock but didn't have the Renaissance (remember Harry Lime's
brutal aphorism?) is both despised and cherished for its long
neutrality.
I've been looking through my passports for the Swiss stamps which
might chronicle several visits to that country, but I can't find any.
And Switzerland isn't even a member of the EU. In fact, the last French
stamp I can find is dated 1981 and the last Spanish one 1978, and I've
been back to France and Spain many times since.
I'm now on my third 10-year passport (its stately British blue will
soon be replaced with EU burgundy) and the only stamps and visas in the
current document are either non-European, or those which pre-date the
dismantling of the Eastern Bloc states.
Anyone who has travelled on the Continent in the past 10 years,
whether in or out of the EU's member states, knows that border controls
have become more and more cursory. Mainland Europeans have long treated
their frontiers more casually than we do. You can board a train in Paris
and get off in Budapest and the border crossings of four countries are
little more distracting than the interruption of a ScotRail ticket-check
between Waverley and Queen Street.
Even at the extremity of Europe, in Istanbul, you can stand in the
Sirkeci station and see transcontinental trains whose destinations read
like chapter headings in twentieth-century European history: Bruxelles,
Munchen, Wien, Zagreb, Beograd, Sofia; as if, for all the hideous crimes
its people have visited on each other, a shared purpose and common
destiny are forged in the steel of Europe's railway network.
If such moments make me sentimental about Europe they don't make me
soft-headed. I'm aware that it's only the traveller of Caucasian aspect
who moves more and more smoothly across its borders. When Fort Britain
lets down the drawbridge to its EU partners, as eventually it must, it
will raise it again on the external frontier of Fort Europe; and on the
other side of the great Mediterranean moat the huddled masses will wait
and dream.
Well, huff the legislators, the bureaucrats, the man and woman in the
street, we must draw the line somewhere. I suppose we must until we find
a working alternative to the nation state and its partisan
conglomerates, but the more I travel the harder it becomes to find the
definitive borderlines of my cultural identity. When I'm in England I
feel Scottish; when I'm in North America I feel European; when I'm in
Asia I feel Western; when I'm in Africa, most troublingly, I feel white.
And when I'm in Europe? There was a time when that was when I felt
most British. These days, whether in or out of the EU, I feel one of the
crowd. ''The idea of national characteristics,'' remarked Stephen
Leacock, long before the idea of European unity, ''has been greatly
overdone.'' There may be some nostalgia when I hand in my last piece of
grave blue cardboard with its totemic crest and old presumptions, but
there will be no regrets.
It will join its partners, with their clipped corners, at the back of
my desk. Every so often I will pull it out and browse through the stamps
and visas of the world outside Fort Europe; with the relaxed mindset and
pleasant recall of the traveller who has always been permitted ''to pass
freely, without let or hindrance'', knowing nothing of the nightmare of
the refugee.
0
</TEXT>
</DOC>
