<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''I coulda been a contender.'' Well I was. Many times. One of the
contentions was for the post of vice-president of the Educational
Institute of Scotland. There were a lot of contentions at that,
especially within the teaching profession, of which I was a somewhat
maverick member, for many on left and right thought I was a wee
foul-mouthed bastard who would cause nothing but trouble. Last week saw
the election of a new general secretary of the major Scottish teaching
union, and saw a somewhat anodyne, though time will tell, candidate win.
All of the candidates for what was not so long ago a horribly
important political position in Scottish life -- after all long-time
general secretary John Pollock had been chairman of the Labour Party in
Scotland twice -- were of course anodyne.
There are three strands to Scottish identity which count: the only
ones that really do. The religious system whereby we are utterly
independent of the State, the unique Scottish legal system, close to
Europe and highly respected world-wide -- and Scottish education. For
many years this has been anglified and transmogrified. For many years
the Scots have felt this should not be so. And it has taken many a
fighter in and out of the world of education to stem the tide.
One of the doughtiest of all has just written a book about his long
and pugnacious life. He is Kenny McLachlan, an ex-president of the EIS
himself, the president in fact of the hardest ever years, the strike of
1983-85, the longest teachers' strike ever, and the only industrial
dispute which Thatcher lost following her victory over the miners. It is
Kenny McLachlan with whom I was the running mate all those years ago.
As it happens both Kenny and myself were ex-Communist Party members. I
have never felt the pain that Kenny clearly did when he was expelled
from The Party. He was expelled simply for being his own man, though a
trumped-up charge was used against him, mainly by West-End Comms who
hadn't seen a single-end in their lives. (I was expelled for ''bourgeois
adventurism '', that is, being pissed at parties and trying to seduce
lassies.)
BUT Kenny, who had not only fought for communism, but also for the
Western democracies during the war -- I may say he made an
extraordinarily handsome squaddie if the war-time photie in his book is
anything to go by -- but he never stopped fighting at all.
I can assure you that Kenny never went for the high positions which he
often reached, for reasons of egotism. I have seldom met anybody with
less pretensions and, believe me, I know all about egotism. Kenny worked
himself into the ground for what he believed. And his faith, sometimes
rather as woolly as his fluffy ring of hair I am afraid, never wavers.
Throughout his book, to be launched tomorrow at midday in,
characteristically, Maryhill Burgh Halls, (Kenny lives in Maryhill), he
never flinches from his belief in the essential goodness of every man,
woman or child, and of the inherent evils of all organisations,
bureaucratic or otherwise. Except of course for the Communist Party.
Nothing can be more sad than listening to ex-party members telling of
such a disillusionment. Even lapsed Catholics cannot express such
despair as that of the ex-faithful of Moscow. And this book is fired
through with that sense of betrayal by what was to be the Great Vision.
It is difficult to explain what The Party meant to those who belonged,
of how the links in the golden chain forged a comradeship which never
quite leaves you, even to sceptics like myself. Kenny comes from a
different age, of course, but even then I suspect he always would have
done.
He is not cynical at all. Despite a hard life, and he blithely
describes some awful things in his book, and many tragedies such as the
early death, from a rare form of cancer, of his son Kenneth, despite all
that, Kenny McLachlan is ever the optimist. Sometimes I don't know how
or why people like Kenny can still think so well of the world: I wish I
did though.
And yet despite all the commitment and the seriousness and the
hardness of his life and all the tragedies I can tell you this: as Para
Handy said of Hurricane Jeck: ''He has the hert of an innocent child.''
I never met a man held in mair affection. I coulda been a contender.
Kenny was. He won many of his battles. Let's hope he wins in the end,
the decent man.
* ONE GREAT VISION, Memoirs of a Glasgow Worker, by Kenny McLachlan,
#5, obtainable Maryhill Burgh Hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
