<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tighter reins on nanny</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>CHECK OUT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NANNY problems are not something many of us face. Nevertheless it is a
problem for some -- as the recent successful BBC series, Tears Before
Bedtime, revealed. Did you know, for instance, there are more than
100,000 nannies working at any one time in the UK? A recent survey in
Nursery World found that on average a nanny cares for two children under
three years old. Yet, despite the high number of young children cared
for in this way, nannies are the only form of full-time day care for
under eights not required to be registered and, since this January,
nanny agencies are no longer required to be licensed to operate by the
Department of Employment.
Earlier this month saw the launch of Nanny Umbrella, the first attempt
to set standards of care for children looked after in their own home as
well as standards in employment conditions for nannies. The Nanny
Umbrella (whose supporters include training bodies and employment
agencies) wants nannies to be registered under the Children Act like all
other forms of full-time child care.
Nanny Umbrella aims to conduct a feasibility study into this.
Meanwhile it has produced two free leaflets, So You Want To Be A Nanny?
and So You Want To Employ A Nanny? Copies available free (please enclose
sae) from Parents at Work, 77 Holloway Road, London N7 8JZ.
Join the B&amp;B brigade
YOU live in an attractive part of Scotland, better still along one of
the main tourist routes, and you've got a spare bedroom. Maybe you've
toyed with the idea of doing a bit of B&amp;B but hesitated. What are the
snags? Can you turn people away because you don't like the look of them?
These and many more questions will be answered in a two-day training
seminar, Setting Up a Bed and Breakfast Business, on March 6 and 7 in
Callander.
Organised by the Loch Lomond, Stirling and Trossachs Tourist Board, it
costs #20 but could turn out to be a very worthwhile investment. For
those who already run a B&amp;B and want to polish up their skills and
increase their profits there is another two-day seminar, also #20, in
Bridge of Allan (March 20 and 21). Ring Loch Lomond, Stirling and
Trossachs Tourist Board (0786) 470945 for details.
Time-served helpers
WANTED: older people, at least 50-plus, for community work. Well, you
don't often see adverts like that these days do you? So what's the
catch? Yes, you've guessed: it's voluntary work. But that's not to
denigrate it. In fact older people have many skills to offer, and often
an interesting job, along with an opportunity to contribute still to the
community, is more important than financial reward.
Now the RSVP, Retired and Senior Volunteer Programme, is anxious to
recruit community service volunteers in both Strathclyde and Edinburgh.
Organiser Jack Waddell says the projects vary but provide mainly care
and support for disadvantaged people in these areas. ''The demand for
our services is increasing all the time,'' says Mr Waddell. ''We
urgently need more volunteers.''
If you would like to help, contact Jack Waddell, 37 Berwick Drive,
Cardonald, Glasgow (041) 882 7097.
On the badger trail
YOU could spend this Sunday morning lounging in bed with the papers.
Or you could dress up in your winter woollies, walking boots, and join
several dozen others for a brisk walk looking for badger trails, weasels
or winter birds.
Drumpellier Country Park is organising a walk at 10am on Sunday from
the visitor centre. Further information from the Ranger Service,
Townhead Road, Coatbridge (01236) 422257.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
