<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's no wonder we're down at heel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
One thing is guaranteed to make parents hopping mad -- the cost of
children's shoes. So much so we are buying fewer pairs, and making do
and mending more. Deedee Cuddihy looks at the reasons.
IF YOU want to see a group of parents spring to life, mention
children's shoes. The subject can excite even more comment and
controversy than computer games or junk food.
Most of us have an opinion on them -- and it's often a bad one. ''Too
expensive'', ''trainers are just a con'', and ''they were done within a
fortnight'' are the kinds of expressions you'll hear when children's
footwear is brought up for discussion.
Most of the dissatisfaction stems from the fact that although you can
pay adult prices -- and more -- for kids' shoes, a pair may be outgrown
within a matter of weeks despite assurances from some specialists that,
properly fitted, they should be roomy enough to last at least three
months.
''Well, yes,'' admitted Clive Chance, shoeshop owner and British
chairman of the Children's Foot Health Register. ''You can get a sudden
growth spurt shortly after shoes have been bought and, frankly, there's
nothing that can be done about it.''
In other words, there's no way the retailers -- having previously
boasted that they are experts in their field and that all staff, even
the 16-year-olds, are fully trained and, therefore, know a lot more
about your child's feet than you do -- are going to admit liability.
You'll just have to pass these nearly-new shoes on to a lucky friend and
stump up for another pair.
A spokesman for Strathclyde Regional Council's consumer and trading
standards department revealed that shoes, both children's and adults,
were among their top 10 most complained-about items. Disgruntled
shoppers willingly left more than 600 pairs of unsatisfactory shoes with
the department last year to be tested by independent experts.
But retailers like Clive Chance maintain that if consumers stuck to
proper shoe shops such as Clarks and Start-Rite where children's
footwear is fitted by an assistant, rather than relying on the
do-it-yourself method at, for instance, Marks &amp; Spencer and BhS, we
would have less to complain about.
It's an argument that is not borne out by a recent report from the
Consumers' Association which found that there was little difference in
fit between cheaper children's shoes bought off the shelf and more
expensive ones sold by trained staff.
During the investigation, families were sent out to buy shoes from
Clarks or Start-Rite as well as stores like M &amp; S. The children and the
shoes were then examined by a leading foot surgeon and an expert shoe
fitter. They discovered that of nine pairs of Start-Rite shoes, four
were a bad fit, five could have been better, and none was good. Out of
16 pairs of Clarks, two were badly fitted, nine were good, and five
could have been better. Of 16 pairs bought off the shelf, four fitted
badly, seven were good, and five could have been better.
The report concluded that although you will get advice and help from
shops selling Clarks or Start-Rite shoes, you won't necessarily end up
with a better fit.
In addition, the report gave the thumbs-up (or should that be the
toes-up?) to trainers, provided they are leather, because they cushion
the feet and have light, flexible soles.
All of which was bad news for Clarks, which although it came out
slightly ahead of the off-the-shelf product and way ahead of the company
which carries a royal warrant, subsequently announced the closure of one
of its children's footwear factories with the loss of 360 jobs. A
spokesman blamed the closure on a decline in demand in the UK for
children's shoes -- sales have fallen from 69.07 million in 1988 to
55.83 million in 1993.
I talked to another Clarks spokesperson at the company's headquarters
in Somerset who maintained that while overall sales of children's shoes
in the UK were down, the company's own share of the market had remained
the same.
The Clarks empire comprises, as well as factories, 700 shops including
Ravel, Kay Shoes, and Bayne &amp; Duckett. Eighty per cent of the footwear
it sells is still made in the UK, although the company, which celebrates
its 170th birthday this year, admitted it was finding it increasingly
difficult to resist the pressure to have more shoes made abroad, where
overheads were smaller.
''Families have less money to spend now,'' said their spokesman. ''And
they're buying fewer pairs of shoes. Where once a child would have a
pair of school shoes and another pair for parties, many parents are
making do with only one general purpose style which they're more
inclined to repair than in the recent past.''
Even Molly Weir, for whom, famously, ''Shoes Were For Sunday'', had
boots during the week, patent leather lace-ups for best, and a new pair
of gutties at the end of June.
Although it's said that fewer pairs of children's shoes are being
bought in the UK, more companies are fighting for a share of the market.
Hush Puppies has recently introduced a junior range which costs about
the same as Clarks but seems to have the edge in style and colour.
Clarks maintains that its fitting technique is superior -- but will the
customer notice? Certainly the company's heyday, when virtually every
child knew that summer had come because they were fitted with a pair of
Clarks sandals, has long gone.
Increasingly, mums are buying children's shoes in the non-specialist
high street stores where prices are considerably cheaper -- often
because the shoes have been made in Third World countries -- and to the
relief of many, there isn't an interfering assistant hovering around
telling you that your child has ''awfully broad feet, hasn't she''?
Clarks isn't the only British company to have been affected by changes
in the UK children's footwear market. Earlier this month, Chatterbox
Shoes near Leicester announced it was to close its last remaining
factory with the loss of 95 jobs because of ''competition from cheap
imports''. Until five years ago the company, which was set up in 1921,
employed 180 people and made 20,000 pairs of shoes a week.
Of course, what really pulled the rug from under the British shoe
trade was the trainer -- invariably imported from abroad but, during the
''trainer boom'' of the eighties, never cheap.
Parents, already struggling to pay for an ordinary leather lace-up of
the home-grown variety, were aghast when besotted offspring expected
them to fork out #60 and more for a jumped-up gym shoe that had been
manufactured in the Far East for the equivalent, in many cases, of a
bowl of rice.
Alan Cork, editor of the London-based trade magazine Shoe and Leather
News, wryly explained that the big sports shoe companies needed to
charge a lot for their trainers because the cost of promoting them was
so enormous!
He believes, however, that the trainer boom is now over -- and for
evidence of that you need look no further than your nearest sports shop
where the venerable Reebok, child size, can now be purchased for as
little as #16.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
