<HEADLINE>Creamery toasts cheese</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LELSEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRIED TASTED</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979812532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Will a new cheese please? Lesley Duncan investigates.
ANEW British cheese was launched nationally this week. In spite of the
demise of the last major new British cheese, the unfortunately named
Lymeswold (a victim of success and production problems rather than
public rejection), its makers have high hopes for it. It's called
Churnton. Its logo shows a whiskered milkman and a boy in short trousers
in front of old-fashioned milk churns. Hence, presumably, the name.
We're in Hovis-style country here, with traditional goodness the
subliminal message.
The Cheese Company, which owns the Lockerbie creamery, sees a gap in
the market for non-cheddar Churnton, which it describes as mild and
fresh-tasting with a distinctive flavour. Handmade in the traditional
way, it has been extensively market-tested. A #3m advertising campaign
is backing it.
But will this cheese please? There were mixed reactions from a random
group of Herald tasters.
Willie, an addict of blue cheese of any description, pronounced it
''soapy''. He also didn't like the name. Jack, in contrast, found it
''quite tasty''. Anne, who usually buys mild cheddar, thought it had ''a
very pleasant taste -- creamy, slightly tangy''. Ann without the ''e''
disapproves of full-fat cheeses anyway, said it reminded her of
Wensleydale, but was much nicer than cheddar.
Roy, whose taste runs to goat's cheese or ''good farm cheddar from
Orkney'', found it ''soft and squidgy'', thought its first taste was
quite nice, but that it faded quite quickly. He did add that his
children would like it. The third Anne's favourite cheeses are Stilton
and the Italian Dolcelatte. ''This tastes very much like rubbery EU
cheddar, she pronounced sternly. ''It's the sort of cheese I find
completely characterless but which my children adore.''
Bob thought Churnton ''slightly chewy'' and ''quite acceptable''.
Keith, who likes Jarlsberg, found it ''a little waxy for my taste; none
the less it's not as bland as it initially appears, with the back-of-the
mouth tang of a more mature cheddar.''
As for me, I too have a penchant for stronger fare, but found that a
finger of Churnton with a crisp bread and a carton of fresh fruit salad
made a very satisfactory desktop lunch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
