<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James McKillop uncovers a sinister force.
FRONT-line troops from a neo-fascist organisation known as Combat 18
were being blamed last night for the mayhem in Dublin.
As much as anything else it was believed to be a staged demonstration
against the framework for peace in Ireland to be made public by the
British and Irish governments next week.
Combat 18 is a force thought to be no more than 200-strong, but one
determined to bring the maximum violence at football matches with
limited risk of arrest to members.
Thereby it hopes to gain the greatest possible publicity for its
cause. It has links with organisations with similar neo-fascist aims in
Europe, especially Germany
It is also said to have a close relationship with loyalist
organisations in Northern Ireland.
Combat explains itself. You have to go through the alphabet to explain
18. One equals ''A'' and eight is ''H''. Ergo, AH is short for Adolf
Hitler.
The explanation comes from Tony Robson, a researcher for the
anti-fascist publication Searchlight. His insight into Nazi involvement
in English football is not disputed by the foremost academic experts on
soccer hooliganism in England.
''There is no question about it,'' Robson said last night. ''We knew
well in advance that Combat 18 were out to cause havoc at this game. So
too did the police intelligence unit. We have had undercover agents
reporting back for some time.''
The Garda Siochana, the Irish police, had been warned well in advance,
he said, and they had been provided with pictures of the ringleaders.
''However, while the Garda were watching obvious routes into Dublin,
the ring leaders were coming in via Belfast and Cork.''
According to Searchlight, there were just over 50 Combat 18 troops at
last night's game, but they were supported by fellow travellers from
Northern Ireland. Once the ringleaders set off the rioting they quickly
fled the scene, according to Mr Robson.
Combat 18 has been in existence for just over two years. The
organisation attempts to goad into violence the hooligan element still
commonplace in English football.
It is known there are cells throughout England that have links with
similar groups in Sweden, Germany, and the United States.
Combat 18 comprises former members of the National Front who now
believe the NFhas become too soft. However, according to intelligence
reports, some members still have connections with the British National
Party.
According to Mr Robson, Combat 18 will travel anywhere in Europe to
cause trouble at football matches. They have been at the heart of
violence at matches in Stockholm, Amsterdam, and Prague.
While the NF was last night distancing itself from the trouble in
Dublin, and probably with some justification on this occasion, there is
no doubt it was their members in the 1970s who were first to introduce
right-wing extreme politics into football matches through violence.
''Sieg Heil'' has long been a greeting between supporters at many
English clubs. The Nazi salute was evident at the height of Wednesday
night's violence.
The English football supporter has long been the pariah of the
football world, and it has been difficult for outsiders to keep tabs on
their activities.
However, the football unit of the police National Criminal
Intelligence Unit has always prided itself on staying one step ahead.
They claim it is largely through their expertise that the violent
scenes demonstrated in Dublin are a rare event in English football
grounds nowadays.
They know the troublemakers, who, as a consequence, tend to stay away
from matches. Cameras inside the grounds have also kept violence to a
minimum. But the police admit they cannot prevent trouble outside
stadiums.
</TEXT>
