<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Political expediency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE front page report (English not afraid of devolution, February 10)
says that in England the constitutional change issue appears to be
''neither a vote-winner nor a vote-loser''. This, of course, has been
the history of this issue in Scotland since its inception.
Edward Heath, Harold Wilson, and James Callaghan all espoused Scottish
devolution as a device of political expediency, not in response to
popular demand. In each case their Scottish votes remained absolutely
static after they had done so.
The issue is kept alive in Scotland today by the speciously dishonest
''75% voted for'' argument based on combining the percentages of the
votes for the Labour Party, the Liberal Democrats, and the SNP in the
1992 General Election.
The Labour and Liberal Democrat component of that vote, the
''pro-devolution'' element, was 52.1% of the total Scottish vote. In
1945, long before the devolution issue had been invented, that combined
vote was 54.4% and it has remained around the 50% mark in every General
Election since then whether devolution has been on the agenda or off the
agenda and whoever has been proposing or opposing it.
To use the 75% argument to imply that there has been electoral swing
to pro-devolution parties is a quite blatant attempt to mislead the
Scottish electorate.
The independence component is easily identified in the vote for the
Scottish National Party. Since 1964, when the Nationalist vote first
showed an increase, the SNP has averaged 15% of the Scottish vote over
nine General Elections with a peak of 30.4% in 1974 and a second, lower
peak of 21.5% in 1992.
It is all there in Scotland's factual electoral tables but in Scotland
today General Election results are regarded as mere aberrations awaiting
correction by the next opinion poll.
If English voters must become embroiled in an issue which comes as low
on their priorities as it does on Scottish priorities, it is to be hoped
for their sakes that the arguments will be conducted with a little more
honesty.
James Scott,
5 Turnberry Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Councillors to view film</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW District Council could ban Oliver Stone's Natural Born Killers
from being shown in the city's cinemas. The licensing committee will
attend a special screening of the controversial movie, which is
scheduled for general release later this month, on Monday.
In the past, the city fathers have banned films like Monty Python's
Life of Brian, The Texas Chainsaw Massacre, and the Australian Nazi
film, Romper Stomper. They will announce their decision shortly after
the viewing.
</TEXT>
