<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour's folly</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is refreshing to read James Scott pouring cold water on the sublime
euphoria of the Nationalists' political dreams and pointing out the
folly of the Labour Party in supporting devolution for Scotland with the
possible additional lunacy of further assemblies in the North of England
(February 11).
Sad it is to see the Labour Party, commanding the greatest polls
advantage over the Tories for decades, handicapping itself with all
sorts of unnecessary devolutionary experiments.
When one adds the unforeseen West Lothian difficulty, and Mr Blair's
coming battle over Clause 4, the hitherto hapless Tories may do better
than even their most staunch supporters could currently envisage a short
while ago.
Allan MacRitchie,
144 Craigpark,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tragi-comedy of Clydeside</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR recent report featured another episode in the tragi-comedy of
Glasgow's yawning gap site between the Kingston Bridge and the old Govan
Ferry.
The combined efforts of all the quangos, agencies, councils, and
Government to disclaim responsibility ensure that the boast of ''miles
better'' does not apply to this notable stretch of Clydeside.
There is certainly an over-simplification in ascribing the current
problems to storm damage. In fact it resulted from a flooded river,
swollen by heavy rainfall and a high tide (though debatable whether it
coincided with highest potential spring tide), and aggravated by the
crass negligence of the human element in the bureaucratic corridors of
supposed control.
For more than 100 years the Clyde has been conducted down a deep
channel on whose man-made banks the city of Glasgow has confidently
built its bridging buttresses and high-rise edifices.
In allowing the river bed to silt up -- now perhaps half the depth
that it was 50 years ago -- it is a racing certainty that the flood
waters will find somewhere else to go.
The Bell's Bridge, Stobcross Quay, the Scottish Exhibition and
Conference Centre, and the aptly-named Moat House Hotel experienced the
consequences in December and no doubt the rodents inhabiting the
derelict garden festival site were similarly afflicted.
In the meantime the Waverley, the last ambassador abroad of the
Clyde's lost steamship pride, is impounded; the pitiful ''one-off''
dredging proposal (not seen as a priority by the GDA) is stuck in the
mud; chunks of Glasgow Green wash down to augment the silt; and the
Neros of assorted bodies fiddle with the legalities.
Ian H Grant,
1 Hillend Road,
Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sex and the Kirk</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I GROANED when I read Ruth Wishart's article (February 13).
If she feels the church is becoming obsessed with sex it is because
the whole nation is obsessed with it to the extent that someone has
surely to say it is wrong.
Certainly the Kirk, as one of the representatives of Christian belief
and practice, has every right to do so, and I for one am glad that it
has a social responsibility convener who is not afraid to speak up.
Of course prostitution has been around almost since time began, but
that doesn't make it OK in the sight of God, and the Kirk would be
failing in its duty if it did not say so.
A big part of the trouble in our country right now is that anything
goes, and to quote from the Bible on how it was when Israel had no-one
to lead them: ''Everyone did what was right in their own eyes'' (Judges
17.6).
When will people realise that while it is necessary to condemn the
sin, the Christian still wants to show God's love to the sinner, if for
no other reason than that we recognise we are sinners ourselves
graciously saved by the grace of God.
Ruth Wishart's final sentence was a disgrace. It was rude, crude, and
extremely distasteful. I sincerely hope she can do better next time.
Rev Jim Murdoch,
5 Ochiltree,
Dunblane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sleeper service</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the question of Anglo-Scottish sleeper services, the best defence
of the status quo must be to press for strengthening the economics of
all these services.
The following suggestions readily come to mind: the Channel Tunnel has
been open for nearly a year and yet through services north of London are
still at least a year away.
Cannot the existing sleeper rolling stock be used with minimum
alteration to provide overnight services to Paris and Brussels as well
as London? This must surely increase demand. With slightly earlier
departure times it should not require additional rolling stock.
Given the number of Scots who take self-drive holidays abroad and the
return trade of tourists from the Continent it seems bizarre that we
should have to drive 450 miles each way to use Le Shuttle. The Motorail
option should be available on all services. However, the price must
stand comparison with the alternative of driving it yourself.
Attractive options for budget-conscious travellers need to be devised,
eg reclining seats with blankets. The channel ferries currently provide
similar options.
Sources of revenue must be diversified so that the overheads of the
service are shared, eg collaboration with the Post Office or courier
services to carry small goods requiring next-day delivery to the
Continent.
P M Walker,
8 Cavendish Drive,
Newton Mearns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opportunity too good to miss</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE proposed development of the former garden festival site as a
pleasure gardens during the next five years represents one of the best
opportunities in Glasgow to create sustainable employment with positive
environmental impacts in the rapidly developing local leisure and world
tourism markets.
These would be genuinely new, permanent jobs, integrating various
disciplines from the arts and sciences with strong emphasis on
education, business, and commerce.
The main visitor attraction would be a range of opportunities to see,
experience, and interact with science, technology, design, and
manufacturing on site -- a walk through the past, present, and into the
future of Glasgow and Scotland.
The design specification must include a sufficiently large structure
to accommodate very large numbers of visitors in inclement weather, also
act as a focus for marketing of the city and be of outstanding
architectural merit.
The site would be made ready for December 31, 1999, when Glasgow, with
these new gardens and this innovative building, would host the largest
Hogmanay celebration ever, not only attracting UK media coverage but
almost certainly worldwide attention.
With a launch of this magnitude, attracting local and international
visitor numbers in excess of 1,500,000 per year would not be difficult.
What other proposed project could offer this opportunity to the commerce
and people of its host city and the Millennium Commission?
Mic Starbuck,
22 Cornwall Avenue,
Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Newspeak</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEORGE ORWELL'S theory in 1984 that the public can be manipulated by
subtle changes in vocabulary is coming true today.
''Joyriders'' are in reality homicidal car thieves, ''moles'' are
dishonest, disloyal employees, ''sleaze'' (not used as a noun in my
dictionary) appears to be moral decadence.
Phrases such as ''the Government must pay for . . .'' are substituted
for the taxpayer must pay. Politicians are described contemptuously as
making U-turns when they have had the courage to try to rectify a
mistake.
The media appears to have taken on the role of Big Brother in
controlling the minds of the public.
F L Paterson,
77 Terregles Street,
Dumfries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A touch of class</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOW that the salaries of company directors are public property it will
be interesting to see if they create a new social hierarchy. It would be
unnatural if money made no difference at all. One has only to think of
Jane Austen, writing in the days when private wealth was also public
knowledge, to recall that characters with #50,000 in the Funds are
treated quite differently from those scraping by on #100 a year. It made
a great difference, however, where the money came from. She may have
been the first novelist to write about the middle class, but she was
snobbish about trade.
These days it is difficult to know where the middle class begins or
ends. A curious dispute has arisen between Miss Rebecca Nicolson and the
College of Heralds over whether her own claim to be middle class is
justified. Of Miss Nicholson's blood-line there is no doubt. ''Two
great-grandfathers were hereditary peers, and her father is heir
presumptive to Lord Carnock, which will give her a shelf in the Hons'
cupboard,'' said a college spokeman. ''She's thoroughly 'U'.'' But even
her father, Nigel Nicolson, son of Sir Harold Nicolson and Vita
Sackville-West, conceded that while he is upper class himself, living at
Sissinghurst Castle, his daughter may have slipped. ''She is three
generations down, and that dissipates things, like with sweet peas,'' he
said.
As a writer, Miss Nicolson could perhaps claim to be classless,
although like auctioneering, estate agenting, and show business, it is a
trade increasingly popular with scions of great families, who use their
connections to write gossip columns. In the old days journalists were
firmly on the bottom rung of society -- grocer's assistants, as one
proprietor put it, writing for other grocer's assistants. They were
badly paid, even on middle-class socialist magazines. One recalls a
young New Statesman sub-editor, being praised for his work by Kingsley
Martin, murmuring that it was hard to survive on #20 a week. ''Good
God!'' Martin replied. ''You mean you haven't got a private income?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScotRail loses a champion</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE resignation of Chris Green, the head of ScotRail, is a big blow to
the business he was managing so well and a blow to its speedy
privatisation. Mr Green was the most able and dynamic force in
Scotland's railways over the past 10 to 15 years. A railwayman through
and through, his commitment was to the most modern and efficient
exploitation and development of the existing systems. He had experience
of the vital but immensely complex commuter traffic in the south-east of
England as well as the mainline InterCity business, which he turned into
a profitable enterprise. In both his drive and success he did much for
the morale of other railway workers. It is impossible to identify any
group in or outside the Scottish railways which will be heartened by his
going, which is some quick measure of his achievement given the way the
business was rarely in the forefront of new investment or expansion: in
fact some expansion in the shape of new stations in central Scotland did
take place under his leadership, a rare development.
Mr Green was a forthright, even bold, exponent of his own ideas and
enthusiasms for ScotRail. He was not ill-disposed to its privatisation
but he disagreed strongly with Government proposals on the best
structures and operating principles for the company assuming that event.
It must be hoped that his strong expression of his opinions, in
particular as expressed to this newspaper, did not contribute to his
going, though it is no secret that some of those involved in the process
of privatisation felt that he was rocking the boat. The privatisation
programme for the railways will go ahead, but it is the most difficult
of all the privatisations (which is why it has lagged so long in the
queue).
So far as Scotland is concerned, the loss of Chris Green will make the
Government's task yet more difficult, though it is unlikely that our
railway will have seen the last of Mr Green.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man falls 30ft</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 67-year-old church elder was seriously injured last night after he
fell about 30ft while cleaning lights in Neilston Parish Church,
Neilston. Mr Walter Tubman, 67, of Main Street, Neilston, was taken to
the Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, where he is in a coma with
serious head and body injuries.
</TEXT>
