<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The game's the thing no more</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEDNESDAY'S ugly scenes in Dublin may have damaged England's chances
of hosting the European football championships next year. But the yobs
whose conduct aborted the friendly international are not representative
of English football fans. Indeed, an apposite question is how far
football is their game at all. Their behaviour seemed premeditated and
organised rather than spontaneous and random. It had an unmistakable
political flavour though it might be too much to see in it any conscious
involvement in the affairs of Ulster -- a demonstration of solidarity
with the Unionists or a considered display of contempt for the Irish.
Its very right-wing content (the Nazi style salutes, for example) may
locate the participants in, or on the fringes of, the National Front.
Their hatred may be more generalised than focused, though its English
nationalist element cannot be denied even if it stems less from
confidence, which needs no shrill or savage expression, than a sense of
insecurity.
The Irish police were caught off guard, but they reacted firmly and
took the right decision to call off the game. No-one here will condemn
them: the record of spectator sport in Ireland is remarkably devoid of
violence. And the warnings they had received were not ignored -- there
was a substantial police presence at the game, which was just as well.
Even though the yobs were relatively few in number, crowd behaviour is
seldom predictable. Something even worse could have developed had there
been retaliatory or copy-cat responses. What transpired was utterly
disgraceful, but it was contained before it claimed many casualties,
never mind lives.
Recent events in Italy and France, and even here in Scotland, should
qualify the notion that football hooliganism is an English monopoly. The
political dimension is peculiar to the English version but the
composition of the yobs, affluent and often intelligent young men, is
similar in various parts of Europe. This sociological identity demands a
more complex explanation than that of frustrated political expression,
though that is a phenomenon with a disturbing potential. Meanwhile
football has become far more competitively intense than it was even a
generation ago. ''The game's the thing'' has given way to the assumption
of victory at all costs. The age composition of the crowd may have
changed as well, with the moderating influence of older men being lost
to the television screens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
