<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff Principal decides that anti-social Grahams must give up home in Glenrothes. Family lose fight against eviction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Graham family of Glenrothes yesterday lost their appeal against an
eviction order from their home.
A ruling that Glenrothes Development Corporation could repossess the
home in Alexander Road was upheld.
The decision was conveyed to Mrs Anne Graham, 35, and her husband,
Gordon, 39, by Sheriff Principal John J. Maguire of Tayside, Central,
and Fife, after a brief hearing at Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court.
It came in a morning of bizarre events which saw Mrs Graham's lawyer,
Mr James Bauld, departing from the case after stating he had given her
advice, but received no clear instructions.
The couple were then left with no legal representation, as Mr Graham's
lawyers had written to the court earlier this month stating they were
withdrawing and pointing out he had no legal aid.
Sheriff Principal Maguire was asked by the Grahams to continue the
case, allowing them time to prepare their own defence, but this was
opposed by counsel for the corporation, Mr James Peoples, QC, who stated
that they had already been given ample time and the matter had been
affected by delays and legal walk-outs.
The Sheriff Principal refused the couple's plea.
Following a brief adjournment, during which Mr and Mrs Graham were
huddled in conversation in the court foyer, Mrs Graham failed to return
to court -- and her husband told the Sheriff Principal he had no
instructions on her behalf.
While he was not abandoning his own appeal, he then said he had no
submissions to make.
Mr Peoples was told by Sheriff Principal Maguire he did not require to
make any submissions other than to move for the appeal to be refused.
Ruling that Mrs Graham had seen fit to depart, she could be deemed to
have abandoned her appeal, he said.
The Sheriff Principal then rejected her husband's appeal and awarded
expenses, still to be determined, against the couple.
He told the court: ''Lest it be thought that the appropriate image in
this case is of a little man defending his rights against a faceless and
amorphous corporation, it has to be borne in mind that justice is a
two-edged sword and while the corporation may be large, it is entitled
to justice as much as the little man.''
He added that having read Sheriff Gail Patrick's lengthy stated case
on last year's eviction hearing ''it would seem to me to be difficult
for anyone to argue that the sheriff was unreasonable to come to the
view she did''.
In any case, no submissions to that effect had been made to him, and
he would therefore refuse the appeal.
No eviction attempt is likely to be made for at least a month until
expenses in the case have been finalised. However, Mr Graham could
appeal to the Court of Session if granted permission to do so by the
Sheriff Principal.
He left the court refusing to comment, joining his wife in the
family's van before driving off.
During last year's eviction action, raised by the corporation on the
grounds that the Grahams had breached their tenancy agreement and were
involved in persistent anti-social behaviour, it was claimed residents
of Alexander Road had suffered years of misery at the hands of some of
the family.
It was told that sheriff officers who attempted to carry out a
previous eviction for rent arrears had been pelted by metal objects and
excrement, and the door handle of the barricaded house had been
electrified.
Ruling that the couple could be evicted, Sheriff Patrick found the
family had shown a total disregard of the conditions of tenancy.
In her judgment, she added that the evidence disclosed a lengthy
history of persistent and serious anti-social conduct by Mr Graham and
his sons over a period of many years, adding that she had taken account
of the fact that this conduct was deliberate, resulting in considerable
distress to many people from tiny children to the elderly, all of whom
had done nothing to attract the unwelcome attentions of the Graham
family.
A spokesman for the corporation said: ''As this case has not yet been
finalised we are making no official comment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Evil new strain of bulldog breed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With help from the experts, Kirsty Scott examines the mind of the
English thug and how it differs from his Scottish counterpart.
BEHIND the deadened eyes, curled fists, and flailing feet, the English
football hooligan is driven by a deeply ingrained racial hatred and a
culture of violence surrounding the game, according to behavioural
experts.
Psychological profiles of the typical thug generally come up with the
same print-out: male, working class, low achiever, right-wing,
pack-minded, and dependent on the support of others for social status.
Rogan Taylor of Liverpool University's Football Research Unit has
studied the culture of football violence for a number of years.
He believes the kind of behaviour that erupted on Wednesday night at
Lansdowne Road is part of a wider malaise of xenophobia and violence
that affects England as a country and is being exploited in the stadiums
by the far-right.
Taylor said: ''This kind of thing runs very deeply in English society;
not British, but English society. We saw in Dublin what was a rather big
eruption, but it's something that goes on every day in every town and
city in the country.
''It's not about the way people behave at football matches; it's about
the way people behave, full stop.
''At Lansdowne Road I think we saw a game hijacked for political
reasons by a reasonably well-organised group of 40 or 50 people. It's
like dry tinder. You flash a spark and off it goes. It's an awful cycle
and a vicious cycle.
''When it goes off, children get hurt and upset and the police get
very, very angry. That drives on the English fans, who may have fascists
whispering in their ears.''
Taylor said that in general the English, from MPs through to ordinary
members of the public, could be ''very disparaging about Johnny
foreigner.''
Standing back from the Dublin incident, he said, the behaviour of some
of the fans mirrored that which might have been seen as positive during
the days of the British Empire.
''If you were up the Khyber Pass in the nineteenth century you would
want these people with you because they fight shoulder to shoulder . . .
these are the qualities that built the British Empire in a different
context and in different circumstances.
''When you stand among people like this you realise you are witnessing
something that in other circumstances and other contexts would be seen
as the bulldog spirit, the Briton standing alone. Here, it is on the
playing field; anarchic, destructive, but nonetheless attracting the
attention of the world.''
However, Professor James Mangan, director for the International Centre
for Socialisation and Sport at Strathclyde University, does not believe
that xenophobia was the root for the problem.
The professor, who staged a conference on football violence in
conjunction with the World Cup last year, said hooliganism was a
phenomenon of Western Europe and happened at all levels of the game.
''I would have thought we should look to expressions of misguided
masculinity and demonstrations of perverted self-esteem . . . in
situations that bring maximum visibility.
''I think that's more significant. I don't know how much nationalism
has to do with it. Remember this takes place within nations as well as
at local football grounds.''
According to Glasgow University sociologist Bert Moorhouse, Scotland
has not suffered from football hooliganism to the same extent as England
because Scots do not consider themselves to be superior to the rest of
the world.
He said: ''I don't think the Scots have ever had the same relation to
right-wing ideology or to that kind of English superiority.
''Scots are more inclined to think of themselves as one of the
oppressed races, rather than a superior race. I think there is something
in English culture in particular that sets itself up as superior.''
Moorhouse said people should not be too surprised at the outbreak of
violence at the Irish match, because it had become part of the game.
''I think violence around English football games has become part of
the tradition of football. It's become kind of accepted. There is
nothing unusual in it.
''There is violence all through the game of football; managers
screaming on the sidelines, refereees being questioned at every
decision, Eric Cantona jumping at people with double-foot tackles. There
is violence at all levels of football -- I think it's probably endemic
now. It is part of the tradition.''
Looking ahead to next year's European Championships, Moorhouse said he
had always thought staging the event in England would be dangerous.
''What happened last night will be a calling card. It will send a
message out to various groups on the Continent . . . I always thought
there was likely to be violence and I see no reason to change that
opinion now . . . where England go, violence will follow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots must stay on the alert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New image could easily slip back, as Ken Smith found out from players'
chief.
WHILE Scots wallowed in the schadenfreude of watching English football
yobs embarrass their country yet again, Tony Higgins, secretary of the
Scottish Professional Footballers Association, warned: ''We cannot rest
on our laurels in Scotland.''
Football hooliganism has been curbed considerably in Scotland since
1980, when the Criminal Justice Act halted the taking of alcohol into
grounds and also stopped overtly drunk people from being admitted. Then
came the Taylor Report, which is turning premier league grounds into
all-seated stadiums, thus diminishing the mob instinct of thousands of
fans all standing and swaying together.
Better stewarding and policing of grounds, and the attraction of more
women and children to matches, has also helped. But there are concerns
that the extra security measures may be moving some of the violence out
into the streets.
The cosy assumption that all was well in Scottish football was shaken
earlier this month when there were 44 arrests in Glasgow's Gallowgate
after Dundee United supporters clashed with Rangers fans. It is believed
a busload of supporters from Dundee arrived too late for the match at
Ibrox and went drinking instead. Fights broke out, with witnesses
claiming knives, sticks, and coshes were brandished.
The previous month, 41 people were arrested in Auchterarder when
supporters of junior club Lochee United, returning from a cup-tie,
confronted Motherwell supporters on their way home from a match in
Dundee. The rival fans clashed in a pub car park in the small town.
Higgins says we must be ''very vigilant'' in Scotland. Although the
image of the game has been cleaned up to a great degree, it is something
that has to be constantly worked at, he says, otherwise it could easily
slip back.
Perhaps the biggest difference between Scotland and England has been
the rise of extremist right-wing groups in England who use football
grounds as recruiting areas and places to plan the occasional ruckus.
They play on fears of unemployment among the largely white, working
class supporters, and try to convince them that immigration is to blame
for their situation.
Although the British National Party, and before that the National
Front, made attempts to recruit at Ibrox, they appeared to have little
effect. No doubt Scots still blame the Tory Government for most of their
ills, rather than persecuting minorities.
But as Higgins points out, the level of racial incidents is rising in
Scotland, so it cannot be assumed that it will not find a home at
Scottish football grounds. His own association has worked closely with
the Campaign for Racial Equality to campaign against racism in football.
At Ibrox, operations executive Alistair Hood said groups such as the
NF had had little effect, and were kept as far as possible from the
environs of the ground.
It is inside Ibrox where the reduction in violence is most marked.
Having fans seated has greatly reduced the sheer pack mentality of
people who may have embraced trouble in the past. But Hood also praises
the responsible attitude of the fans themselves, and his new weapon of
advanced technology.
''The vast majority of fans are not prepared to tolerate misbehaviour.
I will get at least half a dozen phone calls after a match from people
who report their fellow supporters for behaviour that is not
acceptable,'' he explained.
''With 34,000 of the 47,000 attending holding season tickets, it is
easy to identify the seat they were sitting in. I can key it up in the
computer, get their address, and tell them to come in and see me.''
In his eight years at Ibrox, Hood has had about 300 such ''chats.''
Most are for very minor misdemeanours, and a warning suffices. In more
serious cases, Rangers as a club are willing to take a holder's season
ticket away.
''No fan wants to lose his season ticket,'' Hood said. ''Some have
told me they would rather go to prison than lose their season ticket
book.''
It is outside the ground that Rangers have no jurisdiction. Hood said,
however, that some isolated incidents of violence are caused by
''hardened criminals'' who may wear a football top or scarf, but have no
intention of even going to a game. He cited trouble at Slateford in
Edinburgh when there was a battle between youths with Rangers colours
and those with the green of Hibernian. ''It had nothing to do with
football,'' he said. ''None of them had tickets for the game.''
At international level, Scotland basks in the glow of winning awards
for the friendliness of its fans abroad. This may be due to what could
be called the Andy Roxburgh Effect, and now the Craig Brown Effect.
Recent Scotland managers have done little to light the passions of the
fans, who now travel more to enjoy themselves than expecting a win.
SFA security adviser David McLaren explained that they are the only
source for tickets in Scotland and sell only to members of the Scotland
Travel Club -- although they cannot stop fans buying tickets locally.
Each foreign game involves a fair amount of pre-planning, with
officials going out six weeks earlier to discuss security with local
police and stadium officials. Even the places where buses can park are
worked out so that fans have the shortest distance to walk to get to
their seats.
''The Scots fans, like the Irish, want to enjoy themselves, maybe have
a drink with their pals. It's perhaps just a cultural thing,'' McLaren
said.
''They don't seem to have any political affiliation, which can happen
in England. If there's any trouble, it usually emanates from too much
drink. But there are very few arrests. There were 18,000 Scots fans in
Italy for the World Cup in 1990 and there was only one arrest.''
At a police level, there is no Scottish equivalent of the National
Football Intelligence Unit in England. Instead, the Scottish forces
exchange information on known troublemakers, but there is no need
identified for a central register of such people.
The Association of Chief Police Officers in Scotland does have a
football sub-committee which discusses the policing of football grounds,
and it intends to liaise with the National Football Intelligence Unit if
Scotland qualifies for the European Championships in England.
It seems that Scots can take some pride in their behaviour. But all
the authorities are aware that it can take only one incident to drag
Scotland down to the level of England.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
