<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tories lose deposit in by-election</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR last night comfortably retained the rock solid seat of Islwyn
in South Wales -- with the Tories losing their deposit in a humiliating
fourth place.
Mr Don Touhig romped home ahead of the Plaid Cymru candidate, Ms
Jocelyn Davies, in the by-election caused by the decision of former
party leader Neil Kinnock to stand down to become a European
Commissioner.
The Liberal Democrat, Mr John Bushell, was third and the Conservative,
Mr Robert Buckland, trailed in a poor fourth, dropping from second place
at the General Election.
Labour's margin of victory was 11,631 down on its majority of 24,728
at the last General Election.
However, with a low turnout of just over 45% -- caused by appalling
weather and a widespread feeling that the result was a foregone
conclusion -- Labour is unlikely to be too concerned.
Reslts: Don Touhig (Lab) 16,030 (69.20%, -5.06%), Ms Jocelyn Davies
(PC) 2933 (12.66%, +8.73%), John Bushell (Lib Dem) 2448 (10.57%,
+4.92%), Robert Buckland (Con) 913 (3.94%, -10.91%). Labour majority
13,097.
</TEXT>
