<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Error of judgment blamed for circus acrobat's death</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN acrobat told an inquest yesterday how he had watched his partner
plunge to his death before a horrified audience.
Wheel of Death performer Neville Campbell, 20, died after breaking his
wrists, blacking out, and falling 15ft head first to the ground at
Blackpool Tower Circus.
An inquest jury in Blackpool, Lancashire, returned an accident
verdict.
''The accident occurred purely as a result of an error of judgment by
Neville, despite his vast amount of experience on the apparatus,'' his
partner, New Zealander Bryan Donaldson, told the hearing.
The two men were performing on the equipment before a 600-strong
Boxing Day audience.
Both were doing tricks inside and outside two stainless steel
cylinders revolving around a central axle supported by stanchions.
''Neville lost his footing. It is imperative that the artiste
maintains his position in the centre of the wheel but he was slightly
too far forward,'' Mr Donaldson told the jury of three women and five
men.
''As he stumbled, he went to grab hold of the central stanchions and
he must have struck both his wrists on the stanchions.
''I saw his wrists go limp. I slowed the wheels the best I could.
Neville retained his balance. He went forward as if to get off the
wheel.
''His chest went against the wheel. He went to get hold of the
stanchions but as he did so his wrists seemed to give way.''
A doctor in the audience found Mr Campbell still breathing but
unconscious. He died shortly afterwards despite resuscitation attempts.
Dr Karen Carr, of Cheltenham, Gloucestershire, told the inquest she
had been watching the show with her family when the accident happened.
''My impression was that he was either unconscious when he fell or in
the process of fainting.''
Ringmaster Harvey Sagar told how the two acrobats had moments earlier
gone faultlessly through their routines.
A pathologist established that Mr Campbell died from multiple
injuries, including a broken neck.
Coroner Samuel Lee said Mr Campbell, of Trentham, Stoke-on-Trent,
Staffordshire, had lost consciousness: ''That is why he could not put
his hands forward to break his fall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NHS trust in throes of power struggle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POWER struggle between a chief executive and some of her top medical
consultants has been blamed for an unprecedented spate of departures
which has plunged an NHS trust into crisis.
The Moray MP, Mrs Margaret Ewing, is demanding an inquiry into the
conflict which has led to the resignation of the chief executive and two
non-executive directors from Moray Health Services Trust.
Yesterday afternoon, trust chairman Jim Snedden was summoned to a
meeting in Edinburgh with the NHS chief executive in Scotland, Mr Geoff
Scaife, to explain the situation.
Chief executive Elizabeth Hogg quit her #45,000-a-year post 10 days
ago, and was followed by non-executive directors Willie Phillips and Mrs
Marjory Adams.
A source at Dr Gray's Hospital in Elgin alleged yesterday that a rift
between Mrs Hogg and the senior medical team at the hospital was behind
the row. The source claimed that the issue had come to a head after a
series of disagreements culminated in Mrs Hogg asking for the
resignation of her medical director, Dr Brian Heap.
In the flurry of meetings which followed, Mrs Hogg allegedly offered
to go. But the six non-executive directors of the NHS board unanimously
agreed to ask her to stay.
Mr Snedden and his deputy, Jim Royan, are then said to have met
hospital consultants and ''were left in no doubt'' of their feelings.
''It was not the first meeting the consultants had had with the
chairman to express their concerns,'' the source said.
Mrs Hogg later asked Mr Snedden if she could withdraw her resignation,
but he is alleged to have refused, then recommended it to the next board
meeting, at which only three non-executive directors supported Mrs Hogg.
Dr Heap, who remains as medical director, joined the trust last April
-- taking over from GP Ron Stewart, who quit after only a year in the
job.
When it was put to Dr Stewart that the clash between the medics and
Mrs Hogg was either one of policy or management, he said: ''The policy
has been in place for a long time. You can make your own deductions
about the rest.''
Mrs Hogg was the first woman to be appointed chief executive of a NHS
trust in Scotland and took up the post two years ago. Since resigning,
she has refused to speak publicly.
Mr Phillips, managing director of the Macallan Distillery on Speyside,
has also declined to comment.
But Mrs Lydia King, of Dunbar Street, Lossiemouth, a non-executive
director who supported Mrs Hogg at the board meeting, said she was
scared the affair might damage the trust's reputation.
''A damage limitation exercise is going on at the moment and the time
might come when we have to put our cards on the table -- if only to
protect one person,'' she added.
Conal Smith, chairman of Moray Trades Council, said he was perturbed
by the wall of silence the trust had put up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Victorian city of dreadful night</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Michael Fry turns the pages of a new history of Glasgow
AGLASWEGIAN who takes a dim view of his birthplace may be a
contradiction in terms. But one clergyman preaching in 1757 had no doubt
that the city, so far from flourishing, ''seems to be fast ripening for
a stroak''. He saw signs in the rise of swearing, sabbath-breaking,
public drunkenness, and general irreligion -- in other words, of the
Glasgow we know and love.
His sermon harked back to another Glasgow. This was a city famed for
its prettiness, for the cleanly elegant lines of its towers which rose
amid verdant gardens and orchards by the sparkling Clyde, set off
against the sombre Highlands. It was also famed for its Presbyterianism,
standing as it did in the heart of Covenanting country, its people given
to religion of ''a gloomy, enthusiastical cast'', doubting not that the
dogmas for which their fathers suffered were true.
If hardly a cheerful picture, it must have seemed to the minister's
congregation a fortunate one, because it was blessed with prosperity.
But he did well to point out that it was darkening. By the time this
volume* brings its portion of the city's story to a close, eight decades
later, the prosperity was prodigious, but it also fed on a human
degradation which would have shocked Glaswegians of the previous age.
The most enthralling chapters are the ones which chart this transition
from the brisk and bracing Glasgow of the eighteenth century to what was
already in potential a Victorian city of dreadful night, though much
gold gleamed through the gloom.
There is an especially elegant and persuasive essay from Roy Campbell
on how commerce led to industry, and how a city became a region, in a
unique formula for success which combined a vast manufacturing nexus in
the hinterland with a still vaster trading network in the world beyond.
If the economic analysis is the book's central thread, other aspects
are not neglected. Irene Maver performs sterling work in rescuing the
political history of the city, which has otherwise been almost entirely
ignored. It is essentially a story of how the sort of people in charge
as Glasgow's ascent started, a rich merchant clique, stayed in charge
through the resulting changes. Even the liberal reforms of the 1830s did
not dislodge them: they just swopped party rather than personnel, let
alone principle.
Richard Sher's fine article does two things. It defines the Glaswegian
Enlightenment, both its intrinsic nature and its relation to the wider
movement of ideas in Scotland. Thus, for example, we find much more
stress on the classics in Glasgow than in Edinburgh, which tended to cut
them down to size as merely one stage among several in intellectual
history. We also find unusual emphasis on the fine arts, as in the
Foulis brothers' beautiful editions of the ancient authors.
Sher brings out better than most of his fellow contributors the
resilience into the industrial age of that older Glasgow, and of its
blunt, Presbyterian plain-speaking.
The merchants, if rolling in money, bothered little with politeness,
in either our or their sense. They greeted a speech at a public meeting
by Professor John Millar, today revered as the father of sociology,
''with snipes and vulgar laughs of contempt''. One was so philistine as
to suggest that the university's endowment should be transferred to the
chamber of commerce.
And they found, as would never have happened in Edinburgh,
intellectual soul-mates, such as the crabbit professor of natural
philosophy, John Anderson. He so despised his precious academic
colleagues that he set up what he called ''anti-toga classes'' to teach
the students something useful.
His desire for vengeance stretched beyond the grave. He left his
estate to establish a rival institution, specifying that ''no person
connected with the college or university of Glasgow can be connected
with Anderson's University'' -- which has today become Strathclyde
University.
How far all this reflected what might be called the Glaswegian spirit
is something the volume as a whole could have explored more fully. One
outburst of truly popular feeling came in 1778 when Glaswegians rioted
against, and forced withdrawal of, a parliamentary Bill for mild relief
of the penal laws against Roman Catholics.
In the 1790s they remained studiously unimpressed by the fancy French
ideas behind the democratic agitation in other Scottish cities, but
proclaimed their loyalty to king and country.
It is surprising, in the history of a city which habitually glorifies
the proletariat, to find so little attention paid to the mind of the
people except, in Christopher Whatley's piece, in their role primarily
as economic agents. It would have been especially interesting because
the mind of the people seems to have remained rather bigoted and
reactionary.
But that is in line with the general tone of the work, which is
somewhat austere, stressing the impersonal historical forces at work,
and so lacking a little in colour, even when there are kenspeckle
figures such as Kirkman Finlay and Thomas Chalmers available. Still,
with 230,000 words of text, one cannot complain at the richness of the
material, nor at the high standard of production, though this is matched
by the price. Perhaps the next volume in the series of three, with the
heights and depths of Victorian society to range over, will give us a
more pungent flavour of the city.
*Tom Devine &amp; Gordon Jackson (eds.): Glasgow, volume 1, Beginnings to
1830, #60; Manchester University Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
