<DOCNO>GH950217-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Praise for Scots police who caught shotgun killer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS police were praised yesterday for their role in capturing
shotgun killer Colin Middleton, who was jailed for life yesterday.
Toolmaker Middleton -- who killed his former manager Terry Maidens,
34, as he watched television with his family -- smiled yesterday as he
was found guilty of murder at Birmingham Crown Court.
After the trial, the officer who helped lead the hunt for Middleton
praised the work of Central and Tayside Police.
Detective Chief Inspector Steve Hussey, of Warwickshire Police, said
three Scots officers had shown great courage in apprehending Middleton,
41, in the Craigvrack Hotel in Pitlochry in January 1994.
He said particular credit should go to the Perth police officers who
ended the manhunt by tackling the fugitive after a tip from a lorry
driver who had driven Middleton from Stirling to Pitlochry.
The court heard Middleton had called at Mr Maidens's home and was let
in by his wife, Katherine, 27, who thought he was a pizza delivery man.
He then shot Mr Maidens at point blank range. He died instantly.
During the week-long trial Mr Timothy Raggatt, QC, prosecuting, had
described how Middleton had become obsessed with Mr Maidens. He claimed
Middleton planned Mr Maidens's death after they clashed while working at
Linpac Mouldings in Witton, Birmingham.
Middleton was particularly enraged when he was moved to day shifts,
and suffered a small loss of wages.
The clash came to a head when Mr Maidens reported Middleton for
kicking a factory door on November 9, 1993.
Middleton went off sick -- severing all connection with the firm until
he arrived at Mr Maidens's home on January 26 last year.
After the murder Middleton fled to Cheshire and then north to
Scotland. After a tip-off, three detective constables based at Perth,
Shonagh Boyle, 28, Colin Lorimer, 35, and Greig Steele, 28, managed to
overpower Middleton in the Pitlochry hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tribunal rejects woman's claims against former boss</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PEST-CONTROL surveyor who claimed she was sacked after she rejected
her employer's amorous advances has lost her claim of unfair dismissal.
Miss Jane Vigurs, 37, from Stonehaven, claimed she was dismissed
because she spurned Mr Iain Lawson, a partner with Aberpest of Aberdeen
and a member of the SNP's national executive committee.
Mr Lawson denied he had made any amorous advances.
The Aberdeen tribunal was told Miss Vigurs was dismissed because of
her poor sales record and her attitude towards colleagues. The firm
claimed she had become unreliable and abusive.
Miss Vigurs claimed that eight months before her dismissal Mr Lawson
-- also of Pest Protection Services in Paisley -- had asked her if she
was interested in a sales job. She was interviewed by Mr Lawson's
business partner, Mr Peter Stewart, and it was agreed she'd work from
home.
Several months later sales declined and she stopped earning
commission. She was then off work for hospital treatment and when she
returned told Mr Stewart she was unable to call on customers because she
had no money for petrol.
The tribunal heard Miss Vigurs was paid a monthly float for expenses
and, it was claimed, had been sent money a few days earlier. She later
phoned demanding commission for a sale which, the tribunal heard, had
not been completed, and was sacked after she became abusive towards Mr
Lawson.
Miss Vigurs, of Provost Barclay Drive, Stonehaven, denied she had been
abusive. She admitted calling Mr Lawson ''a bastard'' after she was
dismissed.
She alleged the real reason for her sacking was because she rejected
his advances.
The tribunal said there was ample evidence to suggest the reason for
Miss Vigurs's dismissal was not the conduct she alleged against Mr
Lawson and there was no evidence to suggest it was.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hollywood helps with tourism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOLLYWOOD stars are supporting Scotland in a way that could be worth
millions of pounds to the tourist industry, it was claimed yesterday.
The Scottish Tourist Board said Scotland had never been promoted
worldwide on such a scale as a result of four films, shot in the
country, being marketed and released.
The STB, which has just published its overseas guide in seven
languages, says it is standing by for an influx of visitors in the wake
of the country's scenery and imagery being seen by millions of
cinema-goers around the world.
Rob Roy, starring Liam Neeson and Jessica Lange, opens around the
world this spring. It will be followed by Braveheart with Mel Gibson,
Mary Reilly starring Julia Roberts, and Loch Ness with Ted Danson.
The STB's chief executive, Mr Derek Reid, said the marketing budget
for Rob Roy alone was more than $20m.
''We are doing what we can to convert the interest in Scotland that
will follow into tourism trips,'' said Mr Reid.
The industry is worth #2000m annually and provides 170,000 jobs in
Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coal workers offered a share of the future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL CAVEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES of the newly formed Scottish Coal Company Ltd were invited
yesterday to dig deep into their pockets and invest in their future.
About 1000 staff based at the Longannet deep mine, nine open-cast
sites, and the company headquarters in Edinburgh, have been given the
chance to take part in a share-purchase scheme.
Backed by all unions, it allows workers to buy a 12% stake in their
company. Employees can buy a minimum of 1000 #1 shares. The maximum per
employee is 20,000 shares. Staff will also receive a number of free
shares, thought to be around 200.
To encourage the workforce to participate in the venture, an unnamed
Scottish bank will offer personal loans at substantially reduced rates.
Throughout the coming month, senior company personnel, including Dr
Ian Preston, chairman-designate, trade union representatives, bank
staff, and Unity Corporate Advisers Ltd, an independent company brought
in to assist with the scheme, will outline the share-purchase proposal.
Speaking yesterday during a visit to an open cast mine at Shotts, Dr
Preston explained that the company was keeping its promise to offer
staff a stake in the new venture.
''I hope as many employees as possible decide to take advantage of
this opportunity to invest in their futures, and the future of this
company,'' he said.
''We have shown our determination to make this company a success by
committing ourselves to investing up to #15m in developing the
Kincardine reserves to ensure we will be producing coal to the year
2020.''
Dr Preston described the venture as a ''tremendous opportunity'' for
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two Strathallan former pupils fined for possessing cannabis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO 19-year-old former pupils of a leading public school yesterday
were fined for possessing cannabis but cleared of dealing in the drug.
John Aitken, of Castlebrae Lodge, Huntingtower, Perth, and Alan Milne,
of Drummond Road, Inverness, both admitted being found in unlawful
possession of cannabis resin at Strathallan School, Perthshire, on
November 13, 1993.
Aitken, now receiving income support of #36 a week, was fined #120 at
Perth Sheriff Court. Milne, also unemployed but not yet in receipt of
benefit, was fined #100.
The pair also were accused of being concerned in the supply of
cannabis at the school. But all charges relating to alleged supply were
dropped when the Crown accepted their pleas of not guilty to these
counts.
This late development, which followed pre-trial negotiations between
defence and Crown, meant that 11 witnesses who had turned up for the
case were not called to give evidence.
Depute fiscal Ann Orr said that police were called to Strathallan
after staff had learned that cannabis had been brought into the school.
It was then established that the two accused possessed the drug, the
total amount involved being worth about #40.
Defence lawyer David Holmes said that Aitken was a former pupil who
committed the offence while revisiting the school.
He was embarrassed and ashamed at behaviour which had caused a great
deal of concern to his family.
Mr John McLaughlin, representing Milne, said that his client was a
pupil at the time of the offence and was expelled as a result.
The lawyer added: ''The effect on my client's family, his parents in
particular, was quite devastating and this had a salutary effect on him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Roads officials under fire over evidence at death crash inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO senior officials from Strathclyde region's roads department were
criticised yesterday over the evidence they gave at a fatal accident
inquiry.
Mr Ronald Small and Mr Archibald Sexton showed a ''reluctance,
reticence, and avoidance'' in answering questions at the inquiry,
according to depute fiscal Jim Robertson.
Mr Robertson was summing up on the final day of the inquiry at
Hamilton Sheriff Court into the death of Mr Callum Chisholm, 27, a
police officer whose car hit black ice and collided with a lorry.
He said both witnesses had made harder than it should have been the
job of finding out why roads officials had failed to grit the A73 in
Lanarkshire despite two weather warnings.
Earlier in the inquiry, Mr Small, a Roads Direct manager for Lanark
North and Central, had claimed that surface water did not always freeze
at zero degrees.
The inquiry heard how the A73 was known as a problem spot because of
water seepage from nearby bings.
Thermal maps available to roads department staff highlighted the road
as generally colder than the norm.
Weather forecasts alerted roads officials to sleet and snow showers
and freezing temperatures, leading to patchy icing ''chiefly in
Lanarkshire'', the day before the crash which crumpled Mr Chisholm's car
to a width of only six inches.
Although the forecast amounted to a ''marginal'' situation, roads
chiefs chose not to seek clarification from the Glasgow Weather Centre
despite having a 24-hour hotline facility.
They decided against precautionary gritting.
Mr Roberston said: ''This road should have been gritted, though I
would not even attempt to summarise the evidence of Mr Small or Mr
Sexton.''
Mr Chisholm, of Biggar, died early on March 15 last year as he
travelled to work at Stewart Street police station in Glasgow.
Mr Peter Watson, representing his widow Elizabeth, said Mr Chisholm's
death would go down as a ''day of shame for Strathclyde region's roads
department''.
Gillian Johnstone, for Strathclyde region, said that very difficult
decisions had been taken by experienced personnel, and that reasonable
precautions were in place.
Sheriff Lewis Cameron will return a written determination later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conservative attacks #30m plan to upgrade SECC</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS to spend #30m extending Glasgow's Scottish Exhibition and
Conference Centre in Glasgow to meet international conference standards
were condemned by a Conservative yesterday as ''financial nonsense''.
In a complicated sale-and-lease-back arrangement soon to be banned by
the Government, Strathclyde region and Glasgow district intend to borrow
#30m jointly so that the project, estimated to create 900 jobs, can go
ahead.
There is apparently an urgent need to have the facility completed in
time for the international Rotary conference in 1997, which is expected
to generate #20m of income.
But Councillor Iain Drysdale, leader of the council's Conservative
group, warned that extensive destabilisation could have occurred on the
SECC site as a result of December's unprecedented floods.
Councillor Drysdale also expressed doubts about Glasgow being able to
make a significant impact in the highly specialised field of
international conferences for more than 3000 people.
He also felt that hotel and and service industries in the Glasgow
area, which would be the main beneficiaries of the conference, should be
prepared to held fund the SECC development.
''I'm not sure this is a job for local government,'' he said.
But the Liberal Democrat leader, Dr Christopher Mason, commented:
''It's that kind of attitude that has de-industrialised Scotland.''
Councillor Gerald McGrath, deputy leader of the Labour administration,
said the recent Government decision to proscribe buy-and-ease-back
arrangements meant that the council had to act now.
Under the arrangement, Strathclyde region and Glasgow district will
buy the land necessary for the conference centre from SECC Ltd for #5m
amd lease the land back to SECC Ltd for 21 years.
Such an arrangement will enable both councils to create a notional
capital receipt, resulting in a #30m enhancement of their borrowing
consent from the Scottish Office which will pay for the new conference
centre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beattie to be freed on parole</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONVICTED murderer George Beattie is to be released on parole next
month.
The parole board's decision was endorsed by Scottish Secretary Ian
Lang after consultations with the Lord Justice General, Lord Hope.
Beattie, who has always protested his innocence, will walk free from
Saughton Prison in Edinburgh on March 16.
His solicitor, Mr Joe Beltrami, said yesterday: ''I am very pleased.
He should never have been jailed in the first place.''
Beattie, 40, was convicted in 1973 of the murder of 23-year-old
Margaret McLaughlin near Carluke railway station in Lanarkshire.
He was released in 1986 but recalled to prison in 1992 after an
incident with his supervising officer which led to an admonition from a
sheriff.
He was released again to mount an appeal, but this was rejected last
November at a hearing in Edinburgh.
Mr Beltrami said he had not yet decided on what course of action to
take, although the options include seeking a fresh hearing at the Appeal
Court or a pardon.
''Some entirely new evidence has come to light since the last appeal
which we are exploring at the moment,'' he said.
''Several ex-police officers have come forward with fresh information.
''Once we have looked at various lines of inquiry we will decide on
what to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Islamicist mob storms court in blasphemy trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Islamabad, Thursday
A MOB of militant Muslims stormed the courthouse where a 14-year-old
Christian boy is appealing against his death sentence for allegedly
insulting Islam.
About 500 chanting protesters wearing green turbans, the colour
associated with Islam, hurled abuse at defence lawyer Asma Jehangir,
threatened violence against the two justices hearing the appeal, and
rioted outside the Lahore High Court.
''They smashed my car. I escaped with my life,'' said Ms Jehangir in a
telephone interview. She later left Pakistan for Britain to undergo
medical treatment for a heart ailment.
At one point in the hearing Ms Jehangir, the most outspoken human
rights advocate in Pakistan, broke down in tears, according to
witnesses. Turbaned hecklers jeered and abused her relentlessly until
she asked to have the courtroom cleared, they said.
The trouble began earlier as Ms Jehangir rose to address the court,
when fundamentalists rose and moved towards her, shouting ''US bitch''
and ''agent of the US and Britain''.
Outside the court, they pelted her car with stones and smashed the
windows with sticks. They dragged her driver from the car and tried to
strangle him, said Hina Jilani, a second defence lawyer.
Muslim extremists have been closely watching the case against Salamat
Masih, 14, who is a Roman Catholic, and his uncle, Rehmat Masih, who are
both charged with writing anti-Islamic slogans on a mosque wall.
Their appeal continues on Monday.
Several small pieces of paper with anti-Islamic jottings on them were
entered as evidence but no-one, not even those who laid the blasphemy
charge, are saying that Salamat or his uncle wrote these jottings, said
Jilani.
''The pieces of paper have nothing to do with this case, even the
complainants say they were written a year before the writing on the
mosque wall,'' he said.
A third accused in the case, the boy's cousin Manzoor Masih, died in a
hail of bullets on the steps of the court in April last year, gunned
down by Islamic vigilantes.
Fears also exist for John Joseph, a British human rights worker who
was injured in an earlier attack on the co-defendants.
Mr Joseph is the key witness in the case against the alleged
attackers, who include the complainant in the blasphemy case, Muslim
leader Fazul Haq, which is next due to be heard on March 16.
Human rights groups, including the British Amnesty International and
the Jubilee Campaign, which has worked for the release of the defendants
since the case was first brought in 1993, have criticised Pakistan's
blasphemy laws as vague and easily invoked by extremists to attack the
country's minority religions.
The laws were introduced in the 1980s by the military dictator,
General Muhammed Zia-ul Haq. However successive governments have refused
to repeal the laws, including Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, who has
tried to avoid an open confrontation with Pakistan's Muslim extremists,
a small but vocal group.
So far she has shied away from introducing even minor amendments, but
earlier this week she called for change in the laws and she too was a
target of abuse by the mob today.
Yesterday Muslim clerics filed contempt of court charges against Ms
Bhutto for criticising the lower court for sentencing a juvenile to
hang.
She said she was ''surprised, shocked, and saddened'' by the ruling.
However, she has also said that she will not interfere in the legal
proceedings.
The blasphemy case has created a furore both at home and abroad and
has underscored the government's awkward position.
Ms Bhutto has been trying to improve her country's human rights
record, but if her government speaks out against the verdict, it risks a
backlash from Muslim extremists.--AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU fisheries campaign under attack from Lang</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Ian Lang has criticised a campaign urging Britain
to withdraw from the EU Common Fisheries Policy as using fallacious
arguments and misrepresenting the facts.
The accusations are made in a letter to the Scottish Fishermen's
Federation on the eve of a crucial meeting at which it is to discuss
whether it will support the Save Britain's Fish Campaign, to which Mr
Lang is referring.
So far the SFF has been opposed to the campaign but its English
counterpart, the National Association of Fishermen's Federations, has
joined and the Scottish White Fish Producers' Association, the most
powerful group within the SFF, has been a long-term supporter.
Mr Lang said the campaign was based entirely on an appeal to the
emotions of fishermen and failed to recognise the economic, legal, and
political constraints which make the objective of withdrawing from the
CFP both completely unrealistic and damaging to the fishing industry.
''I do understand that fishermen's anxieties have been heightened by
the prolonged negotiations to integrate Spain and Portugal into the
CFP,'' he said.
''I believe, however, that they have been unjustifiably exaggerated
and exploited by the organisers of this campaign to the detriment of
fishermen.''
He said the UK had accepted by treaty that fisheries lay within the
competence of the European Union, and could not pick and choose which
parts of those treaties it wished to observe.
There was no prospect of an unanimous agreement among the 15 member
states to amend the treaties which provide the legal basis of the CFP.
''Even in that case, fisheries would remain subject to all the rest of
EU legislation, including, for example, the single market regulations
which provide the freedom to establish fishing businesses in other
member states.
''The cost of a unilateral withdrawal from the CFP would be quite
unacceptable to this country, but the costs to the industry itself
should also be recognised as unacceptable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour group told to drop bid to co-opt member into 'SNP seat'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE ruling Labour group on Renfrew District Council last night
withdrew plans to propose a party member for co-option to a seat vacated
by a former SNP councillor after the Scottish Labour Party warned that
the move breached Cosla and Labour Party rules and could have ''severe
repercussions''.
The group, which has 21 members, had agreed on Wednesday to propose Mr
Danny Farren, secretary of Labour's Paisley Central branch, for
co-option to the Brediland ward in Paisley at a meeting of the full
council last night.
The ward was vacated following the resignation of Councillor George
McIntyre, who was elected as an SNP councillor in 1992 but later served
as an independent member after being ousted from the SNP group when his
colleagues decided they were ''unhappy with his mode of conduct''.
Mr Gerald O'Brien, assistant general secretary of the Scottish Labour
Party, wrote to the group leader, Councillor Owen Taylor, earlier
yesterday, stating that an agreement had been reached within Cosla that,
where a vacancy arises which has to be filled by co-option, the party
the councillor represented would fill the vacancy.
His letter added: ''It is therefore imperative that the decision of
the Labour group be withdrawn and not proposed to the full council and
that the co-option is left to the party that the councillor represented.
Refusal to carry out the policy of the Scottish Party (Labour) could
have severe repercussions for the Labour group.''
Following Mr O'Brien's intervention, a motion was proposed by Mr
Taylor on behalf of the Labour group that the matter should be continued
until the next full council meeting in six weeks and was passed by a
majority.
A move by the SNP to have co-opted Mr Alex Kerr, who is to contest the
Brediland seat at the council elections in April, was defeated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Killer appeals against 25-year jail sentence New legal move over payroll robbery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN,LAW CORRESPONDENT,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONVICTED killer jailed for life for his role in a notorious murder
and payroll robbery in Glasgow 21 years ago is now appealing against the
trial judge's recommendation that he serve at least 25 years.
Londoner Sydney Draper, 46, was one of seven men jailed in 1974 for
murdering gateman James Kennedy during an armed robbery at the British
Rail depot at Springburn the previous December.
Mr Kennedy, 42, intercepted the raiders' getaway van and was clubbed
to the ground with shotgun butts as they escaped with #9854.
As he staggered to his feet, a gun in the van went off accidentally,
creating a panic. As Mr Kennedy came out of the gate at the depot, one
of the raiders leaned out of the van window and shot him dead.
After an 18-day trial at the High Court in Glasgow in April 1974, at
that time the longest in Scottish criminal history, Lord Kissen
recommended that Draper, then 25 and the possessor of an extensive
criminal record, should serve a minimum of 25 years.
The judge also recommended a 25-year sentence for Alan Brown, 28, the
man who fired the fatal shot.
He said that John Murphy, 35, James Aitken 27, and Stephen Doran, 24,
each should serve at least 18 years and Robert Marley, 30, who had pled
guilty at the end of the Crown case, 15 years.
At a subsequent trial, a seventh man, William Murray, 28, was jailed
for life and Lord Dunpark recommended that he should serve at least 16
years. Murray, also from London, was not arrested until a week after his
six accomplices were jailed and pled guilty on the second day of his
trial in July 1974.
In December 1987, there was a nationwide police hunt after he staged a
spectacular helicopter escape from Gartree Prison, Leicestershire.
He was recaptured after 15 months on the run and in June 1989 pled
guilty to offences of hijacking, escaping, and possessing a firearm. He
was jailed for four years at Leicester Crown Court.
At the Court of Criminal Appeal yesterday, Mr William Taylor, QC, for
Draper, said that of the six men, only Brown and Draper were still in
custody.
At the time of Draper's conviction, it was not possible to appeal
against a recommendation by a trial judge in a murder case. This only
became possible under the 1980 Criminal Justice (Scotland) Act and the
legal position did not become clear until the first appeal against a
recommendation in 1993.
In March 1994, Draper went to the High Court in England to ask for a
judicial review of the 25-year recommendation, but Mr Justice Owen
decided the court case was premature since Draper already was pursuing
an appeal at the Court of Criminal Appeal in Scotland.
If that failed, he could always make a fresh application for judicial
review in England.
Lord Ross, Lord Justice Clerk, sitting with Lords McCluskey and
Morison, asked Mr Taylor whether Draper's appeal was competent since the
25-year recommendation was made before the 1980 Act came into force.
The court adjourned the case so that the question of competency can be
argued at a later date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
