<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flag Officer move will cost 120 jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government last night confirmed it is transferring the operational
headquarters of the Flag Officer Scotland, Northern England, and
Northern Ireland (FOSNNI) from Pitreavie in Fife to Faslane on the
Clyde, with the loss more than 120 jobs.
In a Commons written answer, Defence Minister Roger Freeman said the
move, due to take place by April 1996, would result in the closure of
the maritime headquarters at Pitreavie.
As part of the announcement, Mr Freeman said the Ministry of Defence
would make available to local development company Fife Enterprise a 5.5
acre site to the south of the Pitreavie estate. The rest of the base
will be sold to Fife Enterprise when the MoD finally withdraws from
Pitreavie in 1996.
A spokesman for Fife Enterprise said: ''We are disappointed at the job
losses to Fife but the new site will enable us to develop the
high-quality business park at Carnegie Campus and will allow us to
continue to attract inward investment from companies such as BSkyB and
the Dunfermline building society.''
The MOD claims the switch from Pitreavie to Faslane will save about
#22m over the next 10 years. Mr Freeman said 70 military and 52 civilian
posts would no longer be required as a result. ''We will continue to
consult with staff and the Trades Unions about the detailed
implementation of the measure and its implications,'' he said.
* IN a Commons debate on the Royal Navy last night, Dunfermline West
Labour MP Rachel Squire protested that workers at the Rosyth naval base
felt they had been betrayed by the Government.
She said it had been ''blow after blow'' for the workforce and added:
''They feel that their loyalty has been repaid with betrayal and broken
promises.''
Workers believed public money had been wasted, with #63m spent on
improvements before the decision effectively to close the base. 10,000
defence-related jobs now were likely to be lost in Fife between 1991 and
1996.
Ms Squire said: ''Rosyth workers have felt themselves to be dangling
on a Treasury rope without any firm deck of security underneath them.
The strain and stress has had many effects, not least on people's
health.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Husband nabbed</HEADLINE>
