<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Widow says Draper should stay in prison</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE WIDOW of murdered security guard James Kennedy last night declared
that Sydney Draper should serve all of the 25 years' minimum sentence
recommended by the trial judge.
One of her daughters spoke of her wish to meet Draper and ask him how
he felt about what he and the other gang members had done to the family.
The murder left Mrs Ellen Kennedy with three young daughters -- Shona,
Elspeth and Leila -- to bring up alone.
Mr Kennedy's bravery was recognised in several tributes. In 1975, he
was posthumously awarded the George Cross, the highest civilian honour
for gallantry.
In the same year, he was honoured with the Glasgow Corporation Medal
for Bravery. Six years later, British Rail had his widow name a
locomotive after him.
The awards gave the family pride, a little comfort and something the
girls could remember their father by. But nothing could make up for his
loss, and more than 21 years later, the pain is still evident.
Speaking at her home in Bearsden, near Glasgow, last night, Mrs
Kennedy said: ''We got the medals, but that can not make up for what
happened.''
Told about Draper's appeal attempt, she said: ''As far as I am
concerned, it will not make any difference to me how much longer he
stays in prison. But he was given a minimum of 25 years and I do not see
why he should serve less than that.
''What those men did deprived my girls of a father --and the girls
have suffered for it.
''I do not know what technicality he is trying to use in his appeal,
but he should serve the 25 years.''
One of her daughters, Elspeth, 27, said: ''I think I would like to
meet him, just to find out how he feels. I would like to know whether or
not he feels sorry for what he has done.''
She spoke of the financial hardship her mother has had to endure over
the years, and the lack of state support for the families of victims of
crime.
Her mother added: ''At least he (Draper) has not had bills to worry
about while he has been in prison.''
The family are Jehovah's Witnesses and say they have derived a lot of
comfort and strength from this.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hacker for trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RALEIGH: Kevin Mitnick, described as the ''most wanted computer hacker
in the world'', will appear in a North Carolina court today after a
two-year ''electronic'' manhunt. Mitnick, 31, is alleged to have stolen
information from computers all over the US and in Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Squaddies lose wage battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE,DEFENCE CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE top brass goes to the top brass, according to a Labour Party study
into military salaries since 1979.
Generals and admirals have made a genuine 12.3% gain in salary deals
since the Conservatives took power 16 years ago, while the average
squaddie and naval rating have lost 15.4% in wages.
Dr John Reid, Labour's armed forces spokesman and MP for Motherwell
North, said last night: ''Once again, the poor bloody infantry and their
naval and air force equivalents have borne the economic brunt of
Government policy.
''According to the Defence Ministry's own figures, there has been a
25% cut in budget over the last 10 years in real spending terms. Recent
cuts in support services go even deeper.
''But it is scandalous that the men and women at the sharp end of the
business, the lowest ranks on the rung, have actually lost money while
their bosses have been given a cash bonus.
''The people who fought the Falklands and Gulf wars are poorer now
than they were in the 1970s. The veterans behind the bayonets have been
treated shabbily, but entirely in keeping with the Tory concept of
society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gospel choir moves Prince</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prince of Wales was almost moved to tears yesterday as he listened
to a gospel choir from Los Angeles in a personal royal command
performance at St James's Palace.
The choir from Crenshaw Elite High School, in the violent and deprived
South Central district of Los Angeles, belted out gospel songs in the
Queen Anne state-room -- normally the scene of sedate royal dinners and
presentations.
The Prince had invited the 70-strong choir to sing for him after he
heard it was coming to Europe this month.
He had heard the choir sing during a visit to Los Angeles last
November.
For many pupils this trip was their first outside California, let
alone America.
To applause, choir mistress Iris Stevenson again brushed off royal
protocol to give the Prince a hug, as she had done on their last
meeting.
The choir, made up of pupils, ex-pupils, parents, and others connected
with the school, gave another rendition of its gospel version of God
Bless the Prince of Wales.
Afterwards, the Prince said he would remember the song always.''It was
wonderful. You must teach the Welsh how to sing it,'' he joked.
Miss Stevenson said afterwards: ''The kids think of the Prince as a
friend.''
One soloist, Leland Julian, 16, could barely contain his pride at
meeting the Prince.
''I will be able to tell my grandchildren that I have met royalty,''
he said.
The choir was to sing at Covent Garden and Spitalfields before leaving
for Paris tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Presidents in golf gaffes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDIAN WELLS: Three spectators were hit when President Bill Clinton,
former presidents George Bush and Gerald Ford played a charity golf
match with comedian Bob Hope.
Bush's second shot bounced off a tree and hit a woman on the nose,
causing a heavy nosebleed and a wound which needed 10 stitches. His
drive off the 14th tee hit a man on the leg, but did not draw blood.
Ford's low drive on the 17th hit a woman on the finger.
After the game, Clinton, who lost to Bush by one stroke, said he liked
golf ''because it's a peaceful, beautiful thing''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Precedent feared as Shell saves #34m Atlantic grave approved for giant oil installation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREENPEACE has condemned a plan by Shell to dump in the Atlantic a
redundant 14,500-tonne installation which contains radioactive material.
Government approval was granted yesterday for Shell's plans -- which
would set a precedent -- to consign the 450ft high Brent Spar storage
and tanker loading facility to a watery grave at 2000 metres.
Shell says that balancing safety, environment, and cost, deep-sea
disposal is the best practicable method, but Greenpeace, which questions
Shell's research, says that the main reason is the #34m saving by
dumping over dismantling.
The installation, at which six men died in 1990 after a helicopter hit
a crane and plunged into the sea, was decommissioned in 1991.
The precise site has still be selected by the Government, but it is
planned to sink the Brent Spar this summer.
''One possible option which was investigated closely was onshore
scrapping,'' Shell said. ''However it was concluded that this approach,
involving reversing the installation process, would be technically
complex, involving a high number of offshore operations, and would give
no environmental benefit.''
The company said that a ''detailed environmental impact analysis'' for
the deep-sea option identified the effect of regulated substances on
board and showed the effect to be negligible.
However this was not accepted by Mr Simon Roddy, an independent
environmental consultant who has just completed a study for Greenpeace
on the decommissioning of North Sea installations.
''Out of sight out of mind is not necessarily out of the
environment,'' he said. ''The Brent Spar has about 30 tonnes of
radioactive waste on board known as LSA scale. In the bottom of Brent
Spar is about 100 tonnes of sludge and this contains heavy metal, PCBs,
oil residues and further radioactive waste.
''What guarantees have Shell got that the structure will not hit the
bottom in pieces or will break up on the way down?''
He said there were more than 200 North Sea installations and he was
extremely concerned that others might now argue that they should be
allowed to follow and that all Britain's oil and gas installations would
be dumped at sea.
''The Government and the oil companies made promises when they put
these things in place that they would remove them. US Federal Law
requires the complete removal of all rigs and platforms. More than 900
have been removed from the Gulf of Mexico in depths of up to 150 metres
of water.
''Some of the companies removing them in America are the same
companies arguing that it cannot be done here.''
Giving the go-ahead to the dumping, Energy Minister Tim Eggar said
yesterday that the abandonment of offshore installations and pipelines
represented a large and costly exercise both for the operator and the
Exchequer, and it was vitally important to get it right.
In the first ministerial speech on abandonment since the Petroleum Act
was enacted 18 years ago, he said cost savings by the industry had
played a significant part in postponing inevitable decisions to abandon
installations, but the day had to come.
The Brent Spar was a good example of where, having considered all the
options, it was concluded the best environmental option was deep-sea
disposal.
He said that the Government had to take into account the concerns of
the environment and other users of the sea when approaching abandonment,
but the guidelines also recognised that cost had to be weighed in the
balance.
The announcement of the approval of the Atlantic option will infuriate
fisherman, who have been adamant from the birth of the North Sea oil
industry that all installations should be removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
