<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coastline search in survey of dead sea birds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUNDREDS of volunteers will search Scotland's coastline for dead sea
birds when a nationwide survey is launched later this month to assess
the extent of oil spills and illegal discharges.
The survey -- on February 25 and 26 -- is being mounted by the Royal
Society for the Protection of Birds which will call on an army of
helpers to walk along the shores counting the numbers of dead birds
washed up.
Carcasses found will be taken to laboratories for analysis in a bid to
identify causes of death and oil sources.
Oil pollution is known to kill thousands of birds around Britain's
coastline each year.
The RSPB says most of the oil comes from deliberate waste discharges
at sea rather than accidental spillages.
Chief executive Barbara Young said: ''These surveys are invaluable in
helping to highlight the continuing regular discharges of oil from ships
at sea.
''The UK Government must press for measures to address this
international problem at the forthcoming North Sea conference in
Denmark.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Volunteer 'friends' sought by charity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID,MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VICTIMS of head injury are to have the services of volunteer
assistants, trained to help them cope with the long-term effects of
their trauma.
The volunteers are to be recruited by the Head Injuries Trust for
Scotland, which said yesterday that 5700 Scots sustained head injuries
every year, 800 of them severe.
After their immediate clinical needs are taken care of by
neuro-surgical and rehabilitaion teams about 5000 will be left with some
physical or psychological disability for the rest of their lives.
HITS has received a grant of #30,000 a year for three years from
Strathclyde Regional Council to mount the scheme in the Greater Glasgow
area.
Sir Michael Bond, chairman of the trust, said yesterday: ''Helping
with the problems of head-injured people may sound formidable, but we
can assure those who wish to come forward that they will be well trained
and supervised to cope with the work.''
Under the supervision of a co-ordinator, Penny Keith, the volunteers
will learn to offer friendship -- accompanying clients to social outings
which might otherwise be denied them, respite for full-time carers, help
with travel, assisting with exercise activities, or helping clients to
relearn and improve the basic skills they need for independent living.
Sir Michael emphasised they were looking for men and women.
''Women seem to be more likely to get involved in this kind of thing,
but the nature of head injury is such that most of our clients are men
and they tend to prefer to have men looking after them.''
The scheme's launch coincided with a report by the Joseph Rowntree
Foundation which said that families of young people with head injuries
were being failed by health and social services.
Parents struggling to cope on their child's release from hospital said
they received little or no long-term support, according to the study by
psychologist Jane Hubert.
</TEXT>
