<DOCNO>GH950217-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sacked chief demands 15 hear appeal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS,HIGHLAND CORRESPNDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former chief executive of Lochaber District Council, who was
sacked last month, is demanding all 15 council members hear his appeal
against dismissal.
A four-member committee is due to hear Mr David Blair's case next
month. However, Mr Blair maintains this committee is ''tainted by
personal interest'' as all belong to a group of eight councillors who
voted to suspend him last September.
Mr Blair is being defended by the GMB Scotland union, whose Highlands
and Islands organiser Bruce Crabtree said yesterday: ''The charges
against David Blair are totally without foundation and Mr Blair's
refutation of all seven of them will be made publicly available.
''We have called for an independent inquiry into this affair and for
the good government of Lochaber that investigation must still be held.
As far as Lochaber District Council's conduct of this affair is
concerned, the council's decision to suspend Mr Blair contravened the
Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, was without proper legal
foundation, and should not be allowed to stand.
''That decision and the setting up of an investigation sub-committee
was also in breach of Lochaber District Council's standing orders. In
addition, council chairman Neil Clark, who made a personal complaint
against Mr Blair, was a member of that sub-committee.''
Mr Clark, however, said yesterday: ''In the first place I never made a
complaint against Mr Blair. Two councillors who voted against his
suspension were nominated to serve on the investigating committee, but
refused to attend; we tried to get two others to serve on the appeals
committee and they refused.
''We have conducted this whole affair in as fair a manner as possible
and have received top level independent advice throughout.''
</TEXT>
