<HEADLINE>Court clears way for British soldiers' trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nicosia, Thursday
CYPRUS Supreme Court today announced that the trial of three British
soldiers accused of killing a Danish woman tour guide will resume next
week after ruling that a legal complication had no bearing on the
process.
The trial was interrupted in December after one of the three judges of
the lower court was promoted to attorney general.
The case was then referred to the 11-member Supreme Court, which after
several sessions ruled today that the technicality would not affect the
trial.
The Assize Court will convene on Monday to hear legal arguments by the
defence for the release of the three defendants.
In a pre-trial objection, the defence claimed that a prison guard took
confidential notes the defendants had prepared for their lawyers, and
demanded that the case be dismissed.
The men were arrested on September 13 and charged with killing Louise
Jensen, 23, after kidnapping her in the tourist resort of Ayia Napa.
The soldiers are Privates Alan Ford, 26, of Birmingham, Justin Fowler,
26, of Falmouth, Cornwall, and Jeff Parnell, 23, of Oldbury, West
Midlands.
They have yet to enter pleas to charges of manslaughter and abduction
with intent to rape.
Police have said the three admitted kidnapping and killing Miss
Jensen, whose battered body was found in a shallow grave two days after
her abduction.
When arrested at a police road block several hours after Miss Jensen's
Cypriot boyfriend reported her abduction, the soldiers had bloodstains
on their clothes. A blood-covered shovel was found in their car.
All three serve with the Royal Greenjackets Regiment at the Sovereign
Base Area of Dhekelia in southern Cyprus.--AP.
</TEXT>
