<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kinnock backs code of safety for ferries</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels, Thursday
ROLL-ON, roll-off passenger ferries will be banned from European ports
unless they sign up to a strict safety code if Transport Commissioner
Neil Kinnock has his way.
The plan is the European Commission's answer to a demand for tougher
shipping safety rules after the ferry Estonia sank in the Baltic Sea
last September, drowning more than 900 people.
The plan will take immediate effect if agreed by EU Transport
Ministers.
''Tragedies such as that of the Estonia and the Herald of Free
Enterprise cannot be allowed to happen again,'' said Mr Kinnock.
''Everyone who travels on ferries has the right to expect them to be
safe and efficient.''
The Estonia sinking, the worst ferry disaster in Europe this century,
came seven-and-a-half years after the Herald of Free Enterprise capsized
as it sailed from the Belgian port of Zeebrugge.
The EU executive said it had made today's proposal because too many
companies operating public ferry services did not have sufficient safety
codes.
The Commission proposal would mean that the 15 EU countries would sign
up to the International Safety Management Code -- drawn up by the
International Maritime Organisation -- two years earlier than other
countries.
A Commission spokeswoman said there would be no technical changes to
ships. but the idea was to make sure crews were equipped to prevent and
deal with accidents.
''It's more on how you manage your crews to ensure that safety is
their top priority,'' she said.
The Commission has not considered the issue fitting extra bulkheads on
car decks. That is being studied by the IMO in response to the Estonia
tragedy.
Under the IMO code, management boards would be obliged to have a
person responsible for safety, crews would have to undergo medical tests
and training to ensure that they could deal with an emergency, and
safety rules would have to be clearly established.
''The shipping industry has never had a common set of detailed safety
management procedures covering everything from shore-based management
practices and communications to emergency procedures,'' the Commission
said today.
''The adoption of this regulation would mark a major breakthrough in
ensuring that safety considerations are made an integral part of
shipping business.''
The EU's shipping industry has consistently opposed EU moves to set
its own shipping safety standards over and above IMO rules on the
grounds that they could hinder competitiveness.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
