<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Delinquent teenager becomes hero by saving 14 from blaze</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pine Bluff, Thursday
FLAMES were melting a mobile home around him when Steven Hines ran
inside to see if anyone was trapped. Five families are eternally
grateful that for once, the 17-year-old with a delinquency record did
the right thing.
He saved a dozen children aged four to 13 and their two adult
babysitters, both in their 70s, in Pine Bluff, Arkansas, by rousing them
and singlehandedly carrying them outside.
Not until hours later did he realise what he had done. ''I got scared
then,'' he said.
Steven said he was riding his bicycle home from a grocery shop when he
spotted flames from the mobile home's chimney.
He called but there was no answer.
The door was unlocked so he went inside, and immediately noticed the
ceiling.
''Flames were moving across like waves on the ocean,'' he said.
''Stuff was melting. It was like a marshmallow.''
One nine-year-old boy died in the blaze, and when authorities removed
the body Steven said he had to turn away: ''I didn't sleep that night.''
At Pine Bluff High School this week, principal Andrew Tolbert wanted
to salute Steven at assembly. However, Steven gave school a miss.
''His attendance has not been consistent, at best,'' the headmaster
said, but added that the boy's truancy should not overshadow his
heroism.
Steven acknowledged that he has twice been sent to state juvenile
rehabilitation centres.
''I was young. I was doing things my brothers do and hanging with the
wrong crowd,'' he said.
More optimistic now, he added: ''I have to leave that alone -- I have
better things to do than that.''--AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Menaced writer speaks out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Bangladeshi writer Taslima Nasrin, known as ''the female Salman
Rushdie'', spoke last night about how a death threat for allegedly
blaspheming Islam had changed her life.
Ms Nasrin, 32, who fled to Sweden in August, said she missed her
homeland and longed to walk anonymously in the streets again, but
dreaded an attack by Islamic extremists.
The doctor turned poet, columnist, and novelist said: ''My writing is
more important than a normal life, so I have sacrificed my normal life.
I have given up all my happiness only for that reason, that one day
society and women will wake up.''
She denies calling for changes in the Koran, Islam's holy book, in
remarks to an Indian newspaper. She says she was misquoted and had urged
changes in Islamic law to give women more rights.
Ms Nasrin said she stood by her 1993 novella Shame, about Muslim
persecution of Hindus.
She is in Britain to give a lecture in Oxford sponsored by Amnesty
International.--AP.
</TEXT>
