<DOCNO>GH950217-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yeltsin to shake up armed forces after Chechen debacle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Thursday
RUSSIAN President Boris Yeltsin today pledged to shake up the armed
forces because of their failures in Chechnya, and told his people Russia
had been too kind for too long to the breakaway Chechen leadership.
He called the Chechen regime so criminal that it could be compared
with Colombia's Medellin drug cartel.
In an annual State of the Nation address to Parliament, the
64-year-old Kremlin leader set out to halt the dramatic slide in his
popularity and authority since he launched the campaign in bring the
rebel region to heel.
He did not single out any individuals for criticism, despite
speculation that Defence Minister Pavel Grachev's job could be on the
line over a venture that has hit problems at almost every turn.
Instead he used his hour-long speech to pledge to strengthen the
rouble and stabilise Russia's shaky economy -- but he did not say how.
He also demanded improvements in crime fighting, legal reforms, and more
responsibility from the media.
On the economy, Yeltsin steered clear of any pledges of radical
reform.
Foreign policy also remained unchanged, although he denounced Nato
plans to expand into east European states.
Defending the bloody Chechen adventure which he launched on December
11, Yeltsin said: ''The state can, and must, use the force of authority
to preserve its sovereignty, independence, and integrity.''
However in his toughest criticism of the army since the start of the
war, he said Russian military leaders had been caught unprepared.
''Their failures, setbacks, and mistakes in command are a painful blow
to patriotic and civic feelings,'' he said. ''Decisive measures must be
taken to reorganise the armed forces.''
He said Russia must step up its combat readiness and improve
co-ordination between sections of its armed forces, apparently opening
the way to remove top officers.
Russia is now in the tenth week of the war. Chechnya's capital Grozny
is in ruins. Thousands of Chechen civilians and hundreds of Russian
conscripts have been killed.
''We kept ourselves happy for too long with the hope that the
situation would solve itself and that compromise was possible. That was
a fatal mistake,'' Yeltsin told Parliament.
''But abcesses like the Medellin cartel in Colombia, the 'golden
triangle' of South-East Asia, and the criminal dictatorship of Chechnya
do not heal themselves,'' he added.
He said he was delighted Russians had not been swept by ''chauvinistic
and military hysteria'' while their leaders rid them of the ''Grozny
tumour''.
The war has, in fact, proved highly unpopular with the Russian public,
reluctant for their sons to be used as cannon fodder in a war most
people find unnecessary and incomprehensible.
With presidential elections due next year, Yeltsin's already low
personal popularity has nosedived.
Many foreign and Russian observers were watching Yeltsin's performance
to judge whether he still has a firm grip on power and is fit to govern
the world's largest country.
He read his speech without problems and walked on and off the podium
firmly, looking much fitter than when he stumbled and slurred his words
at a CIS summit last week.
In its first formal response to the address, the White House said
Yeltsin's speech ''confirms our view that Boris Yeltsin is in charge of
Russian policy and is committed to reform''.
However President Bill Clinton has delayed a decision on whether to
attend a summit in Moscow in May, and celebrations of the 50th
anniversary of the defeat of Nazi Germany, as domestic pressure grew to
forgo the trip because of the Chechnya crisis.
* The European Parliament protested over a Russian decision to prevent
an EU delegation from visiting Chechnya next week by denying them visas.
The Parliament also urged ''an immediate humanitarian ceasefire'' in the
Chechen conflict to permit the retrieval of the dead and
wounded.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>O J's alibi flees the country</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday
A KEY defence witness in the O J Simpson trial has fled the country,
and the judge is contemplating dismissing two of the remaining jurors.
The missing witness, Ms Rosa Lopez, was maid in the house next door to
Mr Simpson's, and the defence claimed that she would testify that she
saw his car, a white Bronco, outside the house at the time of the
murders.
Since the prosecution says that Mr Simpson used the car to drive to
his ex-wife's house, and there murdered her and a friend, Ms Lopez's
testimony would be a solid alibi. She is Salvadoran and has apparently
gone to El Salvador, without telling anyone.
Perhaps she will return (Mr Simpson would certainly pay her air fare),
or perhaps make an affidavit in San Salvador.
Meanwhile, one of the jurors is reported to have bet a friend a week's
wages that Mr Simpson would be acquitted. The alleged wager was made
before he was chosen for the jury. He told the judge that he had no
views on Mr Simpson's guilt.
The other questionable juror was found to have a map of Chicago in his
room in the motel where the jury is sequestered. He may have been trying
to study where Mr Simpson spent the night after the murder (he flew to
Chicago), and that would be against the rules.
There are 12 jurors and 12 alternates were ready to replace any who
left. Now there are nine alternates left, and the loss of two more
appears imminent.
The trial will probably last until the summer and will cost the city
of Los Angeles at least #2.6m. Mr Simpson's costs are no doubt even
greater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major claims manufacturing 'renaissance' for Britain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister claimed yesterday that Britain was enjoying a
manufacturing ''renaissance''.
Exports were doing well and so were jobs in the sector, he told the
Commons at question time.
''Manufacturing employment has risen by 37,000 in the quarter to
December. That is the fastest quarterly growth in employment in
manufacturing that we have seen at any stage since records began, and
shows clearly the extent to which manufacturing industry is now
undergoing a renaissance.''
He was answering Mr Anthony Coombs (Con - Wyre Forest), who
highlighted falls in unemployment and said a recent survey by the
Confederation of British Industry showed exports from small
manufacturing companies in Britain were at their best level for 10
years.
Later, in question time, Mr Major claimed Britain was on course to
have the lowest unemployment in western Europe.
He said: ''Long-term unemployment, whether you define that as six
months, one year or longer, is falling and has been falling for a long
time.
''I look to see it falling a good deal further.''
He went on: ''Unemployment, whether long-term or short-term, has
dropped by something over 400,000 in the last 12 months.
''We are well on the way to being the country with the lowest level of
unemployment in Western Europe.
''Our unemployment rate is already substantially below that of other
countries similar to ours.''
In France, for example, which was the most comparable country in
population, unemployment was just under 13% and static, while the UK's
was 8.5% and falling.
He was answering Labour backbencher John Heppell (Nottingham E) who
said: ''Even with the small and welcome fall in unemployment, in the
Greater Nottingham area there are still 20,000 long-term unemployed.''
The Prime Minister told Mr Heppell of his hopes for future job
creation: ''I hope that will include your constituency, though you
neglected to mention that unemployment in your constituency has already
fallen by 11%.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A question of Cabinet control</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979812606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR a Minister not to answer a direct Commons question is not unusual.
Normally, evasion produces some jeering from the Opposition and a few
knowing looks among Government back benchers and Parliamentary scribes.
Occasionally, a non answer can be spectacularly damaging and Mr Major
produced one of those yesterday. As all the Westminster world and Mr
Tony Blair knew, he had come from reading the riot act to his Cabinet
who, as again we all know, are famously divided on whether or not
Britain should ultimately sign up to a single European currency. Some of
them, moreover, we have heard airing their differences in public. This
had to stop, Mr Major told them.
Unfortunately, Mr Kenneth Clarke had just that morning delivered
himself in a newspaper interview of the view that he had a positive duty
to speak out on the longer term aspects of this vexed question. He is,
after all, Chancellor of the Exchequer.
With all this in mind, Mr Blair had prepared a simple question which
this column insists is the best kind. The Chancellor had denied that a
single currency was a threat to the nation state. Did the Prime Minister
agree?
Mr Major, like the girl in the old song, ''didn't say Yes and didn't
say No'', but: ''I think you would be wise not to misunderstand what the
Chancellor has said.''
The absence of a Yes or a No, or indeed of any positive statement, was
uncomfortably palpable. One could sympathise, though only up to a point.
A simple Yes would have had the Eurosceptics reaching for their guns; a
No would have distressed the Europhiles and also demonstrated that the
Cabinet was split.
Mr Major's reply also took the form of asking Mr Blair a question,
which he did last week as well. As it is Prime Ministers who answer
questions, this becomes akin to a pyschological transfer of power.
Mr Blair said he was ''delighted'' at this new habit and was perfectly
willing to move over to the Government's side of the chamber and answer
them once a week. Labour were delighted, the Tories appalled. Mr Major
made things worse by snappishly observing: ''You seem very keen to
answer questions. I wish some day you'd try it.'' Labour howled
delightedly: ''Now, Now.''
The Prime Minister meant, of course, that Mr Blair should answer his
rather ancient charge that the Labour leader had once been anti-EU but
it came out like an offer of the Treasury bench.
By the time Mr Major uttered the claim that the Cabinet was ''utterly
united'' he was sunk. Stymied, in fact, by his Chancellor sitting one
place away from him. For, in his interview, Mr Clarke had not minced his
words. The idea that a single currency was ''in itself'' some threat to
the nation state was ''wrong'' he said bluntly.
In an academic debate, Mr Major might have seized the words ''in
itself'' and argued that the circumstances in which one entered a single
currency were what counted and that, until you know the circumstances,
you cannot form a sensible view.
However, in a noisy chamber with the opposing factions in your party
and your Cabinet ready to fall on every word, Mr Major, even with
probably the best briefing staff in the Western World to help him, had
been unable to come up with a convincing form of words.
To have put the Prime Minister in that position Mr Clarke must reckon,
probably rightly, that his own position is ''unassailable''. Mr Major,
for his part, has made what must be a final effort to control his
Cabinet. If he fails, he is likely to be regarded in future as an
impotent spectator of a civil war he is powerless to stop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rabin lifts ban on Palestinians</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gaza City, Thursday
ISRAELI Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin today agreed in talks with PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat to ease his three-week-old closure of the Gaza
Strip and West Bank.
''We agreed that, starting next week, we will allow 10,000 workers
from Gaza to enter Israel and 5000 from Judea and Samaria (the West
Bank),'' Rabin said after the two-hour meeting in the Gaza Strip.
He said Israel was gradually lifting the ban on Palestinians because
Arafat's self-rule authority had acted against Islamic extremists, and
in the hope that such action would increase.
Rabin imposed the closure, barring 60,000 Palestinians from jobs in
Israel, on January 22 after two Islamic suicide bombers from Gaza killed
21 Israelis at a bus stop. Palestinians see the measure as collective
punishment.
Rabin said Israel and the PLO would also enter into ''intensive
talks'' to implement the next stage of their troubled peace deal --
Palestinian elections and an Israeli troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
The Prime Minister said the Palestinians had shown little enthusiasm
for his proposal to grant them immediate municipal and economic control
of the West Bank town of Jenin, without an Israeli pull-out or
stationing of Palestininan police.
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres described the talks as ''a good
working session''.
He said Arafat had told them that Palestinian security forces had
prevented six attacks against Israel.
Only last week Arafat and Rabin failed to reach an agreement on any of
the topics discussed. Arafat left that meeting without talking to the
press.
Asked if today's session had broken last week's deadlock, a
Palestinian spokesman said: ''Yes, they did.''--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hormone found to reverse bone damage by osteoporosis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
San Francisco, Thursday
THE first successful treatment for osteoporosis has been found in a
naturally occurring hormone which was found to reverse bone damage in a
laboratory study, researchers said on Thursday.
Osteoporosis is a condition in which bones become thin and vulnerable
to fracture.
A University of California at San Francisco study found that
laboratory animals treated with parathyroid hormone completely regained
bone mass lost as a result of osteoporosis and may be less likely to
suffer bone fractures in the future.
The treatment with the hormone, found naturally in humans, is the
first found to be successful in reversing the damage caused by
osteoporosis, said Nancy Lane, UCSF assistant professor of medicine and
lead author of the study.
''We see this therapy as a real jump forward in its ability to
increase bone mass and significantly reduce the fragility of bones in
osteoporosis,'' Lane said.
An estimated 1.5 million fractures each year in the United States are
linked to osteoporosis, including 250,000 hip fractures, according to
published studies.
The fractures can lead to complications and death, with more than 20%
of elderly men and women dying within a year of a hip fracture, Lane
said.
Current methods for treating osteoporosis, such as oestrogen
replacement or the drug calcitonin, may help prevent further loss of
bone, but none can reverse the bone loss once it has occurred, Lane
said.
Lane and colleagues at UCSF are to begin two clinical trials with the
drug.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
