<HEADLINE>Kirk's plea to save accused</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Church of Scotland has called on the Scottish public to help put
pressure on the Pakistan Government in a bid to save the lives of the
two Christians condemned to death for blasphemy.
The Rev Dr John Munro, the Kirk's Asia secretary, has faxed a message
of ''strongest disapproval'' of the sentence to Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto, calling for the immediate and unconditional release of
14-year-old Salamit Masih and his uncle.
Yesterday the Rev Dr Chris Wrigglesworth, general secretary of the
Kirk's World Mission Department, said: ''Of course we are worried
because the boy is a Christian, but we would be equally concerned if he
were a non-Christian child.''
Dr Wrigglesworth, who visited Pakistan last November, said the Church
of Scotland was not interfering in the country's internal affairs.
However, he said, the decision to execute Salamit was in direct breach
of the United Nations position on civil and political rights.
From tomorrow his department is including a plea for support and
prayers for the boy and his family in its regular ''Update'' phone
information line.
</TEXT>
