<HEADLINE>Unionists show  growing hostility to summit plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUSSELL EDMONDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British and Irish Prime Ministers are expected to meet at a summit
in Belfast next week to reveal their joint proposals for the future of
Northern Ireland.
However, as the deadline nears, it has become clear that Ulster
Unionists are gearing up to oppose the historic proposals, now awaiting
final Cabinet approval.
One Ulster Unionist MP, Roy Beggs, bitterly attacked the Government at
Westminster yesterday, calling into question the political integrity of
Prime Minister John Major, the Ulster Secretary of State Sir Patrick
Mayhew, and Northern Ireland Office Minister Michael Ancram.
Three other Unionist MPs revealed the contents yesterday of a letter
which they had sent to Mr Major earlier this week after what they claim
was a vain attempt to change the Government's position on the Ulster
plan.
The MPs, David Trimble, the Rev Martin Smyth, and William Ross said in
the letter that their discussion with Mr Major had ''done nothing to
dispel our concerns''.
They stated that they had heard nothing at that meeting which would be
welcomed by Unionists and repeated their ultimatum that they would, if
necessary, boycott the talks.
''We would not be able to enter into talks on the basis of an agenda
which we regard to be a one-sided nationalist agenda,'' they stated.
The letter ended: ''It is a matter of profound regret to us that what
might be a good chance of resolving our troubles is being destroyed by
Nationalist greed and intransigence.''
Despite the mounting criticism of Unionists, Mr Major appears
determined to forge ahead with his summit in Belfast and Sir Patrick
Mayhew will meet the Irish Foreign Affairs Minister Dick Spring this
weekend to put the final seal of approval on what has been called the
''framework document'' after two years of political negotiations between
parties in Ulster.
The document, running to about 50 paragraphs, will be sent to every
home in Northern Ireland in an abbreviated form. The Government is
banking on the attitude of Unionist MPs being out of step with the
ordinary public.
However, with the Ulster Unionist bloc of nine MPs, led by Mr James
Molyneaux, already sounding their opposition, Mr Major seems prepared to
take one of the biggest political gambles of his time in office. At
worst, the Unionists threaten to bring down the Government. At best,
they seem set to adopt a negative boycotting attitude to what the
document, agreed by London and Dublin, proposes in the way of
all-Ireland links.
Mr Molyneaux, who enjoyed a special political relationship with Mr
Major, has distanced himself from the Prime Minister in the past month
and is even coming under criticism from some of his own supporters who
claim that he was ''duped'' by the Government into accepting the Downing
Street peace declaration in December 1993.
Meanwhile, the Rev Ian Paisley and his Democratic Unionist Party are
absolutely certain to oppose next week's document and to mount a
campaign against it.
Observers in Belfast see the role of the Loyalist paramilitaries as
being a key factor. To date, their political spokesmen have adopted ''a
wait and see'' approach to the London-Dublin proposals, if anything,
taking a more moderate line than Mr Paisley. Their reaction to the
framework document is seen as crucial to its acceptance or rejection
within the Loyalist community.
Government officials are now putting the final touches to the
document, along with their counterparts from Dublin. Mr Major and the
Irish Taoiseach John Bruton are expected to meet in Belfast, possibly
next Wednesday, to announce their long-awaited plan. At the same time,
the Government will also publish a paper setting out proposals for a new
Northern Ireland Assembly which will be given devolved powers from
Westminster.
</TEXT>
