<HEADLINE>Health expert 'may have infected dairy'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAIRY owner Robert Haston told a trial at Linlithgow Sheriff Court
yesterday that a council health expert may have infected his premises
with a killer bacteria.
Mr Haston, 42, said that the Redhouse Dairy in Blackburn, West
Lothian, was visited by Mrs Rosemary Barrett on May 20 last year to take
samples for analysis and to close down the premises during a food
poisoning epidemic.
The court had already heard that the deadly E-coli 0157 bacteria was
found in a pipe and a rubber seal from the dairy.
Mr Haston said: ''The only places that this appeared was on the two
items that Rosemary handled. I have to ask: had Rosemary been somewhere
to get contaminated?''
He claimed that neither Mrs Barrett nor her superior, Mr Crawford
Morgan, had washed their hands before taking the samples.
Mr Haston also denied that he had failed to keep proper records of the
operation of the pasteurisation plant at the dairy.
He claimed that temperature charts for a period of nearly six months
mysteriously disappeared after he had handed them to Mrs Barrett and Mr
Morgan last May.
He was required by law to keep the records for a period of three
months.
A total of 69 people were infected by the bacteria in West Lothian in
May and June last year.
Mr Haston and his wife Margaret deny three charges alleging that they
supplied milk which was unfit for human consumption by being
contaminated with the bacteria.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
