<HEADLINE>Man cleared of attempting to drug his wife</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A UNIVERSITY researcher was yesterday cleared of attempting to drug
his wife after a sheriff described police evidence as ''wholly
unreliable''.
Abdul Rahim Elmegirab, 39, of Sunnyside Gardens, Aberdeen, was found
not guilty of attempting to administer to Mrs Linda Elmegirab the drugs
Temazepam and Nitremazepam with intent to induce stupification last
September.
During the four-day trial, Aberdeen Sheriff Court heard that Mrs
Elmegirab gave detectives a bottle of Coke and a yoghurt carton and told
them she suspected they had been interfered with.
An analysis revealed the drugs in the bottle and carton. Both drugs --
which cause drowsiness -- had been prescribed to Mr Elmegirab.
Giving evidence earlier, Mr Elmegirab denied the suggestion he had
tried to drug his wife to have sexual relations with her.
Returning the verdict Sheriff Alexander Jessop noted discrepancies in
evidence given by two detectives and said he had to disregard it.
Noting the ''background of animosity'' between the couple, the sheriff
said he was not satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that a crime had been
committed.
</TEXT>
