<HEADLINE>Clydesdale Bank strike will bite, says union</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Many Clydesdale Bank
branches will have to shut today, union officials have predicted, as
employees stage a one-day strike over pay.
But the bank has declared that neither it nor the union can possibly
say what effect the action will have until the strike actually begins.
Members of the Banking, Insurance and Finance Union -- which
represents about two-thirds of Clydesdale's 6000 employees -- have voted
in favour of a series of 24-hour walkouts. Today's action is the first
strike in the bank's history.
''We are confident that lots of branches will be forced to close,''
said Mr Hugh Roberts, Bifu negotiating officer, last night.
He was not prepared to say how many of the bank's 325 branches, nearly
all of which are in Scotland, might be closed by the strike. But he
added: ''We are confident that there will be a strong response from our
members.''
Mr Pat Lennon, the bank's head of human resources, said: ''Tomorrow
morning, people will make an individual choice. That is their right and
we respect that right. We will run the business as effectively as we can
with the people who choose to exercise their right to work. We do not
know how many people will come in, and neither does anybody else.''
Bifu leaders yesterday claimed that developments earlier this week had
done nothing to lessen the staff's determination.
They said that in six hours of talks at the Acas conciliation service
on Wednesday, the bank's management had refused to budge on its offer of
average performance-linked rises of 3%, only to raise the offer to 3.5%
in a later statement to the media.
Mr Keith Brookes, Bifu's assistant secretary, said: ''Members are more
angry now than when this dispute began. This bribe will make no
difference to the strike tomorrow, and we are getting the clear message
that the stoppage will bite.''
The union says many members will get nothing or very little out of the
performance-linked scheme. It is seeking a 4% rise for all staff, plus
2.75% available for performance pay.
Last week, the bank decided to go ahead and impose its proposed pay
package which allows increases of between 3% and 7% for employees whose
performance is ''satisfactory'' or above -- more than 90% of the staff
according to the bank.
The 0.5% increase announced on Wednesday means the rises for
satisfactory performers will now range from 3.5% to 7.5%. The bank says
the extra increase is intended to reflect rising inflation and has
denied that it is an attempt to weaken the resolve of staff as the
strike approaches.
The union already has plans for a second strike on Monday, February
27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
