<HEADLINE>North Sea diver to sue for #250,000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN,LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NORTH Sea diver who claims he suffered nightmares and began
sleepwalking after witnessing the Piper Alpha disaster -- in which 167
people died -- has been told he can sue the owners and operators of the
platform for #250,000.
Mr Paul Heathfield feared that the blazing oil-platform would collapse
on him as he worked on the nearby support vessel MSV Tharos tending the
victims, Lord Milligan was told at the Court of Session in Edinburgh.
From the time of the initial explosion about 10pm on July 6, 1988,
until 5am the following morning, Mr Heathfield was involved in rescue
operations, which included putting 18 corpses in body-bags. At one point
the Tharos was partly engulfed by a fireball from the blazing oil
platform.
The court heard that Mr Heathfield had not felt disturbed immediately
after the disaster. His feelings were of disbelief that such a
catastrophe had happened.
He continued to work as a diver offshore until mid-1992, but since
then has worked only inshore.
He did not raise his legal action until August 1993, well after the
normal three-year time limit, and decided to sue only after seeing
another disaster victim being interviewed on TV earlier that year.
Mr Heathfield, of Dereham, Norfolk, is claiming damages from Elf
Enterprise Caledonia Ltd, Union Texas Petroleum, LASMO (TNS) Ltd, and
Texaco Britain Ltd, owners of the Piper Alpha platform at the time.
The companies asked the judge to dismiss the action because it had
been raised too late.
Lord Milligan said the issue for the court was whether Mr Heathfield
should have become aware at an earlier stage that his injuries were
serious enough to justify an action of damages.
Mr Heathfield had told the court that after the disaster he gradually
began to experience nightmares of an increasingly alarming and vivid
nature.
He was sent home from the North Sea in 1991 and sought medical advice.
He was eventually diagnosed as suffering from post-traumatic stress
disorder.
The platform-owners argued that although the consequences of Mr
Heathfield's injury might have increased over time, the injury existed
from the time of the disaster, or at least very shortly after it.
Lord Milligan said that he regarded Mr Heathfield as an honest witness
who had succeeded in showing that at the crucial time he had not been
aware of the serious nature of his injuries and that it was not
reasonably practicable for him to have been aware.
The judge decided to allow evidence to be heard in the case at a later
date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
