<HEADLINE>Jury told of murder trial man's SAS claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN alleged murderer claimed to police that he was absent without leave
from the French Foreign Legion when he was detained following a
shooting, the High Court in Edinburgh was told yesterday.
But Robert Smith, 33, later admitted to detectives that he was a
soldier who, during his 14 years in the forces, has served in Northern
Ireland and the Gulf.
Mr Smith is one of three men charged with the murder of retired mining
engineer Mr David Dunn, 63, after a bank robbery in Bonnyrigg,
Midlothian.
The court heard that Mr Smith allegedly told a policeman: ''The job
was only bungled because of the duff gen I got and the amateurs I was
working with.''
The court also heard that, during a taped statement to detectives, Mr
Smith had allegedly admitted being in possession of a gun, but claimed
it was not cocked.
Mr Smith, Gerald McQuade, 40, and Paul Bootland, 25, have all denied
murdering Mr Dunn on October 19 last year.
The three have also denied attempting to murder Detective Constable
John Duffy and two other men, Mr John Girdler and Mr Duncan Milliken.
They also deny robbing a branch of the Bank of Scotland in the High
Street of #185,000.
Police Constable Michael Stark told the court that he had summoned
help while searching gardens after the alleged murder and robbery and,
when another officer arrived on the scene, he had spotted movement in
bushes.
He said that Mr Smith had emerged from the bushes with his hands up
and a smile on his face. Constable Stark said that a gun was found
hidden among leaves on the ground when they searched the bush from where
he had emerged.
PC David Shilton said he was called out to Dalkeith police station
that evening and told to sit in a cell with a colleague and a detained
man he identified in court as Mr Smith.
PC Shilton said he had told the detainee that any conversation that
took place would have to be reported to investigating officers.
The man twice went out the cell to see detectives and also saw a duty
solicitor.
PC Shilton said he had asked him if he felt happier after speaking to
the CID.
''He said that he had felt better, but the job had only been bungled
because of the duff gen that he had got and the amateurs he was working
with,'' said the constable.
PC Shilton said he had not noted the statement, but did report it to a
sergeant immediately.
He added: ''He was telling us about his past life, allegedly in the
SAS, and service he had seen in various parts of the world.''
Detective Sergeant Robert Jack said that Mr Smith had admitted going
into the bank and being in possession of a weapon, but made it clear
that the weapon was not even cocked.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
