<HEADLINE>Pupils petition school in bid to join M77 protest camp</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE children's crusade against the M77 rumbled on yesterday when
pupils from a local secondary school threatened to stage daily strikes
if teachers did not allow them to join the Pollok Estate protest camp
for two hours a day.
''If we don't get permission we'll start the strike at 1.30 every day
so we can join the other protesters,'' said 15-year-old Amanda Lang, a
fourth-year pupil at Bellarmine Secondary School.
Amanda, together with classmate Michelle McGaughy, raised a petition
signed by over 100 pupils demanding that headmaster Frank Corrigan let
them join the protest against the road, which will pass near the school.
The children intervened decisively on Tuesday when a small army of
between 60 and 100 marched on the motorway link site in what one
observer described as ''like something out of Zulu Dawn''.
Clambering on to mechanical diggers, they quickly brought work to a
halt.
Last night, speaking at her home in South Nitshill, Amanda said they
had decided to act to express their fears over the safety and health of
future pupils at the school, which she will leave in May.
''The road will go straight past our school giving off fumes and all
that and I don't want my wee cousin to end up with asthma or get knocked
over,'' she said.
School staff refused to comment, but a spokeswoman for Strathclyde
region said: 'The school is monitoring the situation and pupils are
being asked to remain in school.
''Their parents have been asked for their co-operation while the
children are supposed to be there.''
But Amanda's guardian, Mrs Margaret Lang, said last night that her
grand-daughter was nearly 16, knew her own mind, and was entitled to her
own opinion.
Amanda and the rest of the fourth year denied that anyone had
encouraged them to take strike action.
Councillor Tommy Sheridan, of Scottish Militant Labour, said the
teenagers were ''more than welcome'' in the campaign.
''There's no way anybody in their right minds should be condemning
youngsters for taking a positive part in their own lives. We should be
applauding them for coming down here and defending something that is
precious to them.''
However Wimpey expressed concern at the presence of children at the
protest.
Its director of roads, Mr Dan Pollard, said yesterday had been another
satisfactory day in the #53.6m contract.
The company completed work at the Pollok Castle woodlands after
treefellers moved in at 6am, then moved on to Patterton where they
worked for an hour before finishing for the day at 3pm.
Strathclyde Police said their presence was much reduced yesterday in
comparison to Tuesday, when 200 officers were deployed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
