<HEADLINE>Ewing fails to win EU backing in whisky row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE,EUROPEAN EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Strasbourg
MRS Winnie Ewing, SNP Euro-MP for Highlands and Islands, last night
failed to win an exemption for Scotch whisky in a new European directive
which treats it as a dangerous substance.
It is the second time in six months that Scotch has been affected by
proposed European law.
Last year, the industry successfully beat off plans to include Scotch
as a dangerous substance for the purpose of transport.
If the European Parliament had not come to the industry's aid,
distillers would have been crippled by additional costs, Mrs Ewing said.
The latest proposed law foresees whisky being included in measures
aimed at toughening fire and accident prevention.
If it is passed, whisky distillers and bonded warehouse operators
would have to install additional, expensive new equipment to prevent
fires. Most of the goods subjected to the new law are chemicals.
Mrs Ewing said she had the backing of the Scotch whisky industry and
the Confederation of European Producers of Spirits.
She said distillers and bonded warehouse operators had already
co-operated with other EU directives. ''But now they all agree this is
getting ridiculous,'' she said.
She argued that stocks of Scotch were worth millions of pounds in
government tax and were, therefore, already kept in conditions of high
security. ''This directive is simply not necessary for whisky,'' she
said.
Mrs Ewing said the cost to each bond would be #50,000 if the new
proposals were made law.
But the European Parliament, sitting in plenary session, did not
support an amendment put forward by Mrs Ewing.
The problem is now likely to come before the Council of Ministers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
