<HEADLINE>Anger at fines after woman's death fall</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE family of a 94-year-old woman, who fell to her death in a lift
shaft in a home for the elderly, yesterday criticised a sheriff for
failing to impose the maximum fine on the owners of the home and a lift
installer.
Earlier, Sheriff Norrie Stein fined Mr Robert Carroll, 46, trading as
Quick Lift Services, of Thornliebank, Glasgow, and CDH (Homes) Ltd, the
owners of Leysmill Residential Home for the Elderly, #2000 each for
contravening health and safety at work regulations.
Mrs Mary Blair, who hadlived at Leysmill Home near Arbroath for seven
years, died on February 3 last year after she fell eight feet down an
unguarded lift shaft.
Arbroath Sheriff Court was told that a door to the shaft was roped off
and that a bolt had been placed on the inside of the door leading to the
shaft. But on the night of the accident, the bolt on the door was not
fastened.
The procurator-fiscal, Mrs Betty Bott, said that Mrs Blair was a
popular resident and reasonably active for her age. She was frail but
did not require a walking stick. Her main handicap was her declining
mental condition.
On the night of the accident, Mrs Blair had been unsettled and
received medication from Mr Thomas Dailly, the manager of the home, in
her first floor room.
Later, he was aware that something was wrong in the lift shaft area
and discovered Mrs Blair at the bottom of the shaft.
The elderly woman died in his arms.
The owners of the home and Mr Carroll had previously admitted that
they failed to co-operate with each other to comply with statutory
provisions.
They also admitted failing to take reasonable steps to protect people
from falling down the incomplete lift shaft, and that Mrs Blair gained
access to the shaft, where she fell and died.
Passing sentence, the sheriff said that there was ''no doubt'' that
the lift shaft required to be properly secured and blocked off, and the
obligation to see that it was done rested with both the owners of the
home and the lift installer.
He added that the death of Mrs Blair ''would not have occurred'' but
for their failure to co-operate and co-ordinate to comply with
requirements.
Outside the court, Mrs Blair's grandson Alan Gavin, 31, said: ''I am
disappointed.''
He added that his grandmother's death was ''due to something which, I
reckon, was incompetence on both parties . . . the penalty ought to have
been the maximum''.
Mr Carroll refused to comment as he left the court, but Mr Dailly, who
is also a director of CDH (Homes) Ltd, said: ''We will be appealing. I
am not at all happy about the outcome of the case.''
Last night, Mr John McAllion MP, Scottish Labour Health spokesman,
said: ''Here we have yet another case involving a residential home for
the elderly which highlights the need for closer supervision and
increased power of inspection of these homes.''
The maximum fine under the Health and Safety At Work act which could
be applied in such a case is #5000.
</TEXT>
