<HEADLINE>Strike threat after nurses reject 1% pay offer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS,INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NURSES' leaders yesterday rejected the 1% national pay award made by
the Government in line with Pay Review Body recommendations and took the
first step towards possible industrial action.
Delegates from Unison, which represents about 240,000 of the 500,000
NHS nurses, met in emergency session at the TUC's Congress House in
London to discuss the award .
Mr Malcolm Wing, Unison deputy head of health, left the meeting
saying: ''It is a long, long time since anyone can remember nurses being
so angry -- angry about 1%, angry about the fact they feel betrayed by
the Pay Review Body and the Government.
''They are very, very angry indeed.''
Mr Wing said delegates had decided to mount a campaign involving
rallies, demonstrations, and marches in a bid to harnesss the public
support they knew existed.
He said they instructed their officers to make arrangements in
preparation for an industrial action ballot should that be necessary.
Everybody knew, he said, that the Pay Review Body was increasingly a
creature of Government and there was no doubt it had been nobbled.
Unison's NHS group executive meets next Tuesday and is expected to
endorse the recommendations of the nursing sector and seek a combined
strategy for pressing substantial pay demands for 300,000 NHS clerical
staff, ambulance workers, and hospital ancilliaries.
Branches would be urged to campaign and prepare members for an
industrial action ballot.
The officers meanwhile would prepare the internal machinery to allow a
ballot to take place should the campaign prove unsuccessful in getting
the Government to abandon its plans for local pay bargaining with all
the available 3% used for a national settlement.
With the fragmentation of negotiations within the NHS, it could take
several months to prepare for a ballot and that was why preparations
would begin immediately.
The rival non-TUC Royal College of Nursing is staging a conference on
pay tomorrow when delegates are expected to discuss lifting their ban on
industrial action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Fraser queriesstatement on trusts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was asked yesterday if a pledge to ban all NHS trusts made
earlier this week by Mr Jim Devine, chairman of the Scottish party, is
official policy.
The Health Minister, Lord Fraser of Carmylie, wrote to Mr John
McAllion, Labour's Scottish health spokesman in the Commons, saying he
had read Mr Devine's comments in The Herald and wondered if Mr Devine
had his authority and if what he said was settled Labour policy.
He asked: ''Are we to take it, for example, that the people of Angus
or Perthshire would see their communities stripped of local health
trusts with control being centralised in Dundee.
''However wrong I may consider it to be, it is refreshing to have one
Labour policy stated so unequivocally. I look forward to your
confirmation.''
Mr Devine's remarks at a party meeting at Cupar promised to integrate
all opted-out hospitals into the NHS health board structure.
The Scottish party will be launching a major health document at next
month's conference in Inverness. There have been suggestions that under
Mr Blair the party, at least in England, may revise its policy towards
trusts before the next election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Excise exemptions stay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MPS with islands in their constituencies claimed victory last night in
their battle to obtain Government concessions on Vehicle Excise Duty for
island-based hauliers.
In a meeting with Treasury Minister David Heathcote-Amory, a
delegation of MPs were told the Government would introduce an amendment
to the Finance Bill, currently under debate in the House, to preserve
the islands' exemption from plating and weighting facilities.
Two weeks ago, the MPs challenged Mr Heathcote-Amory in a Commons
debate to explain why the exemption had been removed, leaving lorries
which never leave the island having to pay hundreds of pounds in excise
tax.
In the delegation were Liberal Democrat MPs Mr Jim Wallace (Orkney and
Shetland) and Mrs Ray Michie (Argyll and Bute), and Labour MPs Mr Calum
Macdonald (Western Isles) and Mr Brian Wilson (Cunninghame North).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Activists advertise opposition to Blair</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR AND KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SECOND attempt by Labour Left-wingers to embarrass the party
leadership is being made today as Mr Tony Blair's roadshow campaign to
abolish Clause 4 of the party constitution moves to Scotland.
Euro MP Alex Falconer, who was accused last month of sabotaging Mr
Blair's visit to Brussels to launch an anti-Tory offensive on Europe,
has placed an advertisement in today's issue of The Herald claiming
Labour is attempting to abandon a ''powerful weapon'' for social and
economic progress.
It was Mr Falconer's advertisement in The Guardian last month --
supported by more than half of Britain's Labour MEPs -- which infuriated
Mr Blair and the party modernisers. Several Euro-MPs recanted after Mr
Blair denounced their ''infantile'' tactics.
Today's advertisement, on page three of The Herald, was placed by Mr
Falconer, one of the party's most staunch traditionalists, on behalf of
the Campaign for Socialism, a Scottish body which was set up early on in
the debate about Clause 4.
Its Scottish supporters include Mr Alex Smith, MEP for South of
Scotland; Westminster MPs Mr Dennis Canavan (Falkirk West), Mr Ian
Davidson (Govan), Mr Jimmy Wray (Provan), Mr Jimmy Hood (Clydesdale),
and Mr David Marshall (Shettleston).
Other prominent Labour activists behind Mr Falconer, a former Rosyth
shop steward, are Scottish executive members Ms Rosina McCrae, Mr Johann
Lamont, and Mr Archie Graham. Mr Bill Spiers, deputy general secretary
of the STUC, is also associated with the campaign, which is run by Mr
Canavan and the STUC's arts officer, Ms Mary Picken, who is also
chairwoman of Glasgow district Labour Party.
Mr Falconer says this spread of support indicates that most Scots in
the Labour Party want to retain Clause 4. He has accused the senior
Scots on the national executive in London of ignoring opinion at home.
In Strasbourg yesterday, he was unrepentant about his latest attempt
to embarrass the leadership. The advertisement is timed to coincide with
Shadow Social Security Minister Donald Dewar's attendance at a roadshow
meeting tonight in Maryhill, Glasgow.
The meeting is part of Labour's charm offensive to win over activists
angered by Mr Blair's modernisation moves in advance of a special
conference on April 29 to decide on the new aims and objectives of the
party.
Mr Falconer said: ''It was an act of deliberate embarrassment by Mr
Blair to announce major constitutional change of this kind to conference
without any consultation. That would never have been done by John
Smith.''
He said Mr Blair was using Labour members' money to push his message,
and so others were entitled to raise the level of debate by placing
advertisements in newspapers.
Mr Wayne David, EPLP group leader, condemned Mr Falconer's tactics.
''This is no way to conduct sensible politics or a sensible debate,'' he
said.
Mr Jim Devine, Scottish Labour Party chairman, said yesterday that
Cunninghame North MP Brian Wilson's amendment, which will ask the
conference to give its support to an alternative to Clause 4, also
mentioned common ownership ''so it may be that we are getting a meeting
of minds''.
He declined to say whether he thought the advertisement was a
constructive tactic but believed its wording suggested a positive change
in the nature of the debate with a substantial move towards common
ownership.
Commenting on the advertisement, Mr Devine, who is not a member of the
CFS, said: ''People have the right to campaign in whatever way they feel
appropriate and it is up to the individual members to decide whether the
advert is placed on the day of a conference and if this is the correct
use of resources and the correct tactics.''
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson yesterday declined to
comment on the advertisement but a spokesperson said he fully supported
Mr Tony Blair's position and was confident in his prospects of winning
the debate on Clause 4.
A spokesperson said Mr Jack McConnell, secretary of the Scottish
Labour Party, had declined to comment because he is a party official and
''it is not for him to comment''.
</TEXT>
