<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mixed response to Bill on caring for the mentally ill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID,MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW Bill governing the care of the mentally ill in the community in
Scotland received a mixed welcome yesterday.
It is intended to create a legal framework for the care of patients
who no longer require to be detained in hospital but still require
supervision -- a matter of growing concern as long-stay psychiatry beds
are reduced in number.
The proposals are aimed at minimising the risk of patients losing
touch with their clinical carers, and possibly failing to keep taking
the medicine that keeps them well.
The Bill parallels similar measures being introduced in England in
response to recent tragedies, including mentally ill patients who have
killed others or harmed themselves, for example by climbing into the
lions' enclosure at London Zoo.
The most contentious measure in the Mental Health (Patients in the
Community) Bill will put a one-year time limit on Leave of Absence, the
status -- currently open-ended -- attached to patients who come out of
hospital but still need supervision.
After a year, such patients -- there are currently thought to be about
100 in Scotland -- will have to be the subject of an application to a
sheriff for a community care order, if supervision is to be continued.
The Government fears that, in its present form, indefinite leave of
absence could be open to legal challenge.
However, the Mental Welfare Commission believes the existing
legislation could have been amended without limiting Leave of Absence,
and that the new Bill would make matters worse. It fears community
orders will not have enough teeth.
Patients on Leave of Absence were subject to powers to insist on
treatment which were necessary in a small, but important, group of
patients who might lack insight into their illness, remained well on
medication, but relapsed on stopping it, posing a risk to themselves or
others.
''Psychiatric disability does not magically change at the end of one
year,'' said the commission's director, Dr James Dyer.
''There are currently more than a hundred people in Scotland who have
been on Leave of Absence for more than a year, and they are monitored by
us. Under the new proposals such people, who are currently able to get
on with their lives in the community, might be left at one extreme or
the other -- having to be kept in hospital, or left in the community
with inadequate powers to insist on treatment.''
The Scottish Division of the Royal College of Psychiatrists also
regrets the replacement of the current system. ''It offered arrangements
which were not possible in England and Wales,'' said honorary secretary
Dr Ian Pullen.
''Having said that, the proposed Bill is a reasonable attempt to
strike a balance between the needs of patients to receive care and
supervision when they lose insight into their illness, and their basic
human rights,'' he said.
''Some Scottish psychiatrists are concerned that there is not a
provision for treatment in the community -- only supervision -- but the
fact is it isn't really possible to treat someone by force in their own
home. If it comes down to that, they have to be taken back into
hospital.
''The Bill also means that if you want to continue supervision you
have to make out a case to a sheriff, so that you are having a review by
someone from the outside,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government blamed for putting pressure on police to manipulate reports    Crime fall 'bogus' says expert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON,CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR police officers in Scotland are under as much pressure as their
English counterparts to manipulate crime figures downwards, a leading
researcher for the Home Office claimed yesterday.
Professor John Benyon, director of the Centre for the Study of Public
Order, estimates that as many as 43% of reported crimes in England and
Wales are not now recorded.
He alleges that crimes are vanishing from official statistics because
of Whitehall's demands to reduce crime rates and meet performance
targets.
Mr Benyon, of Leicester University, said he had no doubts that
Scotland's eight police forces were now under similar pressure from the
Scottish Office to cut recorded crimes.
He added: ''The Government of law and order, which has presided over
the largest-ever crime rise, is in effect asking the forces of law and
order: 'Who will rid me of this turbulent priest?'
''The same danger must apply in Scotland, for obvious reasons. Police
must be under under pressure to improve crime statistics at a time when
there is talk of performance-related pay.''
Mr Benyon, whose Government researches include how different forces'
process cases, alleged ''a subtle manipulation'' of crime figures had
become prevalent in England and Wales over the past year.
He said Home Office figures for last year showed only 57% of nearly
eight million reported crimes were recorded, with at least 220,000 --
including burglaries, assaults, and car offences -- disappearing from
official statistics in 1993 because of changes to recording procedures.
Mr Benyon cited 10 separate offences -- including theft, criminal
damage, and malicious damage arising from a housebreaking -- being
reduced at a stroke to one recorded crime, breaking and entering.
His example is similar to that given by Grampian Chief Constable Ian
Oliver earlier this week. He said some Scottish forces might record five
car break-ins in a street as one crime while others might record all
five.
A spokesman for Mr Oliver yesterday denied any suggestion of massaged
figures in Scotland, and added: ''That would challenge the integrity of
officers.''
Mr Benyon insisted that political pressure ''to be seen to be doing
something about law and order'' was now a nationwide phenomenon, and
added: ''There is no doubt police are under pressure to reduce recorded
crimes and improve clear-up rates.''
His central allegation -- that recent falls in UK crime levels claimed
by the Government are due to police not recording offences as previously
-- follows criticisms by Opposition MPs about initial crime figures for
1994 released by the Scottish Office.
These show a fall in recorded crime of 3%, the third annual drop in a
row. Mr John McFall, Labour's Scottish Home Affairs spokesman, yesterday
declared the figures ''do not accurately depict the reality of the
situation''. He estimated only one-in-two crimes were reported, and
officers only record 38% of them.
He has trawled Government crime statistics since The Herald report on
Tuesday that violence, vandalism, and car offences are on the rise
despite the overall drop in crime.
The fall is due almost entirely to a 7% reduction in recorded crimes
of dishonesty, including housebreakings, shoplifting, and fraud.
Mr McFall said his research revealed ''a frightening picture'' about
Scottish crime rates. Between 1989 and 1993, robberies rose 26% and car
thefts 47%, and he declared: ''The Government is losing the battle
against drugs.''
Drugs offences have increased by 1056% since the Tories came to power:
1655 were recorded in 1979, but the figure for 1993, the latest
available, was 17,986. The problem was most acute in Lothian and
Borders, up 2184% during the same period.
The Home Office insisted it had not asked any police force to change
the way crimes were recorded, and added: ''There has been no pressure
from us to do so.''
The Scottish Office questioned how it could be accused of trying to
force crime rates down when increases in 1994 were reported in five out
of seven categories. A spokesman said of alleged political pressure to
massage figures: ''We would reject out of hand any suggestion of that
kind.''
The Scottish Police Federation, which represents officers to Chief
Inspector level, said it had no knowledge of figures being manipulated.
If it had, it would be ''saying something about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jones 'bites journalist'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOOTBALLER Vinnie Jones last night looked certain to face action from
the Football Association over an alleged attack on a newspaper reporter
just hours after the mayhem of England's abandoned international match
in Dublin.
The Wales and Wimbledon defender, who arrived in Dublin on Tuesday
afternoon with a group of friends, is alleged to have bitten the nose of
a Daily Mirror news reporter, causing it to bleed.
Mr Mike Parry, FA press officer, who has already made a report of the
matter, said he saw an incident in a bar in Jury's Hotel a few hundred
yards from the city's Lansdowne Road ground.
''I did witness an incident between Vinnie Jones and Ted Oliver, a
reporter on the Mirror,'' said Mr Parry.
''I have compiled a report, which I have sent to my colleagues and
senior executives of the FA at Lancaster Gate.''
An association spokesman said reports of the incident would be
investigated.
Later, the Daily Mirror said in a statement that it had filed a
complaint to the Gardai in Dublin ''following an assault on its reporter
Ted Oliver by footballer Vinnie Jones''.
It said: ''The unprovoked attack against Mr Oliver occurred in a hotel
on Wednesday night while he was talking with an FA official, having just
arrived in Dublin to cover the night's disturbing events.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nitric acid discharged at Dounreay for 10 years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS,HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR the past 10 years radioactive nitric acid has been discharged into
the Pentland Firth by the operators of Dounreay, the Atomic Energy
Authority.
This is in direct contravention of the Control of Pollution Act which
carries a maximum penalty of a #20,000 fine and three months in prison.
The sole public mention of the discharges is a small extract which
appears in the 1993/94 annual report of the Highland River Purification
Board which has just been published.
This considers the plant's other failures to meet consents and then
continues: ''Of a more serious nature is the discovery that AEA is
disposing of large quantities of acid through their main radioactive
outfall. The authority has been advised that neutralisation of the
discharge is required in order to prevent a report being made to the
procurator-fiscal.''
The discharges are highly acidic and capable of dissolving any marine
lifeforms coming into contact with them before they are neutralised by
seawater.
Dounreay uses the acid to dissolve spent nuclear fuel rods containing
uranium and plutonium in its reprocessing complex and has been making
the discharges since reprocessing began over 35 years ago.
The practice only became illegal, however, in 1985 when the Control of
Pollution Act came into force.
This Act required the industry to apply for consents for discharges.
Whoever applied for consents on behalf of Dounreay made no mention of
acids. As a result the plant has been discharging it illegally every day
since.
Dounreay now seems to have only two courses: either to stop
reprocessing; or construct a multi-million pound plant to neutralise the
acid.
Mr Philip Wright, the purification board's divisional inspector in
Thurso, confirmed yesterday that the discarging had only come to the
board's attention in 1993. Discussions were now taking place between the
board, the AEA, and HM Industrial Pollution Inspectorate.
''When application for consent was made there was no mention of acids
or nitrates, only of metals. If they had asked to discharge acids we
would have told them to neutralise them first.
''These discharges are highly acidic with a pH as low as one. You
don't get any lower. The seawater will eventually bring it up to seven,
neutralising it, but if a shellfish, for example, was to come into
contact with the discharge in its raw form, it would just dissolve in a
fizz and disappear.
''If this was in fresh river water it could cause an enormous amount
of damage to the environment. It is illegal and something will have to
be done to resolve it. The penalties are quite serious.''
Mr Wright thought the most likely course was that AEA would install a
neutralising plant but that could bring other problems. Other solids
would be produced, settlement tanks would be required, and then
facilities for the removal of the sludges and their disposal.
He said: ''It is an expensive operation.''
Mr Ian Shepherd, AEA's spokesman at Dounreay, told The Herald
yesterday he could not comment on why permission had not be sought for
the disposal of acid 10 years ago.
''What I can say is that we have been in discussion with the HRPB over
the acidity of our discharges for several years. During these
discussions the HRPB has been kept informed of the discharges and the
programme of action that is designed to produce a neutral discharge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Costs for Japan visit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETAILS of who paid for the recent visit to Japan by the Princess of
Wales were disclosed last night by Junior Foreign Office Minister Tony
Baldry.
He said in a Commons written reply, that the cost -- for which he did
not give a figure -- of the Princess's travel to and from Japan had been
a charge to the Defence Ministry.
The #6568 business class travel costs for ''reconnaissance visits'' by
the Princess's private secretary and a press secretary -- ''necessary
for security and other aspects'' -- had been met by the Foreign Office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bill creates threat to tenants, claims Liddell</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish Homes tenants could have their homes sold over their heads to
''predator'' companies, Labour claimed during a debate on the Finance
Bill in a Commons committee yesterday.
Mrs Helen Liddell, Labour MP for Monklands East, said: ''The scandal
of the sale of Scottish Homes houses opens the way to the exploitation
both of tenants and the public purse.''
Mr Andrew Smith, shadow Chief Secretary, said companies benefiting
from the sales could take advantage of new tax subsidies introduced by
the Bill. He said ''This could make peoples' homes the playthings of the
tax avoidance industry.''
Later, he said Treasury Minister Sir George Young had refused to rule
out the possibility of the subsidies going to property management or
maintenance companies, although he claimed that companies directly
receiving rents would not be able to take advantage of the schemes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Complaints about British Gas soar to record levels</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPLAINTS about British Gas have nearly doubled over the past year
and are now at record levels, a watchdog's report showed yesterday.
The Gas Consumers Council said that between last November and this
month its 12 regional offices dealt with nearly 10,960 complaints -- a
94% increase on the same period last year.
Last month there were 5246 complaints -- a 172% increase on January
1994.
That was the highest monthly figure since British Gas was privatised,
a GCC spokeswoman said. The previous record was 3670 in November 1988.
She said all complaints were ''substantial'' and merited
investigation.
British Gas said it was concerned about the figures but felt
complaints would soon start to fall again.
''This is a temporary reversal of a downward trend in customer
complaints, as we switch people and systems from the old world of
British Gas to the new structure which will be better able to cope with
the demands of business in the future,'' said executive director Norman
Blacker.
British Gas has recently been criticised for the 75% pay increase
given to its chief executive, Mr Cedric Brown.
It also came under fire for cutting showroom services, reducing
spending on safety checks, and shedding around 25,000 jobs.
During last month, GCC staff dealt with 13,737 queries from customers
who could not get an answer when they called British Gas -- an 83%
increase on January last year.
Earlier this year, the GCC said the Government should consider
withdrawing British Gas's Citizen's Charter mark because standards had
slipped so much.
Council officials said the rise in complaints came after British Gas
was reorganised in readiness for the opening up of the domestic gas
market.
Labour's consumer spokesman, Mr Nigel Griffiths, said Mr Brown should
meet Clare Spottiswoode, head of industry regulator, the Office of Gas
Supply, and look at ways of restoring services.
''These figures justify all the concerns Labour has raised in recent
months,'' he said. ''This situation must be addressed immediately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jobs price of cash squeeze on councils</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH,LOCAL GOVERNMENTCORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of local government jobs could be lost if the Government
continues its present squeeze on council finances, Professor Arthur
Midwinter, a leading sociology academic, told a meeting of finance
officials in Glasgow yesterday.
He warned that councils would have to resort more and more to offering
early retirement and redundancy packages to help balance their books.
If there were more cash cutbacks next year, they could be forced to
shed more than the 1800 maximum number of staff forecast to go as a
result of reorganisation.
The professor also told the Scottish Audit Group that, as the move to
a single-tier structure got closer, the flaws in the original diagnosis
became clearer.
He said that reform was more likely to fragment specialist services in
areas such as education than to produce more coherent local government,
and that services by contract would be a poor substitute for direct
local authority provision.
The professor is Dean of the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences at
Strathclyde University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Torture instruments export curb bid fails</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government came under renewed pressure yesterday to prevent the
export of instruments of inhuman treatment and torture, as featured in a
recent television documentary.
However, Trade and Industry Minister of State Earl Ferrers stressed
there were controls in place and accused the makers of the recent
Channel 4 Dispatches programme of having tried ''to entrap people into
saying things''.
The company concerned was the Glasgow firm ICL Plastics, based in
Maryhill. They were the subject of an investigation into the sale of
electro-shock batons.
The issue was raised in the Lords at question time by Labour's Lord
Dubs, the former MP Alf Dubs, who said the programme had found that leg
shackles and electric-shock weapons were being exported.
He quoted a businessman featured in the programme as saying his
company had sold electric-shock weapons ''with the Government's
blessing''.
Earl Ferrers insisted that export licences would not be granted for
leg shackles but he acknowledged it was impossible to control the
possible misuse of some exported goods in other countries. Five-amp
flex, bicycle chains, and cigarettes could all be used as weapons of
torture.
Condemning the Dispatches programme, the Minister said its makers had
gone to three companies to try to entrap them into saying they would be
prepared to make instruments of torture for export -- but all three had
refused.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New ocean survey vessel</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW ocean survey vessel for the Royal Navy is to be named after the
Antarctic explorer Captain Scott, Defence Procurement Minister Roger
Freeman announced yesterday. He told MPs: ''We recognise the importance
of specialist hydrographic vessels and personnel.
''We continue to plan for the upgrading of the capability of the
hydrographic service by procuring four new vessels, including a
new-build ocean survey vessel, an order for which was placed last
month.''
He added: ''We have decided to name the new OSV after the great
Antarctic explorer Scott and of course that vessel will do valuable work
for the hydrographic service.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pensioner's killer gets life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who murdered a pensioner for his bank cash card was jailed for
life at the High Court in Glasgow yesterday.
The court heard than John Docherty, 22, subjected his victim to
horrific violence to get him to divulge his PIN number.
Grandfather John Boyd, 69, was battered with a pair of pruning shears,
stabbed in the chest with a screwdriver, and had his throat knelt on as
he lay on the ground.
Despite his age the retired coal industry manager grappled with his
masked attacker in a fight for his life.
Within a few hours of killing Mr Boyd at his isolated cottage in
Waterside, near Patna, Ayrshire, Docherty was using his cash card to try
to get money from an auto teller in Ayr.
But he could not remember the PIN number given to him by his victim
and after three unsuccessful tries left without a penny.
Docherty, from a caravan site at Dalrymple, Ayrshire, admitted the
murder on October 21 last year.
Lord Kirkwood jailed him for life.
Earlier, Mr Colin Boyd, prosecuting, told how Mr Boyd's body was
discovered after his son could not get in touch with him and alerted
neighbours.
They found him in a kitchen/washhouse area lying on his back.
When Docherty was arrested six days later he at first denied being in
Patna at the time of the murder but eventually admitted the killing.
He told police that when the Mr Boyd ran towards him he stuck the
screwdriver in his ribs, and told him he wanted money.
Docherty said after he got Mr Boyd's cash card and asked him for the
number he did not remember very much except for attacking him with
shears.
Police found Mr Boyd's cash card in four pieces in a communal bin at
the caravan site where Docherty lived.
Yesterday Mr Boyd's son Allan, 36, sat in court with his wife Kathryn
to watch Docherty being jailed.
As he walked from court he said: ''The way my father died was
horrific. He must have been tortured for his bank card PIN number.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major asked to apologise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNP leader Alex Salmond yesterday accused John Major and Tony Blair of
scoring an own goal by using the term British instead of English when
referring to the football hooligans who forced the abandonment of the
friendly in Dublin.
In a letter to the Irish Taoiseach, Mr John Burton, Mr Major said the
actions of those who had caused the trouble did ''not reflect the true
face of Britain or of British football'' while Mr Blair had talked about
idiots who had brought ''shame on Britain and contempt on themselves''.
Mr Salmond said the Prime Minister and the leader of the Opposition
should apologise to the Scottish football authorities for their misuse
of the term British.
He said: ''Like all of Scotland I have the utmost sympathy with the
people of Dublin for the ordeal which they were forced to suffer at the
hands of a band of neo-Nazi thugs.
''And -- to paraphrase John Major -- while those thugs are in no way a
true reflection of the people of England or English sports fans, they
are certainly not representative of Scottish fans, or indeed the Welsh
or Northern Irish.''
</TEXT>
