<DOCNO>GH950217-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wife tells court of 'cash in wardrobe' Banker 'loved his job' until three years ago when his health broke down under strain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BANK manager's wife told the High Court in Glasgow yesterday how
#11,000 in old notes were allegedly found in a wardrobe after her
father-in-law died.
Mrs Ann MacGillivray, 40, claimed she heard her husband gasp from
another room: ''Oh, Ann. Come here.''
She said: ''I thought he had found medals his master-baker father had
won for his black bun.''
However, she told the court it was ''more than #10,000'' in used
notes.
Her husband, Hector, 54, denies embezzling #163,000 of soiled notes
over 20 years at the Clydesdale Bank in Glasgow instead of incinerating
them.
Mrs MacGillivray claimed her husband found the money as they cleared
out his father's house in Rothesay on the Isle of Bute in l979.
She told Lord Prosser: ''I told him, 'Take this away from me'. I had
never seen so much money since I worked in the bank.
''He said there must have been at least #10,000 and I told him to deal
with it as it was a lot of money.
''We took it home to Bearsden and I thought he may have put in in a
building society.''
Mr MacGillivray has claimed he kept the money, #11,000, for 13 years
in the back of his own wardrobe before depositing various amounts in
society accounts from Glasgow to the Channel Isles.
Mrs MacGillivray, who met her husband in the bank after he divorced
his first wife, claimed her late father-in-law told her he would leave
money to her children. She claimed: ''He left it, but not in the normal
way.''
She also claimed she kept money left over from her weekly housekeeping
allowance from her husband's #11,000-a-year job in a bedroom drawer.
They both used this money, she claimed, for running expenses and her
husband rarely used a cash dispenser.
She said: ''If he needed cash for a weekly rail ticket to get to work
or for his bowling club, he took it from the drawer.''
Mrs MacGillivray said her husband ''loved his job'' until three years
ago when his health broke down under the strain of an extra work-load.
He became unhappy and she sometimes found him sitting crying.
After #43,000 vanished from the bank he was worried about the way
staff were being questioned, she said.
She added: ''Even some of the men were in tears. I told him not be be
bullied by them.''
Her husband ''shocked'' police with his sudden confession to stealing
up to #600 a week in old notes, the court heard.
However, Mrs MacGillivray claimed: ''He was mentally ill. He would
have confessed to being Jack the Ripper if they had asked him.''
She told the court he later felt he had ruined his family by making a
false confession, but she added: ''I told him we should fight it.''
Days after being charged with embezzlement and ordered out of the
bank, her husband returned home from a pub. She told the court: ''He
crawled under the dining room table and lay crying for his mummy and
said she would tell them he had not taken any money.''
A doctor was summoned and her husband was strapped into a chair by
ambulancemen and carried out of their bungalow.
He lost his memory and spent three months in a psychiatric ward of
Gartnavel Royal Hospital.
His first memory to return, she claimed, was of a fish-and-chip shop
at Bearsden.
She said: ''He did not know me and I took photographs of our wedding
and of our two sons. I know he never took any money from the bank.''
She said her husband sometimes travelled between Glasgow, Edinburgh,
Aberdeen, and the Royal Mint in London.
She told the court: ''He dealt with the Mint and he saved the bank
millions of pounds.''
Bank staff claimed Mr MacGillivray was seen pocketing money and that
notes marked for burning re-appeared back in circulation.
When they complained, they were told there was ''nothing sinister''
and to get on with their work.
When bundles of bank notes which had been weighed before burning
showed up short Mr MacGillivray ordered his staff to ignore it.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
