<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Face cream withdrawn from sale after eye scare</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENS of thousands of pots of face cream were last night being taken
off shelves after an eye scare.
Sales of Oil of Ulay New Skin Discovery and Max Factor Active Response
Cream were suspended after dozens of women reported problems.
A few had suffered blurred vision, others complained that the creams
were making their eyes tingle and water, said maker Procter &amp; Gamble.
Around two million women use the creams, which were launched last
year, said the American soap and cosmetics giant.
A Procter &amp; Gamble spokeswoman said no-one had suffered ''serious or
lasting damage''.
She said the creams were safe if women did not use them near their
eyes. Sales were being suspended as a precaution.
Company scientists think the problem is being caused by the mixture of
chemicals in the creams. They are now looking at ways of changing the
formula.
Procter &amp; Gamble said the problem arose before Christmas and the firm
had attempted to solve it by sticking a label on pots, warning women not
to rub the cream near their eyes.
''We thought a warning label would prevent such problems, but it
hasn't,'' said Ceil Kuzma, vice president of research and development
for skincare products.
''So we're withdrawing these two products until we can invent milder
versions that can be used near the eyes.''
She added: ''We regret any discomfort these products may have caused
for any of our users.''
The spokeswoman would not say how much the withdrawal would cost P &amp;
G, although she said it would not be a huge amount because the creams
were ''niche'' products aimed at women ''over 30''.
P &amp; G said it was also withdrawing similar creams in the US and
Canada.
The creams are hydroxy acid-based products. Their main ingredient is
salicylic acid, which comes from willow bark.
</TEXT>
