<HEADLINE>Officials trying to trace infection in water</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH officials in Grampian are looking for the source of an
animal-based infection which could be running through the public water
supply, and has so far affected 32 people.
The symptoms are severe vomiting and diarrhoea. One woman in her
thirties had to be taken to hospital yesterday with acute dehydration.
It is not known how many children are affected, although Moray
District Council's director of environmental health, Mr Gilbert
Robertson, has revealed that there are now 10 cases outside Elgin town
centre, where the bulk of sufferers live.
All victims live or work in the town, and environmental health
officials confirmed yesterday that the problem had been around for two
weeks. But Mr Robertson said: ''There is no cause for alarm.
''We have identified all the cases, and isolated one supply source.
All others have proved negative in testing.''
Mr Robertson admitted, however, that they did not know where the
bacteria ''crypto sporidium'' was coming from. ''It is from animal
faeces and very difficult to trace,'' he added.
The director said everything that could be done was being done by his
own authority, Grampian Health Board, and Grampian water services
department.
The bacteria has an incubation period of between 12-14 days.
He said tests were continuing, but admitted that there could be more
victims.
''We do not want to cause a public scare by advising people to boil
water before drinking. This kind of infection does not automatically
attack everyone. It depends upon the health of the individual and his or
her immune system. Admittedly though, children could be at greater
risk,'' Mr Robertson said.
Dr John Curnow, consultant in communicable diseases at Grampian Health
Board, said: ''Anyone suffering from prolonged sickness should contact
their GP.''
</TEXT>
