<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScotRail can't afford to lose champion on the right track</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG,ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THANKS to a public address system chewing up speech like a demented
station Tannoy, the words spoken at Tuesday night's formal ScotRail
farewell to Sir Bob Reid were largely lost on me.
As the main hall in Kelvingrove Art Gallery echoed incoherently, I did
make out the departing British Rail chairman telling us that this had
been the best job, bar none, he had ever had. The words of the other
main speaker, ScotRail director Chris Green, had all meaning sucked from
them.
The man himself looked grey and seemed distracted. Even Sir Bob's
affectionate praise drew scarce a smile. No surprise, perhaps. Green's
at-times outspoken criticisms of rail privatisation, from someone who
has devoted his entire professional life to the industry, must have
placed him under intense personal pressure.
When he warned, in a Herald interview on January 12, of a rundown
Scottish railway if proposed budget cuts went through, he was ordered to
London by air the next day to face the music. Iain Wilson's article was,
I am told, minutely dissected, every direct quote examined to see just
how far over the mark Green might have stepped.
He emerged, apparently, on a last warning not to rock the boat. And
now he's going. Has he had a better offer? Or is this a professional
railwayman of impeccable credentials quitting because he can no longer
stomach the butchery of an industry he loves, for ideological ends?
He is turning his back, remember, on the opportunity to bid to lead a
sizeable Scottish business into the private sector. ScotRail operates
more than 95% of all rail services in Scotland, has a turnover of some
#300m (half of it from fares, half from grant support), and employs 4100
people.
It runs 1900 services a day, carrys 170,000 passengers daily, and
through its franchised on-train catering operation sells more than a
million cups of tea and coffee a year.
Green who, after his earlier period as general manager of ScotRail
between 1984 and 1986, went on to run Network SouthEast and InterCity,
could probably have had his pick of bigger plums on the rail
privatisation menu. He choose to come back north.
The plan to break the monolithic British Rail into nearly 100 pieces,
25 of them train operating companies, turns the likes of ScotRail into
businesses which need a much stronger customer focus. That attracted
Green. As he told a conference last November: ''The dynamics of this
relationship make railways one of the most complex and challenging
service providers to manage with excellence.''
That was precisely the kind of challenge which ignited the man.
ScotRail brought him back to a territory where, thanks to nearly 50 new
station openings in 10 years, much of it in collaboration with the
Strathclyde Passenger Transport Executive, rail was arguably enjoying
something of a renaissance.
But increasingly, as the implications of the 1993 Railways Act spilled
out, he could not hide his frustration. Rooms filled up with the new
legal contracts needed to govern relationships between the myriad
operating companies. As the lawyers grew fat on fee notes, Green and his
colleagues had to cope with the consequences.
His going leaves ScotRail rudderless. It also pokes an enormous hole
in the credibility of a policy which has few friends outwith Government
and its City advisers, including those lawyers piling contract upon
contract. If the privatisation timetable survives, Green's departure may
increase the likelihood of ScotRail going to a commercial bidder. But
even there enthusiasm is cooling.
Chris Green became a thorn in the side of successive Transport
Ministers. The current incumbent, Dr Mawhinney, seems a reasonable man.
He should reflect long and hard on a privatisation plan which prompts as
committed and professional a railman as Chris Green to quit the scene.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man who saw the danger signals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON,CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRIS Green's 10-year, on-off love affair with ScotRail is over. The
departure is bitter-sweet, coming after the five most torrid weeks of
his lifetime in the railways, both north and south of the Border.
The disenchantment was signalled in a recent exclusive interview in
The Herald about ScotRail's fate leading up to privatisation. It turned
out to be his swansong.
Mr Green's position as director was probably untenable after
extraordinary attacks on Government cost-cutting targets in the run-up
to privatisation.
He was summoned to London by the British Rail board to explain the
outburst in print which, in reality, was a calm but bleak assessment of
ScotRail's fate leading up to privatisation.
Mr Green was then told not to comment unless it would benefit the
railways and the sell-off process. That was never his way, which makes
his sudden departure all the more poignant -- and odd.
Perhaps he has realised that his promise to renew pride in the network
could not be met. Instead of expansion, he faced cuts of at least 5%
from April -- with more to follow.
The Government has ignored at its peril his warnings that a compromise
on financial support for the railways had to be reached. Mr Green
clearly wants no part of a future in which the money to keep ScotRail in
business at current levels is not forthcoming.
He wanted a future of expansion and quality services. His departure
suggests the rearguard action against cost-cutting targets has been
lost. It also suggests cuts loom on a scale not seen since Beeching --
and that his battles to preserve Scottish sleepers and Motorail are
doomed.
In the earlier interview, Mr Green said he was expected to get through
1995 with ''a near impossible target''.
He said the Government would get ''the cheapest railway, not the
best'', if the financial crisis were not relieved -- and if ScotRail had
to run services ''at minimum cost and without investment''.
However, his message on behalf of ScotRail, the preferred bidder for
the train operating franchise, went much further -- and probably sealed
his fate.
He said there was no escaping the harsh reality that ''a better
railway can be achieved only by higher levels of subsidy'', and went on:
''We have to make more savage cuts than anticipated. We are willing and
able to fund productivity, but not in a position to do so. That cannot
possibly sit with the policy of developing and expanding the railway.''
His statements were pored over by his London-based bosses, who face
pressure from the Government to talk up the privatisation process.
Mr Green, 52, the former general manager of ScotRail, returned north
in January last year to lead the network through the perils of
privatisation into a bright future of expansion.
But his support for privatisation has always been lukewarm.
That support turned to ice as the grim realities behind the break-up
of railways became clear.
He had little or no control, and the lack of power was hard for the
man who had launched Network SouthEast and headed InterCity.
Born in 1943, educated at Oxford, and a BR management trainee in 1965,
he has been a railway man all his life.
In 1980 he came to Scotland as chief operating manager, rising to be
general manager from 1984 to 1986.
His supporters look back on these years with ill-concealed nostalgia.
He pioneered customer innovations and took pleasure in using his
distance from headquarters in London to push through initiatives.
His enthusiasm for one of Scotland's largest businesses is undeniable.
But his frustration at running trains on a network over which he had no
control -- and no real hope of making a profit -- was also plain to see.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whitelaw protests over loss of sleeper</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VISCOUNT Whitelaw -- a deputy Prime Minister under Mrs Thatcher -- has
joined the protests over the loss of Motorail and sleeper services.
He has written to the Rail Users Consultative Committee to complain at
the decision, announced in December, not to include Motorail and the
Fort William and Carlisle sleeper services in minimum requirements under
privatisation.
Lord Whitelaw was also said to be ''extremely angry'' after Transport
Minister John Watt cancelled a meeting with MPs and peers on the west
coast main line upgrade.
Yesterday a delegation of Liberal Democrat MPs met with the users
committee chairman, Major General Lennox Napier, to discuss the campaign
to save the services. He told them the committee had written to the Rail
Regulator, John Swift QC, demanding full consultation on the services.
Mr Charles Kennedy, MP for Ross, Cromarty and Skye, said: ''As and
when we secure consultation it will enable us to move on to the next
stage of the campaign -- preparing as powerful a case as possible for
retention and development of these services.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScotRail forces new union head to quit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS,INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTRAIL has forced the newly elected Scottish official of the
locomen's union Aslef to resign from the industry, breaking railway
tradition and endangering relationships with the rail unions.
Traditionally, locomen who take up union office have been seconded to
the union and BR has guaranteed them a job and protected their seniority
should they want or need to return to rail work.
In practice few did, and most loco drivers who took up full-time union
office tended to stay with the union, although union posts have become
more precarious since Tory labour laws have demanded they submit
themselves for re-election every five years.
But with privatisation looming, ScotRail clearly does not see
guaranteeing jobs for union officials as a very attractive proposition
for prospective buyers, and has taken the opportunity of Mr Pat
O'Connor's elevation, from driver at Yoker depot to Scottish district
secretary, to break the traditional commitment.
ScotRail confirmed that Mr O'Connor, who this week succeeded retiring
Mr Willie Wilkie for an initial three-year term of office, was obliged
to sever his connections with the industry in line with a policy change
decided at BR board level last April, as part of the pre-privatisation
moves which reflect the ''new environment''.
Aslef, which has nine other full-time officials, including general
secretary Mr Lew Adams, fears this move will be followed by other shadow
franchises as Aslef officials on their ''books'' come up for
re-election.
The union is also worried that members might be discouraged from
taking up union office.
Officials of the Rail, Maritime and Transport Union already quit their
rail jobs on assuming union office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScotRail director quits    Frustration over budget cuts leads to resignation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN,POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>RAIL ISSUE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979812643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR CHRIS Green has resigned as director of ScotRail, less than a year
after agreeing to lead the privatisation of the railways in Scotland.
His departure, effective at the end of the month, will be announced
today.
Rumours about it have been circulating for several weeks. Last month
Mr Green made clear his frustrations, as he warned that ScotRail faced
being run down because of Government demands for budget cuts.
His decision is a devastating blow for the Government, which had
counted on him to make privatisation north of the Border a success. The
news has also shocked his many supporters in the railways.
It is understood that Mr Green, who is on holiday, is leaving the
railway industry altogether to take up a post in England. The decision,
said to have been a difficult one, was taken for personal reasons.
ScotRail, however, neither confirmed nor denied that Mr Green is to
resign. A spokesman said last night: ''There seems to be a rumour
circulating that Chris Green will leave ScotRail at the end of the
month. If that is true it must be an absolutely marvellous job to induce
Mr Green away from an industry in which he has had such an outstanding
career for the last 30 years.''
News of his departure has stunned the Department of Transport. When Mr
Green was appointed to ScotRail in 1993, Ministers were at pains to
highlight ScotRail as one of privatisation's flagship franchises, which
would be the first to be sold off.
Last night the Government's disappointment was barely concealed. A
source said: ''If he is going to make any change, that is a matter for
him. If he has chosen to leave then good luck to him.''
When he took up the post in April last year Mr Green put in place a
high-powered team to prepare a management buy-out bid. As recently as
last week, with growing signs that the sell-off of ScotRail has
encountered severe difficulties, directors were still insisting that a
management bid would be submitted.
Last night Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's acting transport spokesman,
expressed shock at the loss of a ''man of integrity''. He said: ''This
is the ultimate indictement of the pure folly of what the Treasury are
doing to our railway network.
''Chris Green turned InterCity into a profitable and respected
business. Then he had to watch as the whole thing was dismembered for no
reason other than political spite.
''He is a man of integrity who is walking away from an industry he has
given his life to and which desperately needs people of his calibre in
its darkest hour.''
At 52 Mr Green, an Oxford graduate, is one of the railway's
high-fliers. After leaving Scotland as general manager of the Scottish
region in 1986, he was subsequently director of Network Southeast and
InterCity.
When the Government decided, against his wishes, to split up InterCity
prior to privatisation, Mr Green faced losing his job. His appointment
to head ScotRail was interpreted as a vote of confidence in ScotRail's
chances under privatisation.
But the optimism of eighteen months ago has been replaced with
confusion, amid evidence that the sale of ScotRail is going ''seriously
wrong''. The network was due to pass into private hands a year ago, but
the timetable, which few believe will be met, has since been put back,
with the earliest possible sale date in 1996.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unionist warning forces rethink</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A THUNDERING letter from Ulster Unionists to the Prime Minister
stalled a Cabinet decision on the future of Northern Ireland yesterday.
The next London/Dublin peace initiative is now being rethought, writes
Geoffrey Parkhouse.
The Northern Ireland Secretary, Sir Patrick Mayhew, arranged for
another meeting with Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring tomorrow to try
again to iron out the difficulties of a joint document designed to point
the way for negotiations between the Ulster Unionists, Sinn Fein, and
the SDLP.
The Unionists' letter warns the Cabinet of bleak consequences for this
initiative if there is any suggestion of cross-border joint authorities.
Signed by three of Mr Jim Molyneaux's colleagues, it also complains
that the Irish nationalists are being kept better informed by the
British Government than they are.
There was hope that London and Dublin could produce their joint
document next Wednesday, but after the Unionists' stance the Cabinet is
expected to need another discussion next Thursday.
The Irish Prime Minister, Mr John Bruton, in an attempt to calm the
situation, told the Senate in Dublin yesterday: ''The document should be
viewed as a facilitator to dialogue and not a political settlement in
itself.
''The final outcome of the dialogue will be put to referendum and the
principles of political agreement and popular consent will apply.''
He claimed that agreement on the document was very close.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950217-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950217-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950217</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gays in push to lower age of consent to 16</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812645</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GAY rights' group, Stonewall, is planning a campaign to lower the
homosexual age of consent in Scotland to 16. It sees the Criminal
Justice (Scotland) Bill as a perfect opportunity to try to change the
law, and is actively lobbying MPs for the change.
The move by Stonewall coincides almost exactly with the anniversary of
last year's change to the law, which saw the age of consent equalised at
18. Previously, Scotland had an age of consent of 18, while in the rest
of the country the age threshold was 21.
Stonewall's point is that if Scotland was out of line before, there is
no reason why it should not be so again, and that a move to 16 in
Scotland may force the Government to lower the age of consent in the
rest of the country.
The Scottish Criminal Justice Bill already has been through the Lords,
and comes to the Commons for its second reading on February 27. It will
go through second reading without any problems, but the moves on gay
rights are set to come to the fore when the Bill enters its committee
stage, probably early next month.
The gay rights' lobby still is trying to find a form of words which
will cover what it is seeking to do, and needs sympathetic MPs to argue
its corner.
A Stonewall spokesman said yesterday: ''We will be tabling an
amendment but we have not done it yet. Sixteen is fair and workable.
When you criminalise a small section of society they do not get the help
and support they need.''
The attempt to reduce the age of consent to 16 was defeated last year
by 307 votes to 280, a majority of 27, but the reduction to 18 went
through by a huge majority of 427 to 162, a majority of 265.
The vote was marked by furious demonstrations by gay rights' activists
outside the Commons, and a similar protest to mark the anniversary of
the occasion is planned for next week.
Labour and the Liberal Democrats are broadly sympathetic to the gay
activists' cause, but are taking a ''wait-and-see approach''. Labour's
spokesman, Dumbarton MP John McFall, said last night: ''Obviously we
will consider any representations made to us and try to formulate an
opinion. Given the different provisions that would exist in England and
Wales it could present certain problems, and it is important to achieve
the right balance.''
For the Liberal Democrats, the Roxburgh and Berwickshire MP, Mr Archy
Kirkwood, said: ''We would not discourage them, but we would have to
look at anything they came up with in that direction. We would be
willing to discuss this further with them, but let's wait and see.''
The Government took a hard line. A Scottish Office spokesman said:
''When the law was changed the last time it brought everyone into line,
but Ministers are not very keen on an amendment that separates us
again.''
While the last vote had been a free vote, it was made clear that this
may not be the case if the gay activists brought forward their proposals
under the current Bill.
</TEXT>
