<HEADLINE>Major tries to 'gag' Cabinet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE,POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812646</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister claimed in the Commons yesterday he had
''reinforced'' Cabinet unity on Europe, after a 15-minute discussion in
which he told his colleagues to keep their doubts to themselves.
Mr Major told Ministers during yesterday's Cabinet meeting that if
they wanted to disagree with the policy he had set out they should do so
in the privacy of Cabinet committee meetings. In public comments they
should stick closely to settled policy -- and Ministers should not be
drawn into other speculative debate.
A series of Ministers then supported this view -- but some of them
made it clear that their doubts about a single currency and further
political union will not go away.
This was agreed as vital to avoiding further public embarrassments
over the clash of opinion among Cabinet Ministers over Britain's future
direction in Europe.
If a Cabinet Minister now breaks ranks after the Prime Minister's
stern move yesterday a resignation may have to be called for. Mr Major's
authority has been severely undermined by public squabbling.
Afterwards No 10 claimed that nobody demurred at the meeting and that
the Prime Minister had the fullest confidence in his Chancellor, Mr
Kenneth Clarke, and his other colleagues.
But profound divisions continue, particularly over the crucial issue
of whether a European single currency and central bank has serious
constitutional implications for the UK. The Chancellor said last week in
a public speech that it did not. He was immediately contradicted by
Welsh Secretary John Redwood who said that it did.
In the Commons the Labour leader, Mr Tony Blair, mocked the Prime
Minister: ''This is your Chancellor -- he has said in clear terms that a
single currency is not a threat to the nation state. Do you agree or
not?'' The Prime Minister dodged the question, pointing to divisions
within the Labour Party on this issue.
Tory back benchers are in a state of despair about the position which
many, on both sides of the argument about a single currency, believe is
being handled badly. The Prime Minister's ''gagging'' attempt yesterday
may be too late to repair his position.
</TEXT>
