<HEADLINE>England in the mood to thwart the thugs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979812647</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN inquiry is getting under way into how a small group of thugs
managed to wreck England's friendly football international against
Ireland.
Last night, politicians on both sides of the Irish Sea were demanding
to know how the ringleaders -- apparently right-wing extremists -- were
able to get tickets for Wednesday's match.
Despite universal condemnation of the scenes, which forced the Dutch
referee to abandon the game and led to dozens of arrests and injuries,
there was also widespread determination that the hooligans should not be
allowed to wreck England's plans to hold the 1996 European Championship
finals.
The Football Association received international support to remain as
host of the event, which is set to attract thousands of European fans to
the UK.
Prime Minister John Major and Mr Joao Havalange, president of
football's world governing body FIFA, united in backing the FA message
of no surrender to the troublemakers.
Nearly 30 English fans appeared before Dublin District Court yesterday
on charges connected with Wednesday's violence.
They all faced charges brought under Ireland's public order law,
including assault and breach of the peace.
Six were remanded in custody, the rest released and ordered to leave
the country.
The key question to be answered by the inquiry into the disturbances
at the Lansdowne Road stadium is: how did so many hooligans get tickets
in the first place?
Former Irish Cabinet Minister Bertie Ahern, leader of the Fianna Fail
opposition party, said it was ''clearly known'' that about 50 English
Nazi sympathisers were in the ground.
Mr Pat Smith, deputy chief executive of the English FA and the woman
in charge of ticketing, said the FA would examine whether there was a
failure in its own checks when distributing tickets to travelling fans.
Irish police admitted yesterday that they had received advance
intelligence about troublemakers attending the game.
But the Garda Siochana said the ''regrettable events'' had taken place
despite extensive preparatory work on their part.
The FA appealed for help from ''genuine'' fans to reveal the identity
of those responsible for the outrage.
MrDavid Davies, the FA's director of public affairs, said the FA was
heartened by the backing it received yesterday for continuing with plans
for next year's tournament.
''We've been in touch with UEFA (European football's governing body)
and FIFA and have been gratified by the widespread support for our view
that Euro '96 should and must go ahead.
''We understand the view of those who say the championships should not
go ahead, but who would have won then -- a tiny percentage of mindless
thugs, or more than a million genuine fans who want to have the
footballing experience of a lifetime?''
Although Mr Havalange backed England to retain the championships, UEFA
will not make a final decision until it has received reports from both
the FA and the Football Association of Ireland.
Mr Davies said: ''We are making a major effort to identify those at
the heart of the trouble. Many of them were recognisable from newspaper
photographs or television stills.''
The FA set up a freephone number, and Mr Davies said: ''We urge true
football supporters to ring 0800-515495 if they can help.
''We will be asking every club involved in the FA Cup fifth round to
repeat this appeal, and we trust the law will be used to its limits to
punish those involved last night.''
In the Commons yesterday, Mr Major condemned those involved in the
trouble.
</TEXT>
